><name>Vaile, M.A.J.</name><name>Vale, D.S.</name><name>Vasta, R.</name><name>Wakelin, B.H.</name><name>Washer, M.J.</name><name>Windsor, A.H.C.</name><name>Wood, J.</name></names></ayes><noes><num.votes>50</num.votes><title>NOES</title><names><name>Adams, D.G.H.</name><name>Albanese, A.N.</name><name>Beazley, K.C.</name><name>Bevis, A.R.</name><name>Bird, S.</name><name>Burke, A.E.</name><name>Burke, A.S.</name><name>Byrne, A.M.</name><name>Corcoran, A.K.</name><name>Crean, S.F.</name><name>Danby, M. *</name><name>Elliot, J.</name><name>Ellis, A.L.</name><name>Ellis, K.</name><name>Emerson, C.A.</name><name>Ferguson, L.D.T.</name><name>Ferguson, M.J.</name><name>Fitzgibbon, J.A.</name><name>Garrett, P.</name><name>Georganas, S.</name><name>George, J.</name><name>Gibbons, S.W.</name><name>Gillard, J.E.</name><name>Grierson, S.J.</name><name>Griffin, A.P.</name><name>Hall, J.G. *</name><name>Hatton, M.J.</name><name>Irwin, J.</name><name>Jenkins, H.A.</name><name>Kerr, D.J.C.</name><name>King, C.F.</name><name>Lawrence, C.M.</name><name>Livermore, K.F.</name><name>McClelland, R.B.</name><name>McMullan, R.F.</name><name>Melham, D.</name><name>Murphy, J. P.</name><name>O'Connor, B.P.</name><name>Owens, J.</name><name>Price, L.R.S.</name><name>Quick, H.V.</name><name>Ripoll, B.F.</name><name>Roxon, N.L.</name><name>Rudd, K.M.</name><name>Sawford, R.W.</name><name>Smith, S.F.</name><name>Snowdon, W.E.</name><name>Tanner, L.</name><name>Thomson, K.J.</name><name>Wilkie, K.</name></names></noes></division.data><division.result><para>Question agreed to.</para></division.result></division><para>Bill, as amended, agreed to.</para></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Third Reading</title><page.no>48</page.no></subdebateinfo><para>Mr RUDDOCK (Berowra—Attorney-General) (12.26 p.m.)—by leave—I move:</para><motion><para>That this bill be now read a third time.</para></motion><para>Question agreed to.</para><para>Bill read a third time.</para></subdebate.1></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>DISABILITY DISCRIMINATION AMENDMENT (EDUCATION STANDARDS) BILL 2004</title><type>Bills</type><page.no>48</page.no><id.no>R2209</id.no></debateinfo><para>Debate resumed from 9 February.</para><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Second Reading</title><page.no>48</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>12:27:00</time.stamp><page.no>48</page.no><name role="metadata">Ruddock, Philip, MP</name><name role="display">Mr RUDDOCK</name><name.id>0J4</name.id><electorate>Berowra</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Attorney-General</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I move:</para></talk.start><motion><para>That this bill be now read a second time.</para></motion><para>This <inline ref="R2209">bill </inline>is an important precursor to the formulation of disability standards for the education of people with disabilities.</para><para>The Disability Discrimination Act 1992 provides that the Attorney-General may formulate disability standards in a range of areas, including the education of persons with a disability.</para><para>Draft disability standards for education have been developed over many years.</para><para>Their development has involved extensive consultation with government and non-government education providers, the disability sector and other interested members of the public.</para><para>In June 2004 the government released for public information a final draft of the standards, along with accompanying guidance notes to assist in their interpretation.</para><para>The draft standards differ from the operation of the act in minor ways. Therefore, it is necessary to make minor amendments to the act to ensure that the standards are supported to the greatest possible extent.</para><para>One amendment is to extend the defence of `unjustifiable hardship' to aspects of education beyond the point of enrolment. The others are to introduce a new definition of `education provider' and to clarify the position with respect to `reasonable adjustments' and the harassment and victimisation of students with disabilities.</para><para>When implemented, the draft disability standards for education will specify how education and training are to be made more accessible to students and prospective students with disabilities, without imposing unduly onerous burdens on education providers. They will clearly describe the obligations of education providers in relation to students with disabilities and provide guidance on how to meet those obligations.</para><para>The standards will cover government and non-government providers in all sectors: pre-school, school, vocational education and training, higher education, and adult and community education.</para><para>The Productivity Commission's recent review of the Disability Discrimination Act identified `exclusion from, and segregation in, education' as `one of the most serious forms of disability discrimination'.</para><para>Disability discrimination in education can manifest itself in many ways, including refusal of enrolment, exclusion from sports or other activities, negative attitudes and unsuitable or inflexible criteria.</para><para>This bill will amend the Disability Discrimination Act to make it clear that disability standards may require education providers to make reasonable adjustments to avoid discriminating on the ground of disability in relation to education and training.</para><para>What is a `reasonable adjustment' will depend on the circumstances of the individual case, but may involve something as simple as allowing a student additional time to complete a test, or supporting the use of assistive computer technology.</para><para>Education providers will not be required to make adjustments for students with disabilities if making those adjustments would cause them unjustifiable hardship.</para><para>The Productivity Commission's review of the Disability Discrimination Act also noted that the absence of an unjustifiable hardship defence after the point of enrolment has created problems for educational institutions. It may be inadvertently aggravating discrimination by being a disincentive to providers to enrol students with disabilities.</para><para>The government considers that more inclusive education and training can play a significant role in changing broader community attitudes about people with disabilities, and will play a crucial part in preparing people for participating more fully in the work force.</para><para>Passing this bill is the next step in ensuring that outcome. I present the explanatory memorandum.</para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>12:30:00</time.stamp><page.no>49</page.no><name role="metadata">Roxon, Nicola, MP</name><name role="display">Ms ROXON</name><name.id>83K</name.id><electorate>Gellibrand</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—As the Attorney-General has set out in his second reading speech, the <inline ref="R2209">Disability Discrimination Amendment (Education Standards) Bill 2004</inline> amends the Disability Discrimination Act 1992 to ensure that provisions of the draft disability standards for education are fully supported by the act. Labor strongly supports the passage of the bill; the implementation of education standards pursuant to the Disability Discrimination Act is long overdue. It is an important step, and one which we had all hoped would have been taken long before now. In fact, this process began in the years of the Keating government—which demonstrates how drawn out the process has been and probably how complicated many of the issues are. </para></talk.start><para>We remain concerned, however, that the government has not looked at how the implementation of the standards can be funded. We dispute the fact that this bill will not result in any extra cost, and strongly believe that the Commonwealth government should put its money where its mouth is to support the important aims of the act and the introduction of the education standards to improve the position of, and opportunities for, disabled people in education and training.</para><para>The government has released a final draft of the standards, which are intended to clarify and elaborate upon the obligations of education and training providers in relation to students with disabilities. The standards will be tabled in parliament some time following the passage of this bill. The bill amends the act to support the draft education standards by: introducing and defining the term `education provider', providing that it is unlawful for education providers to discriminate on the ground of disability in the development or accreditation of curricula or training courses, providing that education providers may be required to develop strategies and programs to prevent the harassment and victimisation of students with disabilities, extending the defence of unjustifiable hardship in education to post-enrolment situations, and clarifying that disability standards made under section 31 may require reasonable adjustments to be made in order to avoid unlawful discrimination on the ground of disability.</para><para>Section 31 of the Disability Discrimination Act provides that the Attorney-General may formulate standards in relation to a number of areas covered by the DDA, including education of people with a disability. As I said at the start, work on these standards has been under way since 1995, with the Ministerial Council on Education, Employment, Training and Youth Affairs being involved in two consultation processes with relevant stakeholders in 1997 and 2000. There is strong support in the disability sector for the standards to be introduced, to help address access issues for students with a disability and remove barriers to their full inclusion in the education environment.</para><para>The education standards must be implemented as quickly as possible to ensure access for students with a disability, but this will not be without significant cost. We strongly support the bill but I would like to place on the record our concern at the lack of consultation with the states, which will have the major responsibility for bringing education facilities up to standard. Our concern is not with the lack of consultation over the standards themselves but with the lack of consultation on their implementation and the cost of that implementation.</para><para>In the most recent Senate inquiry into this bill, several states made submissions contesting the Commonwealth government's view that there will be no financial impact upon the passage of the legislation and the introduction of the standards. We are therefore greatly concerned at the fact that the costs will fall heavily on the states—and the failure of the Commonwealth government to make a contribution is a significant issue.</para><para>In 2003, all state and territory members of the Ministerial Council on Education, Employment, Training and Youth Affairs—except for Tasmania and the ACT—voted against the Commonwealth's move to introduce the standards. While they agree with the content and intent, the states and territories were not prepared to move forward unless the Commonwealth agreed to share the costs of implementation—which it is considered will be significant—and a phase-in of the standards.</para><para>The Commonwealth has moved unilaterally to have this bill passed and the standards introduced. There is strong support from education authorities and disability groups for the principles behind the bill. However several states are arguing that the cost implications are likely to be significant, and the Commonwealth is not providing any extra resources to assist with implementation. Clearly, this is worrying a number of those who have to provide the facilities and services on the ground. </para><para>It is clear that new subsection 31(1A), while it may require only minor changes to teaching practice or equipment provision, could result in major capital expenditure being required of an education provider. MCEETYA specifically raised this issue in the development of the standards as a possible impediment in the implementation phase. This government is clearly trying to steamroll the states in this cost-shifting exercise and has been unwilling to meet its responsibilities in sharing costs. While we are willing to accept the passage of this legislation, because we strongly believe in improving access for students with disabilities, we are gravely concerned that the money will not be available to make sure that the bill, once passed, and the standards, once introduced, will be able to work effectively.</para><para>There is also some concern from parent groups that the extended defence of unjustifiable hardship is a major trade-off for the other beneficial aspects of the bill—that is, that their children may in fact experience increased discrimination because underresourced schools will be able to enrol their children but continually refuse to make necessary adjustments for their full inclusion. This is a worrying area, where the issues of financing and principle interact with each other. Labor support the bill, but we call on the government to immediately undertake negotiations with state and territory education authorities and come to an agreed cost-sharing arrangement. Labor also reiterate the 2004 Senate committee's comments that the final education standards should be introduced as soon as possible.</para><para>In summary, we have some concerns about aspects of this legislation and its implementation but these concerns cannot override the very important benefits that this bill and the education standards will provide for disabled students. The goal to eliminate discrimination against people with a disability in education is enormously important. The right of every person and every child to an education is essential, and this parliament must do all it can to ensure that this right is available to everyone, regardless of any disability they may have.</para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>12:37:00</time.stamp><page.no>51</page.no><name role="metadata">Richardson, Kym, MP</name><name role="display">Mr RICHARDSON</name><name.id>E0B</name.id><electorate>Kingston</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I rise to support the <inline ref="R2209">Disability Discrimination Amendment (Education Standards) Bill 2004</inline>. My counterpart just mentioned the cost implication to a school. That school could perhaps apply for funding under the Howard government's direct funding for building alterations or infrastructure. The purpose of this bill is to establish a framework and legislative base which will give the best possible support to the education standards to be tabled in this parliament shortly. The Disability Discrimination Act 1992 allows the Attorney-General to develop disability standards in a wide variety of areas. One such area is the education of individuals with a disability. In June 2004 the government released for public information a final draft of the disability standards for education. These standards have been developed through extensive consultation with a wide variety of education providers, as well as with the disability sector and interested members of the public.</para></talk.start><para>The operation of the act differs marginally from the final draft of the standards, and that brings us to the specific achievements of this bill. The aim of this bill is to bring the legislation into line with those standards. The disability sector is eagerly awaiting the introduction of these standards, because they will finally provide the clarity and direction the industry so desperately needs in relation to students and prospective students with a disability. This government is dedicated not only to serving the disability sector but to doing so in the most effective manner possible. For that reason we have not introduced these standards without first seeking these amendments, for the simple reason that the industry and the community alike need the standards to be fully supported in legislation, without ambiguity, if they are to achieve their desired result. </para><para>The term `education provider' is used throughout the draft standards; it is a term used to describe educational authorities, institutions and organisations whose purpose is to develop or accredit curricula and training courses. The term `education provider' is neither defined nor used in the Disability Discrimination Act. This bill seeks to remove that anomaly, and to do so by defining the term with reference to terms already used and defined in the existing legislation. This bill also takes the very important step of making it unlawful for education providers to develop or approve any form of curricula or training course which would have the effect of excluding individuals with a disability from participation or which would otherwise subject them to detriment.</para><para>Individuals with a disability are not simply dealing with the physical impediments posed by their disability; they are also faced with the ever-growing challenge of overcoming the perceptions held by others and, in some cases, learning to deal with harassment and victimisation. This bill seeks to require education providers to become proactive in the prevention of harassment and victimisation. It will require providers to develop and implement strategies and programs which will prevent such behaviour, and to educate staff and students about the policies and the consequences if victimisation or harassment occurs. We are talking about a provision which ensures that a group who are already disadvantaged by circumstance are not further inhibited from accessing education because they are subject to the soul-destroying acts of others.</para><para>In proposing this bill, the government has not simply shifted the burden of preventing discrimination onto education providers. This bill provides for the extension of the `unjustifiable hardship' defence to cover post-enrolment situations, as well as curriculum development and accreditation, student support services and proposals for the elimination of harassment and victimisation. This bill affords education providers the ability to avoid provisions of this bill which would place the provider in a situation of undue hardship. The extension of this defence ensures that education will not be taking on the entire burden of eliminating disability discrimination in education.</para><para>Finally, this bill seeks to amend section 31 of the Disability Discrimination Act by allowing the disability standards to require reasonable adjustments to be made by education providers to eliminate, as far as possible, discrimination on the ground of disability. The Howard government made a public commitment in the joint statement by the Attorney-General and the Minister for Education, Science and Training on 15 June 2004. They made a commitment to the disability sector, to education providers and to the Australian people that they would introduce legislation which would ensure full legislative support for the draft disability standards for education. I stand before the House today to assist my government in delivering on that commitment. I increasingly meet with constituents in my electorate of Kingston who have a disability but who seek employment, and I regularly come in contact with service providers who place individuals with a disability into employment. The benefit to the community, to employers and to those individuals with a disability who obtain employment cannot be denied. I can tell you first-hand, Mr Deputy Speaker, that one of the major steps to ensuring higher levels of employment amongst this group is providing them with education. </para><para>This bill provides a base which will enable the disability standards for education to remove a massive roadblock currently preventing those with a disability from accessing education. The Howard government are dedicated to the education of Australians, and by that we mean all Australians. Australians with a disability face very real barriers when it comes to accessing education because those barriers are not always visible or obvious and they are not always dealt with. That stops today with the passage of this bill; that stops with the introduction of the disability standards for education. In the hope that it will make a difference in the lives of those with a disability, I commend this bill to the House.</para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>12:45:00</time.stamp><page.no>53</page.no><name role="metadata">Macklin, Jenny, MP</name><name role="display">Ms MACKLIN</name><name.id>PG6</name.id><electorate>Jagajaga</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—Congratulations, Mr Deputy Speaker, on joining the Speaker's panel. I will have to behave now!</para></talk.start><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">McMullan, Bob (The DEPUTY SPEAKER)</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para><inline font-weight="bold"> (Mr McMullan)</inline>—Indeed you will!</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>PG6</name.id><name role="metadata">Macklin, Jenny, MP</name><name role="display">Ms MACKLIN</name></talker><para>—It is a great pleasure to be able to speak on the <inline ref="R2209">Disability Discrimination Amendment (Education Standards) Bill 2004</inline>. At the outset, I want to say a couple of things about two schools in my electorate that do an outstanding job, along with many, many other schools. The first is Banksia Secondary College, which is a fantastic school. I remember being part of a most extraordinary end of year awards presentation at the school in which one of the school captains, Nick Brock, who is deaf, delivered his speech and ran the assembly using Auslan, and there was somebody there interpreting for him. It was an incredibly special afternoon, and a tribute to the wonderful efforts of the school. That school has a number of children with disabilities, some mild but some extremely disabling. There are some students with cerebral palsy and a significant number of students who are hearing impaired.</para></talk.start></continue><para>The second is the wonderful Rosanna Golf Links Primary School that has the regional deaf facility located within the school. It is a great tribute to the staff and the parents of Rosanna Golf Links to see the fantastic way in which the hearing impaired children are integrated into the school. There is separate learning time when there is very highly focused education for the children who are deaf, but they spend a lot of their time in the ordinary classrooms with all the other kids, and it is a wonderful thing to see the way in which they develop.</para><para>In both schools, one of the most special occasions is to see them all singing together. This happened while I was at Banksia, and I know it will happen at Rosanna Golf Links when I go there shortly to present their leadership awards. It is amazing to see the children using their voices to sing alongside children who are signing, whether the national anthem or other songs. It is a very moving experience.</para><para>It is very important that we support this legislation today to amend the Disability Discrimination Act 1992 so that we can have disability standards properly introduced into all of our educational facilities. I think it has taken far too long, frankly, for these standards to be introduced, so I am a very strong supporter of them going through this parliament. The whole purpose of the standards is to make sure the Disability Discrimination Act is being applied in our schools. Of course, the standards set out not only the rights of students but also the legal obligations of education and training providers. The standards provided for under the bill will detail how education systems have to meet their obligations under the Disability Discrimination Act. They are a very important step towards ensuring—not only in the schools I mentioned at the start of my remarks today but in every single school, TAFE or university—full participation in and equal access to education for people with a disability. </para><para>The disability standards will make sure that education providers take all reasonable measures to deliver equitable access to educational programs for students with disabilities. Providers will be able to claim unjustifiable hardship, such as the cost of capital upgrading or equipment, but I certainly hope the Commonwealth government, the state government and non-government providers of education do everything they possibly can to make sure these standards are met, because they are designed to protect the interests of students with disabilities.</para><para>The standards are all about making sure that students with disabilities have access to schools and other educational facilities so they can participate in the curriculum and related programs on the same basis as other children and young people. As is the case at Banksia Secondary College, schools have come a very long way over the last decade, but they do need additional support and guidance to make sure they provide equal access to people with a disability.</para><para>Compliance with disability standards for education is an important investment. We know that providing equal access is a very big task, because there are about 100,000 students with disabilities in our schools, both special schools and regular schools. Eighty per cent of students with disabilities attend government schools. The number of students with disabilities receiving integration support to help them in regular schools has grown significantly over the last decade—I think it has trebled.</para><para>So there has been a very significant increase in the number of students with disabilities being `mainstreamed' into government schools. It is probably the case now that almost every government school would have enrolled at least one student with a disability. State and territory governments provide over 95 per cent of funding for students with disabilities in government schools. As in other areas, the Commonwealth government is the major source of public funds for students with disabilities in non-government schools—in fact, over two-thirds of the public funding in those schools.</para><para>Students can have a very wide range of disabilities, whether it is intellectual disability, sensory disability, vision or hearing impairment, physical disability, one of a very wide range of social, emotional or behavioural disabilities, or developmental delay. It is often the case that students have multiple disabilities, and these are significant issues for students, teachers and parents to deal with in school. Some students also have other forms of disadvantage, whether it is isolation, poverty, being Indigenous, social deprivation or so on. We have a very significant challenge, particularly for the schools in those environments.</para><para>There are some students with disabilities who are still educated in special schools, and these special schools provide a very important educational environment for those students. There are about 20,000 students in these separate special schools—that is, about 15 to 20 per cent of all children with disabilities. The remainder are in our regular primary and secondary schools. Interestingly, about two-thirds are in primary schools. </para><para>I think everyone in this House knows that the students and teachers in schools, whether they are special schools or regular schools, certainly need extra support. Some of the students need in-class aids—of course, these are the students with more serious disabilities—to help them with their school work and often with other activities around the school as well. There are good systems in place in some schools to provide support through additional consultants who provide advice to teachers, additional print or ICT materials and a range of other integration supports. At each and every school that I go to, this is one of the major issues raised with me. Teachers are feeling under enormous pressure from the demands to respond positively to the needs of the increasing numbers of students with disabilities in their schools. Of course the teachers welcome these children into their classrooms, but I think we have to recognise that it puts a lot of pressure on the teachers. I am sure each and every one of us wants to do the best we can to help them. This area is crying out for more professional-learning programs. Teachers want to be better equipped to deal with the range of children with disabilities. Teachers want their knowledge, skills and teaching and learning methods expanded so that they can do their best by both the children with disabilities and the other children in the classroom.</para><para>We also could be doing better in our universities and TAFEs. About six per cent of people doing vocational education and training have a disability, including about 90,000 Australians with a disability at TAFE. There are about 24,000 Australians with a disability studying at our universities. That is about 3½ per cent of all of our Australian students. These disability standards are important not only in our schools but also at TAFEs and in universities so that young people and the mature aged are able to go on to get further qualifications and the skills they need to get a good job. Those students at TAFEs and in universities not only need their teachers to have the skills to educate people with disabilities but also particularly need access to equipment and curriculum materials so that they can succeed in their studies.</para><para>Parents with children who have disabilities also have particular needs. They probably need more time with their teachers, especially at school, to help with the education of their children. It is important for schools to have that extra time to develop individual learning plans for the children and to take account of the individual needs that different children have.</para><para>One of the big areas of expense is the capital adjustment schools and other educational institutions need so that students with disabilities can access schools, in particular, but also TAFE and universities. This applies to major capital areas, like lifts for educational institutions, and other areas, especially facilities for the hearing impaired and the visually impaired. All of these people need particular capital adjustments to be made so that they can participate in the teaching and learning programs that are available and be successful.</para><para>We need some system-wide reforms. Updated curriculum material and better production of equipment would also assist in many of our educational institutions. There has been some independent analysis, such as a paper by the Allen Consulting Group for the Department of Education, Science and Training and the 2004 report of the Productivity Commission. These reports support the development of standards but, most importantly, acknowledge that there are costs associated with the development of these standards. I do not think there is any doubt that implementing the standards will see future education and training of Australians with disabilities improve, but it is a cost that needs to be shared by the Commonwealth, the states and the non-government authorities. </para><para>We have had some warning about this. There was a Senate inquiry not long ago that warned the government of the challenges facing our educational authorities when they provide quality services for people with a disability. This inquiry reported in December 2002:</para><quote><para>There is unambiguous evidence of under-resourcing of programs aimed at bringing students with disabilities into the mainstream of learning; as well as funding inconsistencies between states.</para></quote><para>The committee reported `evidence that the proportion of students with an identified disability is increasing' at a much greater rate than the overall student population. One of the reasons for that is that there is much more effective early diagnosis and continuing successes in medical intervention. Both of these things are good developments, but it is adding to the cost of delivering education.</para><para>One area that the committee particularly reflected on was the better understanding of the nature of disability particularly, for example, in the area of autism. I am sure that many members have been in schools where there are children with autism. That particular condition provides challenges both to the staff of the schools and to the parents of the children who have that condition. The Senate committee made the important point that school authorities are moving from remediation, which used to be the way to early diagnosis and mainstreaming of programs. I have no doubt that these strategies will be much more effective in the longer run, but all of us have to face up to the resource pressures that are on our schools, TAFEs and universities now.</para><para>The committee made quite a few recommendations and I urge the government to have another look at the Senate inquiry's report and the recommendations that were made. I think they were all very practical, sensible recommendations that would have a very positive effect if the government took them up and introduced them. Unfortunately, we have not had that response from the government. We have this bill today, which I strongly support, but we do need to go further and to recognise that this government has a responsibility to share in the cost of meeting these standards. Unfortunately, when it comes to children in government schools, we have not had any funding above indexation for students with disabilities since 1996 from this government. That is certainly an area where we could do with some improvement. It is also the case that students with disabilities in nongovernment schools, particularly the more needy ones, are crying out for more support. I met with the Associations of Christian Schools this week and once again they raised this issue with me; they too have urgent needs. The 80 per cent of students with disabilities who depend on the public system could certainly do with increased support from this government, as could the students with disabilities in nongovernment schools.</para><para>Finally, I just want to touch on some other initiatives that we took to the last election because it is an area that I think that we could certainly do better in once these standards are implemented. We had particular initiatives both in government and in nongovernment schools. They included additional funding not only for capital equipment and ICT infrastructure, both of which are very important if we are going to meet these disability standards, but also for helping teachers in schools to deliver the intensive support that the students with disabilities in both regular and special schools need. Some of the things that we would have spent that money on were more teacher aides in classrooms, more time for classroom teachers to be able to provide personalised teaching, better professional development for classroom teachers and teacher aides, better equipment for students—particularly with physical and intellectual disabilities—and so on. I am very pleased to say that we did have a very comprehensive approach to this area but, all that having been said, I really do want to lend my strong support to the introduction of these standards. But I say to the government that to make these standards work and to make sure they are delivered in all of our educational institutions will require additional financial support from the Commonwealth. </para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>13:04:00</time.stamp><page.no>57</page.no><name role="metadata">Elson, Kay, MP</name><name role="display">Mrs ELSON</name><name.id>6K6</name.id><electorate>Forde</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I am very proud to speak today on this <inline ref="R2209">Disability Discrimination Amendment (Education Standards) Bill 2004</inline> that furthers the rights of people living with a disability. I note that this bill was first introduced in August last year but, of course, it lapsed when the election was called the following month. I commend the Attorney-General, Mr Ruddock, for re-introducing it so quickly. The Howard government has worked hard since being elected to further support and improve opportunities for people with disabilities and to help and support their families to access greater respite and care services. Of course there is still more to be done, and I am working hard with the local organisations in my electorate of Forde to secure more funding for services in our region. This will be an ongoing battle, particularly when the state Labor governments are withdrawing services in some areas. I will outline that in detail later, but I am very pleased to be able to speak today on this bill, which goes one step further in enabling the introduction of the disability standards for education.</para></talk.start><para>Members of this House would be aware that before entering politics I worked as a coordinator for the Handicapped Association—now the Horizon Foundation—and Multicap, a service provider for people with multiple disabilities. In these roles I had the opportunity to see at first hand the daily struggles of people living with a range of disabilities, from mild to more severe. I gained a very deep understanding of their desire to be active, contributing members of their communities and to be accepted as a valued part of society. On a daily basis I learnt much from their constant displays of courage, their determination and their willingness to appreciate the true value of life.</para><para>Modern medicine advances have, fortunately, vastly improved the treatment of many conditions, thereby improving the quality of life of people living with a disability. It is estimated that around 20 per cent of Australians live with some form of disability. For some people this will mean an extra daily challenge, but essentially many people living with a disability are able to hold down full-time jobs, lead an active life and play a very important part in our communities. For others, their disability affects their daily life to a greater degree and they require a larger range of support services.</para><para>The most comprehensive data collected on the range of disability services provided by both the Commonwealth and the states is the recent Australian Institute of Health and Welfare report <inline font-style="italic">Disability support services 2002-2003</inline>. That report found that a total of $2.9 billion was spent in 2002 to 2003 on direct services for those living with a disability and their families. Accommodation support services accounted for 51 per cent of the total funding; community access services were 12 per cent; community support services, 10 per cent; employment services, nine per cent; and respite services, six per cent, or around $172 million. </para><para>As I said at the outset, our government has worked hard to deliver more services and assistance for people living with a disability, including the $1.7 billion Australians Working Together package, which offers more employment services and opportunities. Of course, education and training is a major factor in employment opportunities and advancement. Sadly, the Productivity Commission review of the Disability Discrimination Act found that exclusion from education and training is one of the most serious forms of disability discrimination. The setting of disability standards for education is expected to go some way towards addressing this inequity and setting out clear guidelines for the provision of education services.</para><para>Our approach with this bill, as always, is balanced. We want to improve access and make people with a disability more aware of their rights, while at the same time ensuring, through the provisions about unjustifiable hardship, that education providers are not unduly disadvantaged. It is a sensible and balanced approach, and I am hoping that the Queensland state government will take note.</para><para>Once again I am asking in this House that the Queensland Premier, Mr Beattie, look at the impact that the review of special needs funding by Education Queensland has had on disabled children and their families. Many disabled children had their teaching support seriously cut, which resulted in special needs children being placed in ordinary classrooms with little or no assistance. In late 2003, Education Queensland dropped the ascertainment level of nearly 1,000 disabled children, which in turn meant their teaching support was reduced or even entirely dropped.</para><para>At the special education development unit at Mount Warren Park, a school in my electorate, parents who do secure a place in this unit for their children have been dismayed to find that a vital service like speech therapy is virtually nonexistent. I repeat: the vital, basic service of speech therapy is nonexistent. We are talking about children aged from three to six years, a vital stage for speech development. These children are being denied access to speech therapy for whole semesters at a time. When they do have contact with a therapist, it is generally only for a very short period, one day a week—and that is only if they are lucky, as the parents tell me. Mainly the therapist conducts assessments, rather than actually working with the child to make improvements. As a mother, I can only imagine how frustrating this situation is for parents of children with special needs.</para><para>These parents have been fundraising like crazy to pay for an additional speech therapist to help their children, but, as this is only a small unit, that is an enormous task to ask of these parents. After all, we are talking about the basics here. As one parent put it to me, `Communication is the essence of our society.' If we cannot give our young children the opportunity to communicate to the very best of their ability, what chance do they have to overcome any difficulties they may face later on in life?</para><para>Despite ongoing representations from me and from parents—we even took petitions up—this situation remains unchanged. The local Labor state member, Margaret Keech, is unwilling or unable to do anything, and the state government just do not seem to be listening. They do not seem to be listening to her, the parents, me or our special needs support groups within our community.</para><para>I am hoping that, eventually, the introduction of the disability education standards will support our efforts to lobby the state government and add weight to the concerns of parents, who know the needs of their children best. It should not have to come to this. I should not be standing here once again. It is simply common sense to ensure that funding for speech therapy services for young children seeking to overcome development and learning difficulties should be allocated to this school so these parents' children at least get a chance in life. </para><para>Again, I ask the Queensland Premier to have Education Queensland urgently review the level of support and assistance available to children with disabilities, including those with mild impairment. These are often the ones who slip through the cracks, come out the other end of the system and—not having any support—have problems later on in life. This is a shocking situation. More resources clearly need to be allocated to help these special needs children. While various state governments try to dodge it, it is very clear that responsibility for the delivery of primary and secondary education services rests with them. They have a duty to deliver these services to everyone, including these people living with disabilities.</para><para>The Queensland government has received and continues to receive more funding than expected through GST revenue. It is worth noting that every cent of the GST goes directly to the states and territories to fund such things as roads, schools and hospital services. Every state and territory has received more than they expected in GST revenues in the past few years, yet they have failed to properly deliver the basic services that they really ought to deliver. The Labor Party are always big on their rhetoric when it comes to services, but their track record at state government level is one not just of inaction but of actually cutting funding for many vital services. The states really need to be brought to account.</para><para>Even in relation to this bill, several states tried to delay the introduction of the education standards. As the members of the Disability Discrimination Act Standards Project put it in their press release of 11 July 2003:</para><quote><para>We are disappointed that some of the States and Territories attempted to once again delay the introduction of the Education Standards.</para><para>To our delight, the Commonwealth Minister, Dr Brendan Nelson, has exercised his leadership. Dr Nelson recognises that after seven and half years of development, the Education Standards are now in agreement, and that legal and financial concerns have been resolved through independent inquiry.</para></quote><para>I, too, commend the minister and thank him for his leadership on this issue.</para><para>I am very proud to be part of a government that is taking the lead on these issues and that is working hard to improve these services and support the people who are living with disabilities. I look forward to working within government to secure more funding for effective programs. As I said, there is still more to be done in my electorate, but I will continue the fight down here for them. Unfortunately, I am going to conclude my speech very shortly because I am suffering from the flu and a sore throat, and I do not think it is going to do anyone any good for me to stand here coughing for the rest of this speech.</para><para>In closing, I would like to congratulate volunteers and providers of disability services within my electorate of Forde. They are all very dedicated and caring people. They work extremely hard to ensure that people and children with disabilities have a better and fulfilling quality of life.</para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>13:14:00</time.stamp><page.no>59</page.no><name role="metadata">Ferguson, Michael, MP</name><name role="display">Mr MICHAEL FERGUSON</name><name.id>DYH</name.id><electorate>Bass</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I rise to speak in favour of the <inline ref="R2209">Disability Discrimination Amendment (Education Standards) Bill 2004</inline>. As we have heard already, the bill proposes relatively minor amendments to ensure that the disability standards for education are supported to the greatest possible extent by the legislation. The standards do vary the operation of the DDA in some minor ways. Accordingly, the bill was prepared following legal advice that it is desirable to amend the legislation to remove any uncertainty and to avoid any potential challenges to its validity. </para></talk.start><para>The disability standards for education will be applied to government and non-government providers in all education sectors: preschool, school, vocational education and training, higher education and even adult and community education. They will also apply to organisations whose purpose is to develop and accredit curricula and courses—if you like, third-party providers. This is to ensure that these bodies consider the needs of students with disabilities up front in the design and accreditation of curricula which will be used by other schools and education providers. The standards cover the areas of enrolment; participation; curriculum development, delivery and accreditation; student support services; and the elimination of harassment and victimisation, to the extent that that is possible. These areas have been identified as covering all areas required for a student's access to and participation in education or training.</para><para>This legislation also provides reasonable adjustments to put students with disabilities on the same basis as other students. The standards recognise that to overcome the disadvantage arising from their disability students with disabilities need to be treated differently to remove or reduce barriers to their participation in education. The standards operate on the principle that students with disabilities should be provided with opportunities that place them on the same basis as other students so that they can achieve and realise their own potential in education and training. It is, of course, the goal of every parent in Australia to see their child achieve their potential, whether or not they have a disability or special needs.</para><para>To achieve this, the standards set out a process for determining and providing a reasonable adjustment. This is a measure or an action that enables the student to enrol and participate. As the forms of disability recognised by the act and the standards are wide ranging, in order to identify and make an adjustment which is appropriate to that student's disability education providers are required to consult with the student or their associate or parent. The consultation may also include an independent expert opinion to assist in that process. An adjustment is only required to be reasonable, and this is an important point. That is to balance the interests of all the parties who are affected, including the student with the disability, the school or education provider, staff and also other students.</para><para>I am advised that in any one year in Australia there are more than 200,000 students with a disability across all of the different sectors that I have described. This number is, interestingly enough, increasing over time. Definitions do vary across the sectors for reporting these statistics. In the school sector the number of students with disabilities is reported by the state and territory governments and non-government school authorities, while in the higher education and vocational education and training sectors students are self-identified. Notwithstanding these definitional issues, in 2003 there were 210,000 students with a disability across all sectors. It is important to note that the disability standards for education have the potential to make a significant difference by ensuring that all of these students can participate in education on the same basis as students who do not have special needs or disabilities.</para><para>With regard to Australian government support for the education of students with disabilities, I believe it is important to place on the record the excellent work that has been carried on by this government, not just in the current parliament but also previously, and to place on the record what has been achieved. Perhaps towards the end of my remarks I will identify some areas where more work is required. While, as we know, the primary responsibility for the provision of education and training rests with providers—and the Australian government is of course not a provider of education and training—the government does provide substantial assistance to state and territory and also non-government education and training authorities. This happens throughout the education sectors and, importantly, includes students with special needs and disabilities. </para><para>In the school sector the Australian government's financial assistance to the states and territories is significant. It is designed to improve the educational outcomes of all students, including those with disabilities, and is largely provided through three programs. Of these, the general recurrent grants program is the main source of Australian government funding and we have heard much about this, particularly towards the end of last year when the bill was passed, with an estimated $20.1 billion being provided to Australian schools in the 2001-04 quadrennium.</para><para>The Strategic Assistance for Improving Student Outcomes program, or SAISO, is the Australian government's major targeted funding program to improve the learning outcomes of educationally disadvantaged students in government and non-government schools. This is particularly the case in literacy and numeracy and for students with disabilities. Passed by parliament on 13 December last year was the Schools Assistance (Learning Together—Achievement Through Choice and Opportunity) Bill 2004. As we have heard, this will deliver a record $33 billion package of funding for Australian schools in the next quadrennium, 2005-08. This funding includes an estimated $2.1 billion for a new, overarching targeted program, the Literacy, Numeracy and Special Learning Needs Program, which will be targeted at the most educationally disadvantaged students, including those with disabilities.</para><para>In the vocational education and training sector, the Australian government has provided $1.15 billion to the states for VET in 2004. Under the national VET arrangements, responsibility for both public and private training systems lies with the states and territories. However, the Australian government has significantly increased VET funding for people with a disability, under its Australians Working Together welfare reform package, with an additional $9 million being available in 2004 for more training places and learning supports for people with disabilities. This will grow to over $11 million in 2005 and to more than $22 million in 2006, once the Senate passes legislation associated with this government's welfare reform package. The focus of activity in Bridging Pathways, a blueprint for improving opportunities for people with a disability, agreed to by state and territory ministers for training in June 2000, has been to improve the VET system's capacity to respond to the needs of people with a disability, including ensuring that resources and supports are available at the point of delivery.</para><para>In the higher education sector, universities are expected to provide the infrastructure and support that is necessary to ensure the best and the most effective participation for all their students—again, including those with a disability. In 2005, the Australian government will provide funds under the Commonwealth grants scheme of almost $3 billion for the provision of Commonwealth supported university places. As part of the Our Universities: Backing Australia's Future reforms, from 2005 the higher education disability support program will strengthen the focus of disability support in Australian higher education providers and increase that funding to over $6.5 million. This program consists of three parts. First, there is additional support for students with disabilities, which provides funding support to higher education providers to assist with the high costs that can be incurred in providing support and equipment to students with disabilities. The second part is the regional disability liaison officers, who will help to facilitate the transition from school to VET or higher education and then, hopefully, on to employment. The third part will be performance based disability funding support, which encourages higher education providers to implement strategies to attract and support schools with students with disabilities. </para><para>As I was waiting for my turn to speak just now I was listening to the remarks being made by the member for Forde about the level of support being provided to students across the sectors by the Queensland government. I had a great sense of deja vu as I reminisced about my years as a teacher in the state school education system in Tasmania. It was very disappointing to hear that it is happening in other states also. But, that being no surprise, this morning as I was talking with a Labor colleague on, I suppose, a collegial basis, they remarked that, even though they were in the same party as all of the state governments around Australia, despite that sense of camaraderie it was so difficult to get their state counterparts to pull their weight.</para><para>In closing, I would like to bring to the attention of the House the situation in Tasmania. Tasmania has a policy for students with disabilities which, I think, is complimented around Australia—that is, the policy of inclusion. Without going into the ideological arguments for or against inclusion—I am not about to do that today—it is important to note that inclusion has been sold to the community, and even to parents, as providing a choice for children. That choice is said to be between going to a special school—or, if you like, a specialist school for students with a disability or special needs—and going to a mainstream school. That choice is very important. It should not be lost on those of us in parliament or in the community who are not necessarily parents or, indeed, parents of children with special needs that it is in fact not the politicians, the teachers or the principals who care most about the students concerned—it is the parents. They, after all, are the ones who brought the children into the world. Undisputedly, they are the ones who love the children and have their welfare at heart the most. Hence, the choice is so important. I would argue that the implementation of the inclusion policy in Tasmania has utterly removed that choice.</para><para>I witnessed students come into my classroom, say, in grade 8 of high school, having come from a specialist school, and they struggled. They found it difficult. In my own extended family, I have a similar story where the child and parents were put under great pressure by the educational authority to move the child from a specialist school, where the classes were small, the teaching assistance was intensive and where the care factor was so very high. The school had teachers specially trained just for the purpose of teaching children with a disability. That is not to say it was easy, but it was a specialist environment and a very nurturing place for the child. They were pressured to go to what we shall call a regular mainstream school, such as mine.</para><para>That being the case, and being the case with many different students, it has had a great result in changing the profile of each of the two school sectors. This has meant a reduced resource base available to special schools. By continuing to put pressure on parents and students to move from specialist schools into mainstream schools there was, of course, an impact on the funding arrangements for each school concerned. The specialist schools had fewer students, therefore they received less funding support, less teacher allocation and less resourcing in terms of programs available to the students who were left. It also allowed the government to argue later that there was reduced demand in these specialist schools. That is the great hypocrisy of what happened. First arguing that there was a reduced demand on these schools, they then made a case that some of these schools should be closed down. Over time, the choice available to parents, even for that small community of parents and students, was diminishing and being eroded by the day. That has made me extremely angry. I think it has made a lot of parents in Tasmania very angry. </para><para>It breaks my heart to hear that it is happening all around Australia, because of state governments who are negligent, who do not seem to care about the students given to their care and who I think are showing a great disregard. It breaks my heart because I see that schools in my electorate—like St Michael's school and like St George's school—are being treated like cannon fodder for education authorities who do not want to spend the money. They do not seem to want to appreciate—just because they have a nice, cushy life on a politician's salary—that other parents and students find it more difficult and that their needs are just as important. I think that is a great tragedy.</para><para>I welcome the amendments to the Disability Discrimination Act in that they again reinforce that notion of choice and real support being given to students who need it. I think that if we do not know someone ourselves or if we do not have someone in our own family who suffers from a disability or who has a special need, we forget sometimes in this place what it must be like. I do not think we do appreciate what it could be like to live with that day by day. Of course the school day is just a small fraction of the time of a child's life, most of it being in the care of their parents. I would today call upon all state and territory governments to rededicate themselves to providing real choices to parents, to providing real support to students who need it and to providing a real future for these students.</para><para>I made the comment earlier in my contribution that really the goal of every parent is to see their child achieve their potential. Today I do not propose to know exactly how to measure that for each child. We are all different and our children are all different. I just argue that parents, being the ones who love their children the most, ought to be given more flexibility and more support. I think that there would be nobody in this place who would disagree with the basic tenets upon which I have based my argument. I call upon the state government to review the level of funding support and structural support available to this very important sector of the educational program in Tasmania.</para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>13:32:00</time.stamp><page.no>63</page.no><name role="metadata">Pyne, Chris, MP</name><name role="display">Mr PYNE</name><name.id>9V5</name.id><electorate>Sturt</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister for Health and Ageing</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—Thank you, Mr Deputy Speaker McMullan. I have not seen you in this role before, so I welcome you to the chair. I would like to thank the members of this House who have taken part in the debate on the <inline ref="R2209">Disability Discrimination Amendment (Education Standards) Bill 2004</inline>, particularly the member for Gellibrand and the Deputy Leader of the Opposition. Importantly, for the heartfelt and intelligent contributions on our side of the House I thank the new members for Kingston and Bass and the member for Forde. I thank them for the role that they played in the debate.</para></talk.start><para>The Disability Discrimination Act 1992 provides that the Attorney-General may formulate disability standards in a range of areas, including the education of persons with disabilities. There are already disability standards governing accessible public transport. These came into effect in October 2002. It is clear that the transport standards have already benefited people with a range of disabilities, as well as other members of the public, including the elderly and parents with prams. Draft standards for access to premises were also released for public consultation in 2004. Under section 31(2) of the Disability Discrimination Act, disability standards formulated by the Attorney-General must be tabled in parliament. Once they are in effect it is unlawful to contravene a disability standard. The purpose of disability standards is to clarify and elaborate the obligations imposed by the Disability Discrimination Act. </para><para>The draft disability standards for education have been developed over many years. Their development has involved extensive consultation with government and non-government education providers, the disability sector and other interested members of the public. In June 2004 the government released for public information a draft of the standards, along with accompanying guidance notes to assist in their interpretation. The draft of the standards differs from the operation of the act in minor ways, so it was necessary to make these amendments to the act to ensure that the standards are properly supported.</para><para>In particular, this bill will amend the Disability Discrimination Act to introduce and define the term `education provider'; provide that it is unlawful for education providers to discriminate on the ground of disability in the development or accreditation of curricula or training courses; extend the defence of unjustifiable hardship in education to post-enrolment situations; clarify that disability standards may require reasonable adjustments to be made in order to avoid unlawful discrimination on the ground of disability; provide that education providers may be required to develop strategies and programs to prevent the harassment and victimisation of students with disabilities; and clarify that education providers may not be excused from complying with a standard of education on issues relating to programs that prevent harassment or victimisation on the ground of unjustifiable hardship. When implemented, the draft disability standards for education will specify how education and training are to be made more accessible to students and prospective students with disabilities, without imposing unduly onerous burdens on education providers. They will clearly describe the obligations of education providers in relation to students with disabilities, and provide guidance on how to meet those obligations.</para><para>This bill was referred for inquiry and report to the Senate Legal and Constitutional Legislation Committee. The Senate committee reported on 8 December 2004. A majority of the committee recommended the bill be passed without amendment and urged the government to introduce the final education standards into parliament as soon as practicable after the passage of the bill. The bill was then passed by the Senate without amendment. The support for the passage of the bill has been very positive, and we thank the Senate.</para><para>There have been a few issues raised in the debate by the member for Gellibrand and the Deputy Leader of the Opposition. The first of those has been the costs of implementation of disability standards for education, which I would like to deal with. The standards and the amendments to the Disability Discrimination Act make it clear that education providers will not be required to make adjustments for students with disabilities if those adjustments would cause them unjustifiable hardship. As the regulation impact statement shows, there should be no, or very minimal, additional costs incurred in implementing the education standards if providers are already meeting their obligations under the Disability Discrimination Act. </para><para>The government already provides substantial assistance to the states and territories and non-government education and training authorities in all education sectors, including for students with disabilities. The funding includes an estimated $2.1 billion for a new overarching program of literacy, numeracy and special learning needs to be targeted at the most educationally disadvantaged students. I very strongly support this. My father was the founding vice-president of SPELD in South Australia. SPELD is the specific education learning difficulties non-government organisation, which was established by my father in South Australia and around the country in 1975 or 1976 because one of his children suffered from dyslexia. I digress momentarily. My father was made father of the year for South Australia in 1975 because of his work with SPELD and specific learning difficulties. I very strongly support the role of the government in providing that money and support for people with learning difficulties.</para><para>Another issue that the member for Gellibrand and the Deputy Leader of the Opposition raised was the possible undesirable consequences of extending the defence of unjustifiable hardship. The government is keen to ensure that, when they are formulated, the disability standards for education reflect an appropriate balance between the interests of a student or a prospective student with a disability and the effects on the education provider of making an adjustment to accommodate the student. At the moment, it is only possible for an education provider to claim unjustifiable hardship at the point of enrolment of a student with a disability. The amendment in this bill to extend the defence of unjustifiable hardship beyond the point of enrolment will avoid the undesirable effect of discouraging educational institutions from admitting students with disabilities because they are concerned about the potential future costs of accommodating the student. The experience has been that some educational institutions refuse enrolment on the basis of potential concerns about disability when, if they could enrol students and see how they go, the institution may find they did not have any difficulties that would have precluded their being enrolled in the first place. This is an important step.</para><para>This bill will clear the way for draft disability standards for education, which have been the product of extensive consultation with industry, government and disability sector representatives. The standards are a practical way of clarifying the requirements of the Disability Discrimination Act. They will provide certainty for education providers about their obligations under the Disability Discrimination Act, and they will clarify the rights of people with disabilities with respect to education and training. There is no doubt that one of the key issues that members of parliament deal with that is heartfelt and heart-rending for all of us is the difficulties that people with disabilities face that those of us without a disability have not had to face. I was the Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister for Family and Community Services for 12 months, and I listened to many very difficult and challenging stories from parents who are trying to help their children have as normal lives as possible. I am sure that you, Mr Deputy Speaker McMullan, and every member of parliament tries to do everything they can and more to help those parents who come to them because they are having difficulties with their children who have disabilities.</para><para>I welcome this bill because it creates a smoother process to enrol students with disabilities and to give them the support they need. I hope the states and territories and those members of the Commonwealth who will implement aspects of the legislation do so with good grace in the hope that they can help people with disabilities to have as normal a life as possible, which they deserve. I thank the House. </para><para>Question agreed to.</para><para>Bill read a second time.</para></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Third Reading</title><page.no>66</page.no></subdebateinfo><para>Mr PYNE (Sturt—Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister for Health and Ageing) (1.37 p.m.)—by leave—I move:</para><motion><para>That this bill be now read a third time.</para></motion><para>Question agreed to.</para><para>Bill read a third time.</para></subdebate.1></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>APPROPRIATION BILL (NO. 3) 2004-2005</title><type>Bills</type><page.no>66</page.no><id.no>R2279</id.no><cognate><cognateinfo><title>APPROPRIATION BILL (NO. 4) 2004-2005</title><type>Bills</type><id.no>R2278</id.no></cognateinfo></cognate><cognate><cognateinfo><title>APPROPRIATION (PARLIAMENTARY DEPARTMENTS) BILL (NO. 2) 2004-2005</title><type>Bills</type><id.no>R2277</id.no></cognateinfo></cognate><cognate><cognateinfo><title>APPROPRIATION BILL (NO. 4) 2004-2005</title><type>Bills</type></cognateinfo></cognate></debateinfo><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Second Reading</title><page.no>66</page.no></subdebateinfo><para>Debate resumed from 16 February, on motion by <inline font-weight="bold">Mr Brough</inline>:</para><motion><para>That this bill be now read a second time.</para></motion><para>upon which <inline font-weight="bold">Mr Swan</inline> moved by way of amendment:</para><para>That all words after “That” be omitted with a view to substituting the following words:</para><para>“whilst not declining to give the bill a second reading, the House condemns the Government for its:</para><para>(1)	dishonest promises during the 2004 election campaign that it would keep interest rates low;</para><para>(2)	short-term, reckless spending during the lead up to the 2004 election, which is adding to inflationary and interest rate pressures;</para><para>(3)	gross neglect of Australia's education and training needs, leaving Australia with a skills crisis which is adding to inflationary and interest rate pressures; and</para><para>(4)	failure to secure Australia's economic future by making the long term policy commitments that will improve the productivity and competitiveness of the Australian economy”.</para><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>13:42:00</time.stamp><page.no>66</page.no><name role="metadata">Slipper, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr SLIPPER</name><name.id>0V5</name.id><electorate>Fisher</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I have only a very short amount of time left. Yesterday when I was speaking I was interrupted by the adjournment. Yesterday in the Main Committee I was talking about the outstanding work carried out by the University of the Sunshine Coast and the tremendous progress that that institution has made since it was established in 1994. The member for Fairfax and I went to see the then education minister, Dr Kemp, with a view to allowing the university to become a fully independent institution. This occurred in 1999, when the university changed its name to the University of the Sunshine Coast. Since that time, it has gone from strength to strength. The current Minister for Education, Science and Training, Dr Nelson, has been to the university. He has spoken with the key stakeholders at the university, and I have to say that the university owes him a very great debt because of the strong support that he has given to the University of the Sunshine Coast.</para></talk.start><para>I pointed out in the Main Committee yesterday that, between now and 2008, the University of the Sunshine Coast has been allocated 1,080 new places out of a total of 6,500 new places allocated to the state of Queensland. In fact, 395 new places have been made available for this academic year. Of the 1,080 new places, 328 will go to secondary teaching. Other disciplines to receive substantial increases in places include business, 205 new places; enabling sciences, 137 new places; human movement, 150 new places; and human welfare, 96 new places. New places will also go to nursing, health promotion and communication media studies.</para><para>These new places have been allocated to a wide number of disciplines, which is a great thing. This means that the university will be able to offer a wide range of courses and will become a much more attractive place for students to attend as students will be able to study a wide range of subjects in a wide range of degree courses. The breadth of disciplines is indicative of the university's innovative approach and the Howard government's support for students' learning across all disciplines. </para><para>Part of the university's success lies with the very high calibre of staff employed by the university, which ranks No. 1 among all Queensland universities and fifth among all Australian universities in proportion to full-time academic staff with PhDs and higher degrees. This extremely high level of professionalism is reflected in the documented graduate satisfaction rate of 92 per cent from students' university experience. I have met many of the students from the university, and I am impressed with the calibre of person the university is releasing into the community to perform worthwhile work on behalf of their fellow community members. I am personally proud of this institution. It is a university that will go from strength to strength, and it is a university we can all admire.</para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>13:45:00</time.stamp><page.no>67</page.no><name role="metadata">Elliot, Justine, MP</name><name role="display">Mrs ELLIOT</name><name.id>DZW</name.id><electorate>Richmond</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—There is a crisis in aged care and the <inline ref="R2279">Appropriation Bill (No. 3) 2004-2005</inline> does nothing to rectify it. After nine years of underfunding and neglect, the government remains complacent about fixing the problems. Red tape, a funding shortage, a lack of facilities and staff, and differing standards of care are always issues that come up when people speak to me about aged care. Nowhere are the problems more obvious than in the electorate of Richmond. One in four people living in Richmond is over 65 and thousands of people retire to the electorate every year. They come to Richmond looking for a better lifestyle. We can certainly offer them that—beautiful beaches and a relaxed and friendly environment. Unfortunately, they also often find a lack of infrastructure and underfunded aged care facilities that are unable to meet their needs. That is what nine years of neglect by the government has given them. The government had simply failed to put resources where they are most needed—in areas like the North Coast of New South Wales. If our elderly want to retain their independence, they find that they are unable to access some basic assistance to help them stay in their homes.</para></talk.start><para>Our older Australians have made a tremendous contribution to our society. It shows a total lack of respect from this government that our seniors are not being cared for properly. The government has taken the support of older Australians for granted. They think that this is a licence to neglect aged care in Australia. The government's record on aged care is not a good one, particularly in my electorate. Waiting lists for aged care beds in Richmond have blown out. Our hospital wards are filling up with elderly people who cannot get into an aged care bed because there is simply not one available. There is a six- to seven-month waiting list for CAPS packages that provide vital home care—home care that allows our local elderly to maintain their independence.</para><para>In 1990 there were 250 referrals to CAPS across my electorate. By 2004 there were 1,800 referrals. In January alone this year, there were 190 referrals. The government is failing to keep up with this level of demand. Locally, we received just 180 CAPS packages, which provide seven hours a week home care. That is one-tenth of the referrals. It is obvious to me and my community where the demand lies, yet the government has failed to act on its responsibility to older Australians. That is why I have decided to hold a local aged care summit. The summit will bring together local aged care and health experts as well as elderly residents of Richmond. I want to hear from them about the aged care needs of my local community and I want to work with them to find solutions to the current problems facing the aged care sector in my local community. That is also why I fought so hard to get on this parliament's health and ageing committee. It is important to elderly people in my electorate and their families that the government is held accountable for the decisions they make regarding aged care. </para><para>The government have become so complacent on aged care that they have failed to provide the necessary funding. I would be happy for the Minister for Ageing to come to Richmond to see the need for herself. She could visit any one of the nursing homes in my electorate and see first-hand the problems in aged care. They could tell her about the number of people who are waiting to get into an aged care bed and they could tell her about their staffing problems and the problems they have with red tape—the time they spend away from caring for residents, filling in paperwork. I am happy to work with anyone—across party lines and at all levels of government—so that elderly people in Richmond are well cared for. In my view, this is an issue above politics. It is about care and respect for the senior citizens who have contributed so much to our community.</para><para>Just last week the National Aged Care Alliance, the peak representative body of the aged care industry, released a paper urging the government to address the funding problems in aged care. The alliance is made up of health professionals, the elderly, unions and aged care providers. These are the aged care experts. If the minister ignores their recommendations, she is ignoring the problems faced in the aged care sector. The alliance has compiled a list of major problems that the government needs to address, including insufficient funding, a failure to provide for older Australians with special needs and proper training for staff. I was encouraged to see that the shadow minister for aged care has taken on board their recommendations and will continue to consider them closely.</para><para>I want to take this opportunity to pay tribute to the staff of my local aged care facilities. Over the past two years I have had the opportunity to visit several of my local nursing homes. During every visit I meet dedicated and caring staff who work hard to provide for our seniors. Unfortunately, the government ties them up in red tape. Instead of caring for our elderly, they are forced to spend their time bogged down in paperwork. Professor Warren Hogan, author of a $7.2 million government report into aged care, agrees. He thinks that there needs to be a complete overhaul of aged care legislation. Let us hope that the $7.2 million the government has spent on this report does not go to waste. My fear is that Professor Hogan's report will gather dust on a shelf in the minister's office. I urge the Minister for Ageing to look carefully at Professor Hogan's report—a report she herself called:</para><quote><para>One of the most expansive and detailed reviews of residential aged care ever produced.</para></quote><para>I know that the message from my community to the minister is: act on this report immediately and make the changes that the Hogan report recommended. Instead of ignoring the experts, it is time the minister listened to what they and the community are saying. The time to fix our aged care system is now. Older Australians deserve the very best care available.</para><para>The government's complacency over the past nine years has left the aged care system in an absolute shambles. I will always support sensible proposals to improve quality, affordability and access to aged care. I am always willing to work with anyone to get a better deal for seniors in Richmond and I will continue to push the minister to fix the problems created over the past nine years—problems created because the government has simply ignored the needs of older Australians. </para><para>The lack of aged care beds and suitable home care arrangements for our elderly creates problems in the wider community. I know of many cases of elderly people who are forced to stay in hospital because there is no aged care bed available. Some are going to the emergency ward because they cannot afford to see their GP. That is why I secured a commitment from the Minister for Health and Ageing for an after-hours GP clinic for Tweed. I understand that tenders have been called for. That is positive news for Tweed families.</para><para>Tweed Hospital has the second busiest emergency ward in New South Wales outside of Sydney. Our community—from the elderly to young families—relies on Tweed's emergency department. The government's changes to bulk-billing have meant that it is harder than ever to find a bulk-billing doctor. This means that people are forced into the emergency department of the local hospital, particularly in the case of elderly people on fixed incomes. Some simply cannot afford to get sick. That is why an after-hours clinic is so important; it will provide a bulk-billing doctor to take the pressure off our local emergency ward.</para><para>Another major concern of elderly people in my electorate is this government's decision to cut the Commonwealth dental scheme. The minister for health himself has said in relation to Labor's dental health scheme, and I quote:</para><quote><para>The Keating government's program did reduce waiting times, no doubt about that ...</para></quote><para>If he agrees that this system worked, why doesn't he restore the funding to public dental health his government tore out nine years ago? There are only about 240 public dentists to cater for more than 2.5 million health care card holders, children and the elderly. This compares with more than 3,000 private dentists to treat the rest of the population. I have met many elderly people who were unable to eat solid foods because their teeth were so bad and they were unable to see a dentist. The government cannot wash their hands of this crisis. Providing public dental care is an obligation that this government have failed to meet.</para><para>I agree with the member for Moncrieff, who said on Monday that our public dental scheme was third world. I agree because I have seen first-hand elderly people in pain and waiting for a dentist. In Australia in 2005 this should not happen. Again, it shows a complete lack of respect and a disregard for the needs of elderly Australians. Public dentists are doing everything they can; they just are not getting the support they need from this government. It seems that the Prime Minster and the minister for health are content to leave elderly Australians with severe dental problems to suffer. They are not training enough dentists to meet the demand and they are not providing the support that public dentists need to meet the demands of their patients. This is not something that the government should be allowed to ignore. Public dentists provide an invaluable service to our community. This government have an obligation to meet the dental health needs of our community. They are simply not meeting that obligation.</para><para>The care of veterans in our community is also an important issue in my electorate. A number of veterans have contacted me recently concerned about the indexation of payments for veterans who are totally or partially incapacitated. This is an important issue for all veterans who served in the world wars, Vietnam or in more recent campaigns. I am particularly concerned about this issue because a number of veterans who live in my electorate are being unfairly treated. The issue arises because the TPI payment is indexed only partially to male average weekly earnings. Other pensions and payments are indexed fully. This means that people receiving an aged pension or unemployment benefits are, in a sense, better off than our veterans </para><para>The Prime Minister and Minister for Veterans' Affairs never miss an opportunity to talk about their respect for veterans and the contribution they have made to our country. But, as the saying goes, actions speak louder than words. These veterans were injured so badly defending our nation that they can no longer work. It is only right and fair that the government provide adequately for them. The government's refusal to index these payments fairly means that the livelihoods of these veterans are slowly eroding. The federal government's bandaid solution of partial indexation has slowed the erosion, but it will not stop it completely. These men and women served our nation with distinction. The federal government's blatant disregard of the needs of veterans is absolutely appalling. Our veterans deserve better from the federal government. They do not expect any more than what is fair; and that is precisely what they should get. I call on the Prime Minister and veterans' affairs minister to act immediately to rectify this gross injustice.</para><para>Our elderly Australians deserve to be taken care of properly. The contribution they have made to our community is one we should all be grateful for. We can show that gratitude by taking care of them well. This government has taken elderly Australians for granted for far too long. This issue is about showing a basic level of respect for the contributions of elderly Australians—and the government should be working to find solutions to these problems instead of just watching from the sidelines.</para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>13:55:00</time.stamp><page.no>70</page.no><name role="metadata">Baldwin, Robert, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BALDWIN</name><name.id>LL6</name.id><electorate>Paterson</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I rise today to speak on the <inline ref="R2279">Appropriation Bill (No. 3) 2004-2005</inline>. In the five minutes afforded to me this afternoon prior to question time, I would like to focus on the issue of roads in the electorate of Paterson. I was awoken this morning by one of my media outlets that informed me that last night there was, yet again, a serious smash on the Tea Gardens turn-off on the Pacific Highway. Work is under way now—thanks to the Minister for Local Government, Territories and Roads, Mr Lloyd, who provided support and assistance—to upgrade the Pacific Highway between Karuah and the Viney Creek turn-off. One of the key issues in the development of this road, planned for by the New South Wales state government, is that there has been absolutely no allowance for a flyover.</para></talk.start><para>The accident occurred last night simply because a vehicle had to go across the oncoming traffic, which was only doing 90 kilometres an hour. There was a collision and a person is now in a serious condition in hospital. As this road is upgraded we are going to see vehicles travelling past this intersection at 110 kilometres an hour. If a car is travelling with a caravan attached—because the Hawks Nest-Tea Gardens area is an extremely popular tourist destination—canvassing a vehicle with a caravan on the back in front of vehicles doing 110 an hour defies any logical stance on safety. I will be writing to Mr Costa this week urging him, as the new roads minister in New South Wales, to have a look at this intersection. Communities in my electorate such as North Arm Cove, Tea Gardens and Hawks Nest are up in arms at the state of the planning for this road.</para><para>Prior to the election, I had Minister Lloyd up to see the commencement of works at Nabiac. That is a section of road from Bundacree Creek right through to Nabiac. There is supposed to be a community consultative group for issues pertaining to these roadworks. The state government has established these community consultative groups in name only because each and every time these community groups go to meet with the RTA they meet a stonewall approach. I believe it is time that the planners and developers who look at this road infrastructure in New South Wales, the RTA, take into serious consideration the accident rates that occur when you do not have a flyover in place. Every time I hear of an accident or a fatality on these roads in my electorate it drives straight through me because I can feel the pain of those who are left behind and suffering. I urge the state government in New South Wales to seriously reconsider the planning approach that it takes to the upgrading of the highway, and in particular the approach it takes to flyovers in the region. </para><para>We were very fortunate during the election that the Prime Minister decided to invest an additional $10 million in roadworks in Paterson. This road work will include the works between Dungog and Raymond Terrace and an area on Lakes Way near the Seal Rocks turn-off. We were caught out by the state government in the 2001 election when we committed $20 million to the Bucketts Way. We expected that the New South Wales Labor government would do the honourable thing and match the $20 million that we were investing on a state road. They did not. So the $10 million that we have committed to these roads in the Paterson shire has a riding clause that it must be matched by the New South Wales government. We will wait and see whether they treat roadworks and motorists' safety as a priority.</para><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—Order! It being 2 p.m. the debate is interrupted in accordance with standing order 97. The debate may resume at a later hour. The member will have leave to continue speaking when the debate is resumed.</para></talk.start></interjection></speech></subdebate.1></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>MINISTERIAL ARRANGEMENTS</title><type>Ministerial Arrangements</type><page.no>71</page.no></debateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:00:00</time.stamp><page.no>71</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HOWARD</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I inform the House that the Treasurer will be absent from question time today.</para></talk.start><para><inline font-weight="bold">Opposition members</inline>—Oh!</para><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>ZD4</name.id><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HOWARD</name></talker><para>—I know you miss him; I know you do, and he misses you. We all miss him. He is attending the annual Treasury-Finance portfolio discussions in New Zealand. In the Treasurer's absence I will answer questions on his behalf.</para></talk.start></continue></speech></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>QUESTIONS WITHOUT NOTICE</title><type>Questions Without Notice</type><page.no>71</page.no></debateinfo><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>National Water Initiative</title><page.no>71</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:00:00</time.stamp><page.no>71</page.no><name role="metadata">Beazley, Kim, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BEAZLEY</name><name.id>PE4</name.id><electorate>Brand</electorate><party>ALP</party><role>Leader of the Opposition</role><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I suppose the real question is: does the Prime Minister miss him?</para></talk.start><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The Leader of the Opposition will get to his question.</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>PE4</name.id><name role="display">Mr BEAZLEY</name></talker><para>—My question is to the Prime Minister. I refer the Prime Minister to the National Water Initiative, agreed at the COAG meeting in Canberra on 25 June 2004. Can the Prime Minister advise the House of the rationale behind his commitment at that meeting to the application of full cost recovery pricing for water in both urban and rural sectors? Has there been any change to that rationale? Has that caused the Commonwealth to review its commitment to the principle of full cost recovery? If so, what is the nature of that change and what is the government's position in relation to full cost recovery for water?</para></talk.start></continue></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>72</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HOWARD</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—That is a very technical and well-researched question and I will do my very best, without any notice, to answer it. The National Water Initiative is the greatest single initiative to address the problem of water shortage in our country for generations. I welcome the fact that at last we have an expression of commitment to that initiative from a political leader from Western Australia because, when the initiative was signed, the Premier of Western Australia, Dr Gallop, held out and thereby denied to the farmers of Western Australia the opportunity to participate. The Leader of the Opposition asks me specifically why a provision relating to full cost recovery was included. I would, in addition to what I am about to say, examine the papers relating to that decision to see if there were further things, but I would have thought, if we are to have any kind of hope of dealing with the problem of water shortages in this country, we have got to in the future send more accurate market signals. </para></talk.start></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Kyoto Protocol</title><page.no>72</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:03:00</time.stamp><page.no>72</page.no><name role="metadata">Turnbull, Malcolm, MP</name><name role="display">Mr TURNBULL</name><name.id>885</name.id><electorate>Wentworth</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is addressed to the Minister for Foreign Affairs. Would the minister inform the House whether the Kyoto protocol will be effective in reducing greenhouse gas emissions? Is the minister aware of any alternative views?</para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>72</page.no><name role="metadata">Downer, Alexander, MP</name><name role="display">Mr DOWNER</name><name.id>4G4</name.id><electorate>Mayo</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Minister for Foreign Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I thank the member for Wentworth for his question. I know he and most members—probably all members—of this House share the view that climate change is an issue that has to be addressed. The international community needs to address this issue. But it is the view of this government that the problem with the Kyoto protocol is that it does not address the problem. If you actually look at what the Kyoto protocol is intended to achieve, it is intended to reduce global emissions by just one per cent below what they would have otherwise been within the target period. In other words, emissions will still be some 40 per cent higher in 2010 than they would have been in 1990. I think, if the public and the international community were aware of this, they would be less enthusiastic about Kyoto. The international community is right: the issue of climate change must be addressed. But Kyoto is not addressing it.</para></talk.start><para>The Kyoto protocol has set targets—but how are countries going in meeting those targets? Of the countries with targets, at the moment the current projection is that Canada will be 25 per cent above its target. Yes, it has ratified the Kyoto protocol, but it will be 25 per cent above its Kyoto target. Japan will be 13 per cent above it; Denmark, a member of the European Union, will be 38 per cent above its Kyoto target; and Ireland, 27 per cent. If you take all 25 countries in the European Union at the moment, the projection is that they will be some eight per cent overshooting their target.</para><para>The point here is: if the Kyoto protocol is such a great idea, why is it doing nothing to address climate change? Our answer to that is that in this country we are spending $1.8 billion to address this issue and we are on target—we are on, if you like, our Kyoto target. So, whilst we do not believe in the Kyoto process for very good reason, because the Kyoto process is not working and is not workable, nevertheless we are able to make a substantial contribution ourselves to addressing this issue. It is the view of this government that the international community needs to get together and work through ideas which will seriously address this problem, not resort to the sort of stuntsmanship that we have seen from the opposition on this issue over the last few days, and ensure that the international community is driven more by substantial policy outcomes than the mere symbolism which is all that Kyoto amounts to.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Economy: Interest Rates</title><page.no>73</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:06:00</time.stamp><page.no>73</page.no><name role="metadata">Beazley, Kim, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BEAZLEY</name><name.id>PE4</name.id><electorate>Brand</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is to the Prime Minister. Does the Prime Minister recall his comments during the election at the opening of the Gladesville campaign office when he said:</para></talk.start><quote><para>Well we're certainly, first and foremost, we're offering a continuation of the low interest rates of the last eight and a half years. </para></quote><para>With markets now anticipating a 0.5 per cent increase in rates, won't your government's failure to deliver the continuation of current interest rates add $148 to the monthly repayments of new home buyers in Sydney?</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>73</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HOWARD</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—No.</para></talk.start></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Western Australia: Economy</title><page.no>73</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:07:00</time.stamp><page.no>73</page.no><name role="metadata">Henry, Stuart, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HENRY</name><name.id>E0L</name.id><electorate>Hasluck</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is addressed to the Prime Minister. Would the Prime Minister advise the House of recent developments in the Western Australian economy? Are there any risks to Western Australia's economic outlook?</para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>73</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HOWARD</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I thank the member for Hasluck for his question. I can report that Western Australia, being part of Australia, has enjoyed the wonderful economic conditions of the last nine years. I think it is fair to say that, whenever the national economy of Australia performs well, the premiers of Australia—whatever their political stripe may be—try to claim credit for the economic growth in their own states. But the reality is that the federal government is responsible for the economic health of this country. That means, when the national economy is doing badly, the federal government is to blame, and, when the national economy is doing well, the federal government is entitled to take some of the credit. So it is with the economy of Western Australia.</para></talk.start><para>I have noticed with interest in the current election campaign that the Western Australian Premier is asking the people of Western Australia to re-elect him on the grounds of the strength of the Western Australian economy. Without in any way denigrating the contribution of those Australians who live in Western Australia, let me say that the strength of the Western Australian economy—which is undoubted—is due overwhelmingly to the economic policies of the coalition government, just as the strength of the Queensland economy, the strength of the New South Wales economy, the strength of the South Australian economy and the strength of the Tasmanian economy are.</para><para>The message that I would like to convey is that Western Australia could be doing even better if it had a state government that followed policies that were more supportive of the national government in a number of important areas. Let us take the very important area of industrial relations. The rate of working days lost in Western Australia due to industrial disputes has trebled since the year 2001. By June 2004 Western Australia's rate of 121 working days lost per thousand employees was almost twice the national average of 67. It is right to say, as Western Australian premiers of both political complexions have said to me over the years, that Western Australia may have only 11 per cent of the population but it contributes 28 per cent of the export income of the nation. It is also fair to say that there is no reason that Western Australia cannot have an industrial record the equal of the national average and the equal of the best that is achieved around Australia. That can happen if Western Australia has a change of state government.</para><para>Let me say of the alternative Premier of Western Australia, Colin Barnett, whom I know well, that he is rightly making an issue in this campaign of taking decisions and not dithering about decisions being taken by government because, as minister for resources and energies in the 1990s, for example, he was the driving force behind the Dampier to Perth gas pipeline. I know that that is an example of the kind of focus that he will be able to bring to the government of that wonderful state if he is elected Premier on 26 February.</para></answer></subdebate.1></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>DISTINGUISHED VISITORS</title><type>Distinguished Visitors</type><page.no>74</page.no></debateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:11:00</time.stamp><page.no>74</page.no><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name><name.id>10000</name.id><electorate>PO</electorate><party>N/A</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I inform the House that we have present in the gallery this afternoon His Excellency Mr Gran Persson, Prime Minister of Sweden, accompanied by Her Excellency Mrs Karin Ehnbom-Palmquist, the Swedish Ambassador. On behalf of the House, I extend a very warm welcome to our visitors. </para></talk.start><para><inline font-weight="bold">Honourable members</inline>—Hear, hear!</para></speech></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>QUESTIONS WITHOUT NOTICE</title><type>Questions Without Notice</type><page.no>74</page.no></debateinfo><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Economy: International Monetary Fund</title><page.no>74</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:11:00</time.stamp><page.no>74</page.no><name role="metadata">Beazley, Kim, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BEAZLEY</name><name.id>PE4</name.id><electorate>Brand</electorate><party>ALP</party><role>Leader of the Opposition</role><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is to the Prime Minister. I think the Prime Minister will find that Western Australians think they are responsible for Western Australia's prosperity, and they may well tell him that when he goes there.</para></talk.start><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—I would ask the Leader of the Opposition to come to his question.</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>PE4</name.id><name role="display">Mr BEAZLEY</name></talker><para>—But my question to the Prime Minister is not about that. I ask the Prime Minister if he is concerned by the IMF's recent warning:</para></talk.start></continue><quote><para>... the new package unveiled in the 2004 Budget could pose some risk to the medium-term outlook. ... The mission noted that the short-term stimulatory effect ... could complicate monetary policy ...</para></quote><para>Does the Prime Minister agree with the IMF's view that the effect of his government's fiscal policy decisions has been to complicate monetary policy?</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>74</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HOWARD</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I have read a number of reports on the Australian economy in recent years, in recent months, in recent weeks, authored by bodies such as the IMF and the OECD. As the Leader of the Opposition knows, the totality of those reports indicates that the Australian economy is seen around the world as an outstanding example of reform and good performance.</para></talk.start></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Regional Services: Program Funding</title><page.no>74</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:12:00</time.stamp><page.no>74</page.no><name role="metadata">Randall, Don, MP</name><name role="display">Mr RANDALL</name><name.id>PK6</name.id><electorate>Canning</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is addressed to the Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Transport and Regional Services. Is the Deputy Prime Minister aware of media reports concerning announcements of Australian government funding in the electorate of Brand, in particular for a project to build a marina at Rockingham? What do these media reports show?</para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>74</page.no><name role="metadata">Anderson, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr ANDERSON</name><name.id>4K4</name.id><electorate>Gwydir</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Transport and Regional Services</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I thank the honourable member for Canning for his question. Yesterday in this place we established quite plainly that the Leader of the Opposition is quite a hypocrite when it comes to the Regional Partnerships program because what he has in essence been saying is this: `This is a program that should be shut down and everyone should give their money back, except in the case of the five grants in Brand,' because he supported them. He has made applications for them. He has told his electorate how hard he has been working to secure them. But in his embarrassment and in his desire to recapture some lost territory in this place, he flourished quite dramatically a swag of press clippings which purported to show that the government was abusing regional partnership announcements. It was not that Regional Partnerships was the problem any more; it was the way the government was using the announcements, specifically by having the Liberal Party candidate in Brand make these announcements in a way that was plainly meant to favour that candidate and which was demonstrating precisely how the government was `using these rorts as opportunities to create bogus local reputations for their candidates'.</para></talk.start><para>Nine of these clippings were tabled by the Leader of the Opposition yesterday, and overnight I have had a chance to look at them. I must say there were quite a number of announcements. I was amazed to discover—if they were all made by Liberal Party candidates—that you had quite a number of Liberal Party candidates in the seat of Brand. There was funding under the Black Spots Program, the roads program, by the Liberal Party candidate for Brand, whose name is Senator Ian Campbell! He made that announcement. There was Regional Partnerships funding announced by the Liberal Party candidate for Brand, my then parliamentary secretary, De-Anne Kelly! Then we had a confiscated illegal fishing boat; the Liberal Party candidate for Canning made that announcement. And then Senator Ellison presented a cheque for the Rockingham marina—a Regional Partnerships grant. </para><para><inline font-style="italic">Opposition members interjecting—</inline></para><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—Order! Members on my left will come to order.</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>4K4</name.id><name role="display">Mr ANDERSON</name></talker><para>—The Leader of the Opposition's claim that these announcements had all been made by the Liberal Party candidate in that seat is absolutely wrong. Only one announcement was made in all of these press reports by the candidate. The announcement was that he would be resigning from the marina project because he was about to become the candidate. That is the only announcement made in all of the material the opposition tabled yesterday. The Leader of the Opposition owes that candidate an apology for the claim that he was trying to establish a bogus reputation.</para></talk.start></continue><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>LS4</name.id><name role="metadata">Ferguson, Martin, MP</name><name role="display"></name></talker></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The member for Batman is warned!</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>4K4</name.id><name role="display">Mr ANDERSON</name></talker><para>—That candidate was the founder and president of the Rockingham Marina Action Group, the treasurer of the Cruising Yacht Club of Rockingham, the chairman for marketing and promotion for Tourism Rockingham, and the co-founder of the West Coast Dive Action Group. He did not need a bogus local reputation; he is a man of real standing in the area. He is owed an apology by the Leader of the Opposition and, I tell you this, so is the Leader of the Opposition's own party because of his hypocrisy in this matter. He has led them to believe that he thinks this program should be closed down. He plainly does not. He thinks it should be strongly supported, because he has been out there actively campaigning for support under the program in the electorate of Brand.</para></talk.start></continue></answer></subdebate.1></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>DISTINGUISHED VISITORS</title><type>Distinguished Visitors</type><page.no>75</page.no></debateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:18:00</time.stamp><page.no>75</page.no><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name><name.id>10000</name.id><electorate>PO</electorate><party>N/A</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I inform the House that we have present in the gallery this afternoon 100 students enrolled in the Australia and New Zealand School of Government inaugural Executive Master of Public Administration degree. One of the students is the House Serjeant-at-Arms, Mr David Elder. On behalf of the House I extend a very warm welcome to the students.</para></talk.start><para><inline font-weight="bold">Honourable members</inline>—Hear, hear!</para></speech></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>QUESTIONS WITHOUT NOTICE</title><type>Questions Without Notice</type><page.no>75</page.no></debateinfo><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Economy</title><page.no>75</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:18:00</time.stamp><page.no>75</page.no><name role="metadata">Beazley, Kim, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BEAZLEY</name><name.id>PE4</name.id><electorate>Brand</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I wish I had not asked the last question, but I will ask this one. My question is to the Prime Minister. Does the Prime Minister recall the following comments made by the shadow Treasurer from this dispatch box in September 1995:</para></talk.start><quote><para>Australia has high foreign debt and because Australia has a current account problem, that puts premium on Australian borrowings, that flows through and every Australian pays for the consequences.</para></quote><para>Does the Prime Minister agree with his Treasurer that a high current account deficit and foreign debt will result in a premium on interest rates, especially in light of the Reserve Bank's warning last week that the current account deficit could hit 6 per cent of GDP in the December quarter?</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>76</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HOWARD</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I must confess that I do not specifically recall that, but I will not argue with the Leader of the Opposition as to whether those words were actually uttered; but as to what the context of that may have been I would have to have a look. Let me address the issue of debt. I think we are all aware that at various stages in our existence, whether as a nation, as individuals or as companies, we have debt. The question of the size of that debt and the manageability of that debt is determined by our capacity to service that debt. One of the products of the sparkling performance of the Australian economy over the last few years is that our capacity to service foreign debt has increased dramatically. One of the reasons that our capacity has increased spectacularly is the volume of government debt. Bear in mind that the foreign debt, which the Leader of the Opposition is undoubtedly alluding to, is of course largely the debt of individuals and corporations. </para></talk.start><para>The government itself has made a tremendous contribution towards reducing the government's contribution to debt. In fact, at 3.9 per cent of GDP, name me a developed country in the world that has a lower proportion to GDP of government debt than Australia. The OECD average is about 45 to 50 per cent; in the United States it is about 45 per cent; in Japan I think it is over 100 per cent; and ours is 3.9 per cent. That is due to the fact that when the government came to office and inherited a budget deficit of $10½ billion from the Leader of the Opposition, who was the outgoing finance minister, this government, despite the attempts of the Labor Party and others in the Senate to frustrate its budget reduction program, set about not only getting rid of that $10½ billion but also accumulating surpluses and paying off debt. That is one of the reasons why this country is in such a strong economic position. I warmly thank the Leader of the Opposition for the question.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Indigenous Affairs: Health</title><page.no>76</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:21:00</time.stamp><page.no>76</page.no><name role="metadata">Tollner, David, MP</name><name role="display">Mr TOLLNER</name><name.id>00AN4</name.id><electorate>Solomon</electorate><party>CLP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is to the Minister for Health and Ageing. Would the minister inform the House how government is protecting Indigenous communities from the dangers of petrol sniffing?</para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>76</page.no><name role="metadata">Abbott, Tony, MP</name><name role="display">Mr ABBOTT</name><name.id>EZ5</name.id><electorate>Warringah</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Minister for Health and Ageing</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—Petrol sniffing is a serious problem. It has claimed far too many Indigenous lives, and I thank the member for Solomon for his question and for the concern he has to promote better Indigenous health in communities in the Territory. In 1998 the Commonwealth introduced a special scheme to substitute aviation fuel for normal petrol in remote Indigenous communities to help combat the problem of petrol sniffing. Because aviation fuel did not contain aromatic hydrocarbons, it was not attractive to sniffers. But as a result of environmental changes avgas has now become unleaded. It will contain aromatic hydrocarbons and therefore it is no longer an effective substitute for use in communities which are prone to petrol sniffing.</para></talk.start><para>I am very pleased to say that BP Australia has now developed a special type of unleaded fuel without any aromatic hydrocarbons, specially designed for use in remote Indigenous communities. I am pleased to say that, thanks to this, the government will continue to spend $1 million a year supplying unsniffable fuel to remote communities where petrol sniffing is a potential problem. Because of this, the government will be able to continue to work with community leaders in the fight against petrol sniffing. It is a very important fight. This has claimed 100 Indigenous lives since 1981. It needs to be continued and it will be continued thanks to this government and the good work of BP Australia.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Iraq</title><page.no>77</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:24:00</time.stamp><page.no>77</page.no><name role="metadata">McClelland, Robert, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McCLELLAND</name><name.id>JK6</name.id><electorate>Barton</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is to the Prime Minister. Is the Prime Minister now aware of evidence given during Senate estimates yesterday that Mr Rod Barton advised senior Defence officials in March, April, May and June last year that he had `interviewed' prisoners in Iraq and expressed in writing his concerns about the possible abuse of detainees and further recommended that `Australia should not be involved in the interview process'? Prime Minister, on what basis, therefore, do you stand by the credibility of your defence minister when he told the Senate on 16 June last year that his statement to the Senate, omitting those crucial details, was `the most complete picture Defence can provide on its knowledge to date on this issue'? </para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>77</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HOWARD</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I am aware, broadly and in some areas in some detail, of the evidence given. I am also aware of the very clear distinction that is apparent in the Army's manual between interviews and interrogations. I have followed the comments that have been made by the member for Barton on this subject and I have also followed the comments of Mr Neil James, the head of the Australian Defence Association—a former intelligence officer and a lieutenant colonel in the Australian Army. I quote from what he said last night on the <inline font-style="italic">PM</inline> program:</para></talk.start><quote><para>So what he—</para></quote><para>namely, Mr Barton—</para><quote><para>was in effect doing was he was questioning someone inside a facility that ... was used for detailed interrogation. But his questioning of that subject was by no means an interrogation.</para></quote><para>That is from somebody who was an intelligence officer. With the greatest of respect to the member for Barton, whom I do respect, Mr James knows a little more about this subject than the member for Barton has indicated with his comments. The reality is that within the military there is a clear understanding of this distinction. It comes out in the manual. I do stand by my minister and I think he has been unfairly, wrongly and quite disgracefully criticised by the opposition on this issue.</para><para>Let us get to the essence of this issue. The essence of this issue is that at no stage last year when we were talking about Abu Ghraib was there any evidence of substance—any evidence at all—that Australians had been involved in prisoner abuse. The whole exercise last year was designed, however indirectly, to create a different impression. The Leader of the Opposition knows this and those who sit on the front bench know this. Frankly, I think there are a growing number of Australians who are sick and tired of this endeavour to spear people who are trying to do an honest job on behalf of this country. They are getting sick and tired of it.</para><para>Obviously it is impossible for the defence minister or the Prime Minister, whether you have a Labor government or a Liberal government, to know the minutiae of everything that takes place in a theatre of conflict. We have to rely on the information that is provided to us by the defence department. I think the Defence people have done their level best to provide accurate information to the Senate, accurate information to ministers and accurate information to me. There is a difference between interrogation and interview. That is clearly spelled out in the military manual. It is understood by Lieutenant Colonel James. It is understood by the military officers who gave evidence to the Senate estimates committee yesterday. It ought to be understood by the Leader of the Opposition, who is a former defence minister, and it should now be understood by the member for Barton.</para><para>This exercise we have had over the past few days has been a nitpicking attempt to damage the political reputation of the Minister for Defence. I can understand that it is the mission of an opposition to damage the political reputation of their opponents, but in the process they have made unreasonable, unfair and inaccurate remarks about members of the Australian Defence Force. That is something that I am certainly opposed to and that is something that this side of the House will never defend and never support and never condone. </para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Trade: Exports</title><page.no>78</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:28:00</time.stamp><page.no>78</page.no><name role="metadata">Neville, Paul, MP</name><name role="display">Mr NEVILLE</name><name.id>KV5</name.id><electorate>Hinkler</electorate><party>NATS</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is addressed to the Minister for Trade. Would the minister update the House on the growth in Australia's resources exports? What is the Australian government doing to assist exporters?</para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>78</page.no><name role="metadata">Vaile, Mark, MP</name><name role="display">Mr VAILE</name><name.id>SU5</name.id><electorate>Lyne</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Trade</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I thank the member for Hinkler for his question and recognise his long representation in his electorate. The port of Gladstone, in particular, is one of the foremost export ports in Australia for bulk products, particularly from the resources sector. The member for Hinkler would know that that port is owned and operated by the Queensland government, along with a number of others in Queensland.</para></talk.start><para>In answer to the member's question, the value of Australia's resources exports rose by 13 per cent in 2004 to a figure of almost $40 billion, which is the second highest level on record in Australia for the resources sector. A significant proportion of that was our coal exports, leading the way with growth in value. They grew by 24 per cent in 2004. This certainly is a remarkable performance as far as the resources sector is concerned. It sustains the livelihood of many people and of course a lot of the work force in the electorate of the member for Hinkler, particularly in Gladstone, which, by the way, returned the member for Hinkler with a very comfortable majority. It is a very wise electorate.</para><para>The Minerals Council has estimated that the resources sector is proposing to invest about $8.2 billion in 2004-05. A lot of that is going to be going into improvements in infrastructure across Australia in terms of getting those exports from their source out of the country to our export markets. Along with what our government is doing, particularly through programs like AusLink where we are set to invest $12½ billion over five years in Australia's road and rail infrastructure, it is all going towards developing the logistical supply chain to match the needs in the marketplace and the ability of our exports sector to deliver to those needs in the marketplace.</para><para>You might ask what the state governments across Australia are doing. What are the states doing, the people that control a lot of the export ports across Australia? We know what the Queensland state government is not doing. They are not investing in infrastructure, but they are collecting massive amounts of royalties from our resources sector. The Queensland government has forecast that it will receive around $800 million in royalties in 2004-05 from our resources exports. It is also forecast that that may even go through the billion dollar mark being collected by the Queensland government. Yet they will not invest any money back into the much needed infrastructure to accommodate the growth in the export of resources out of that state. They will not even fund a 70-kilometre rail link, worth around $100 million, to Abbott Point, which would immediately alleviate the bottleneck that currently exists at Dalrymple Bay, an issue that the Treasurer spoke about yesterday.</para><para>One of the local mayors in Queensland, the Mayor of Bowen, who wants to see this investment take place, said about the Queensland government: `It is just a matter of someone pulling their finger out and getting on with it.' We agree with him. The Queensland government should get on with investing in assets that will help our exporters get their product out, instead of living off the infrastructure that was invested by previous Queensland governments, particularly the Bjelke-Petersen government, over the last 30 years. They should stop loafing on that, join the Australian government and industry and invest in what we need to enhance our export infrastructure for the future. </para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Iraq</title><page.no>79</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:33:00</time.stamp><page.no>79</page.no><name role="metadata">Beazley, Kim, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BEAZLEY</name><name.id>PE4</name.id><electorate>Brand</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is to the Prime Minister and follows his answer to the previous question from the honourable member for Barton. Does the Prime Minister accept that obtaining information even from a willing individual falls within the military's own definition of `interrogate', which is: `the systematic extraction of information from an individual either willing or unwilling'. Why, then, on 28 May last year when discussing Iraq on the Neil Mitchell program did the Prime Minister state, `We weren't involved in any interrogations'? Isn't this another example of the government's distortion of the meaning of words in order to keep the true facts from the Australian people and undermine honourable defence personnel like Mr Rod Barton?</para></talk.start><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>4G4</name.id><name role="metadata">Downer, Alexander, MP</name><name role="display"></name></talker></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—Order! The Minister for Foreign Affairs.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>4G4</name.id><name role="metadata">Downer, Alexander, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Downer</name></talker><para>—General Cosgrove is a liar: that is what you are saying.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—Order! The Minister for Foreign Affairs is warned.</para></talk.start></interjection></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>79</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HOWARD</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I thank the Leader of the Opposition for the question. The essence of the question, I think, is that there really is no difference between interrogation and interviewing. That, I think, is a fair representation of what he is putting. Particularly in the context of military operations, I do not accept that. The Australian military forces do not accept that and Neil James, who is the original author of the ADF interrogation manual, does not accept that either. Speaking on the <inline font-style="italic">PM</inline> program last night he had a number of things to say about the difference between interrogation and interview. He said:</para></talk.start><quote><para>The rough working definition is simply ... you're free to get up and leave. In an interrogation you are not. There's some form of legal or criminal or physical restriction.</para><para>Generally speaking in most situations there's a clear-cut difference between what's an interview and what's an interrogation.</para></quote><para>The opposition defence spokesman, the member for Barton, yesterday in contradistinction, when he was asked whether he thought there was an argument in the distinction between terms of interrogation and debriefing—and bear in mind that the expression `debrief' is being used interchangeably with the expression `interview'—replied:</para><quote><para>No there is not ... They have used a highly technical definition. Even on the basis of that highly technical definition there was unquestionably interrogation.</para></quote><para>That is the view of the member for Barton and he may hold that view and he is entitled to hold that view. But what I am putting in all seriousness to the opposition is that that is not the view of the Australian military. It is not the view of the head of the Defence Association. It was not the view of the head of military operations in Iraq who commissioned the circumstances under which people would participate in the Iraq Survey Group, and it was clearly not the view of the defence department when they provided advice to both the defence minister and to me last year. This all arises out of an attempt by the opposition to allege that in some way the defence minister and I and others in the government have misled the parliament and the Australian public.</para><para>We have done no such thing. At all stages in relation to this we have been absolutely candid. The people who are trying to distort the language, with great respect, are those who are speaking for the opposition, because they are refusing to accept what I do and what I believe most people who have examined it will do: that in the military context there is a clear distinction between an interview and an interrogation. It is spelt out in an Australian Army manual. So if it was meaningless and if we were just playing with words, why would it be spelt out in an Australian Army manual? </para><para>I say again: we have the head of the Defence Association, a former intelligence officer, who has said it very clearly. And I make no comments about Mr Barton—he is entitled to his view—but the reality is that when he signed the questionnaire that was sent out last year, the word he used was `interview'. He is a person who quintessentially was in a much better position to know the difference between `interrogation' and `interview' than I was, or the Leader of the Opposition or indeed anybody else, because he in fact had been commissioned as part of the Iraq Survey Group and he understood the terms of that commission and the terms of that engagement. He used the word `interview' when he answered the question last year. He did not use `interrogation'; he used `interview'. I suggest he did that because he then understood very clearly the distinction that existed between the two concepts, as Lieutenant Colonel James understands it, as Barton's commanding officer understands it and as I know the Leader of the Opposition understands it. Anybody who has studied the manual will understand the difference. There is a difference in Australian military parlance between the two concepts. And when that is understood, any suggestion that Senator Hill has misled the Australian public on this issue is completely false.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Education: School Standards</title><page.no>80</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:39:00</time.stamp><page.no>80</page.no><name role="metadata">Draper, Trish, MP</name><name role="display">Mrs DRAPER</name><name.id>0L6</name.id><electorate>Makin</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is addressed to the Minister for Education, Science and Training. Would the minister update the House on the government's plans for improving standards and consistency in schools across Australia?</para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>80</page.no><name role="metadata">Nelson, Dr Brendan, MP</name><name role="display">Dr NELSON</name><name.id>RW5</name.id><electorate>Bradfield</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Minister for Education, Science and Training</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I thank the member for Makin for her question and her very strong support for the government's initiatives to drive national consistency and high nationally consistent standards in Australian schooling. One of the many initiatives announced by the government during the recent election campaign was that we will move to develop and establish an Australian certificate of education which could be undertaken by students across Australia as an alternative to the conventional year 12 examinations conducted in eight different jurisdictions.</para></talk.start><para>I will shortly be calling for tenders for appropriate organisations to develop the model, which would be based on four things. The first is that we can drive consistency amongst the eight different jurisdictions at the moment in terms of year 12 assessment and make sure that we have a common test across Australia. Alternatively, the Australian certificate of education could be based on a national curriculum based assessment. Thirdly, it could take the form of a student aptitude test, which is currently applied quite successfully across the United States of America. Alternatively, it has been suggested that the Australian certificate of education could be based on the template of the international baccalaureate, which is currently being undertaken by 20,000 Australian students throughout schools because, increasingly, parents and teachers and students are frustrated and looking for a nationally and internationally recognised and consistent qualification.</para><para>No sooner had I announced the detail in relation to this than the Deputy Leader of the Opposition issued a media release on 7 February this year which described this move for national consistency and the certificate of education in the following terms: absurd, meaningless, nonsense, bureaucratic nightmare—and so on it goes. So obviously at least the Labor Party is consistent in criticising anything which drives national consistency and high quality in standards. Then I thought, no, not everybody in the Labor Party could think that way. Then I recalled that, slipped among my Christmas cards on Christmas Eve, was a letter that I had received from one of the Labor MPs. This one, rather than being the typical one you get from the Labor backbench wilderness, was indeed from the front bench. </para><para>The letter read in part: `Dear Minister, I write on behalf of a certain school located in my electorate. The school is interested in offering the international baccalaureate course to interested students. Indeed the school is collaborating with two other schools on the development of an international baccalaureate pilot program. Currently, government schools in Victoria are not allowed to offer such a course. However, in order to pilot the international baccalaureate some funding would be required. I would be grateful for your indication as to whether such a program would be considered for funding under the Howard government's Investing in our Schools program.' That, as the Prime Minister knows, is the $1 billion that this government is investing to cut through constipated educational bureaucracies to support things that are desperately needed at the school level. The letter goes on: `I would also be grateful if you would consider allocating time when you are in Melbourne to meet with representatives with the schools who are interested in this new development in public education. I look forward to your reply.'</para><para>I am sure that Julia Gillard, member for Lalor, shadow minister for health and alternate Deputy Leader of the Opposition, will look forward to my reply. My reply is that I look forward to meeting those schools. And I ask the member for Lalor: why don't we jointly write to the Deputy Leader of the Opposition and she can come along to the meeting too? It would be a lovely meeting, and the Deputy Leader of the Opposition can actually listen to what parents are saying. They have had it up to here with inconsistent national standards and they are sick and tired of educational ideologues in education departments telling them what they know is not in the interests of their children.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Iraq</title><page.no>81</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:43:00</time.stamp><page.no>81</page.no><name role="metadata">Rudd, Kevin, MP</name><name role="display">Mr RUDD</name><name.id>83T</name.id><electorate>Griffith</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is to the Prime Minister. I refer to his answer to our previous question. Does the Prime Minister recall the following statement by Mr Rod Barton:</para></talk.start><quote><para>... someone was brought to me in an orange jumpsuit with a guard with a gun standing behind him and, all right, you can call it what you wish ...</para></quote><para>He continues:</para><quote><para>I believe it was an interrogation. The Iraqis regarded it as interrogation, interrogations. The Americans I think regarded it as interrogation.</para><para>It wasn't just a simple interview ...</para></quote><para>Is the Prime Minister saying that Mr Barton has told a lie in this statement?</para><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The honourable the Prime Minister will answer that question but I think the last statement did not add anything to the question. Would the honourable member for Griffith like to rephrase that last part of the question?</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>83T</name.id><name role="display">Mr RUDD</name></talker><para>—Does the Prime Minister accept the accuracy of Mr Barton's statement that I have just read to the House?</para></talk.start></continue></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>82</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HOWARD</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—At no stage have I accused Mr Barton of being a liar.</para></talk.start><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>83T</name.id><name role="metadata">Rudd, Kevin, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Rudd</name></talker><para>—You just did before.</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>ZD4</name.id><name role="display">Mr HOWARD</name></talker><para>—No, I do not accuse Mr Barton of being a liar. People can hold strong views about circumstances which are different from each other without either of them being a liar. I am not casting any aspersions on Mr Barton's character; I am going to the essence of this issue. The essence of this issue is that the Labor Party has tried to establish and continues to allege that the lying and the deception of the Australian public has come from the defence minister and myself. What I am doing is pointing out that there is a clear distinction between interrogation and interview in a military situation. </para></talk.start></continue><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>83T</name.id><name role="metadata">Rudd, Kevin, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Rudd</name></talker><para>—Were you there or was Mr Barton?</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>ZD4</name.id><name role="display">Mr HOWARD</name></talker><para>—I am glad the member for Griffith asked, `Was I there?' No, I was not. I thank the member for Griffith—that was one of his better interjections. Of course I was not there, and therefore I have to rely on the advice I receive from the defence department and I have to rely also on the analysis of experts. May I again return to Neil James. This is what he had to say in that very lengthy and very informative interview on <inline font-style="italic">PM</inline> last night:</para></talk.start></continue><quote><para>Rod Barton is a very distinguished biological warfare intelligence analyst.</para></quote><para>I have no argument with that; I am not suggesting he is not. I have not met him but I have no reason to denigrate his professional qualifications in that department, and I will not. James goes on to say:</para><quote><para>He's not a qualified interrogator. I don't know whether he's had any exposure to the interrogation process. But it's quite common for people with no understanding of the process, or little understanding of the process, to misunderstand the things they see and the safeguards employed.</para></quote><para>The question of whether Mr Barton believed then—which apparently he did not, because he described it last year as an interview—or he believes now does not alter the requirement that all of us make an objective analysis of what it was. To aid that objective analysis we must look at the military manual, which draws a clear distinction between an interrogation and an interview. That was the basis of the advice that Defence transmitted to Senator Hill last year. It remains the basis of Defence's advice and it is the basis of my claim that the attempt by the opposition to discredit the integrity of the Minister for Defence is completely false and completely dishonourable.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Insurance: Public Liability</title><page.no>82</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:48:00</time.stamp><page.no>82</page.no><name role="metadata">Ciobo, Steven, MP</name><name role="display">Mr CIOBO</name><name.id>00AN0</name.id><electorate>Moncrieff</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is addressed to the Minister for Revenue and Assistant Treasurer. Would the minister advise the House how the government's tort law reforms have improved the availability and affordability of public liability and professional indemnity insurance?</para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>82</page.no><name role="metadata">Brough, Mal, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BROUGH</name><name.id>2K6</name.id><electorate>Longman</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Minister for Revenue and Assistant Treasurer</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I understand how many members of this House have been concerned about how the increase in and availability of public liability insurance to so many local community groups put at risk the future of many events, such as country shows. I am pleased to inform the House that the ACCC has just released a report which shows that the premiums for public liability insurance and professional indemnity insurance have both fallen significantly. The report shows that the premiums for public liability insurance have fallen by 15 per cent in the six months to June 2004. This is very welcome news for the community. It means that community events that were at risk due to increased premiums will now be under less financial stress and, as a result, we have a better chance of these very important aspects of community life continuing to operate.</para></talk.start><para>The finding is also very welcome news for business and particularly small business who have to find the money for the public liability insurance premiums. These reductions will be very welcome by them. The report shows that professional indemnity insurance premiums have also fallen by 17 per cent in the six months to June 2004. This is after a number of increases in previous years. Whilst these lower premiums are welcome, the government realise there is more to be done, and we will have to monitor these prices over time to ensure they do not escalate. To that end, I have agreed that the ACCC continue to monitor prices and to make that information available in an annual report, and this will be done for next three years. The one major item of tort law reform that remains outstanding is the passing of the amendments to the Trade Practices Act which were stymied by the opposition in the Senate. We will be reintroducing that measure, and I call on the Labor Party to change their position to assist the government to keep downward pressure on insurance rates. </para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Regional Services: Program Funding</title><page.no>83</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:50:00</time.stamp><page.no>83</page.no><name role="metadata">McMullan, Bob, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McMULLAN</name><name.id>5I4</name.id><electorate>Fraser</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is to the Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Transport and Regional Services. Is it the case that the Tweed Shire Council mayor and local National Party electorate council chair was project officer of the Northern Rivers Dairy Regional Assistance Program and member of the Northern Rivers Area Consultative Committee? Can the Deputy Prime Minister confirm that the National Party mayor recommended an $88,000 dairy regional assistance grant to add farm-stay accommodation to the Tea Tree Farm of prominent National Party supporters John and Kathleen Corrocher?</para></talk.start><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>SE4</name.id><name role="metadata">Bishop, Bronwyn, MP</name><name role="display">Mrs Bronwyn Bishop</name></talker><para>—Mr Speaker, I rise on a point of order. Asking the question in that way is in total breach of the standing orders. Using the names was in no way necessary to convey the meaning of the question, and it was a deliberate slur on those people. He should be asked to withdraw.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>5I4</name.id><name role="metadata">McMullan, Bob, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McMullan</name></talker><para>—The standing orders make it clear that the names are necessary to make the question relevant or comprehensible. How on earth could I ask the Deputy Prime Minister to confirm something about which he did not know the details?</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The point of order raised by the member for Mackellar indicates, I think, that the member for Fraser included some material that was clearly unnecessary to make the question clear. Nonetheless, I believe the Deputy Prime Minister can answer it, because the thrust of the question is in order.</para></talk.start></interjection></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>83</page.no><name role="metadata">Anderson, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr ANDERSON</name><name.id>4K4</name.id><electorate>Gwydir</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Transport and Regional Services</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I have absolutely no idea as to the accuracy or nature of the member for Fraser's allegations. I will consult with the Minister for Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry, who was responsible for the administration of Dairy RAP. I presume the opposition is now going to smear Dairy RAP, a program which the federal government put in place to help the dairy farmers of this country when the states deregulated that industry—cold turkey—which resulted in enormous dislocation and economic and social trauma. But, as to the details of the allegations, I will consult with the Minister for Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry and report back to the House.</para></talk.start></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Education and Training: Apprenticeships</title><page.no>83</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:53:00</time.stamp><page.no>83</page.no><name role="metadata">Richardson, Kym, MP</name><name role="display">Mr RICHARDSON</name><name.id>E0B</name.id><electorate>Kingston</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is addressed to the Minister for Vocational and Technical Education. Will the minister advise the House how new apprenticeship centres are helping young people to get a start in the traditional trades?</para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>84</page.no><name role="metadata">Hardgrave, Gary, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HARDGRAVE</name><name.id>CK6</name.id><electorate>Moreton</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Minister for Vocational and Technical Education and Minister Assisting the Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I thank the member for Kingston. He would be interested to know that since 1996 there have been 530 new apprentices in training in his electorate, which is a 221 per cent increase. I urge the member to work hard to get an even better result over the years ahead. New apprenticeship centres, NACs—such as National Apprenticeship Services in Morphett Vale in his electorate—are contracted by the government to provide information and support, coordinate the relationships between apprentices and their employers and administer incentives for new apprenticeships. Over the last two years the number of new apprenticeship centres—an investment by this government in Australian apprenticeships—has increased from 300 to some 500 right around Australia. This year the government will spend more than $685 million on incentives paid directly to employers of new apprentices and on the provision of these support services. </para></talk.start><para>This support is absolutely essential. It is helping young people to get a start in traditional trades such as metal trades, motor trades, carpentry and plumbing. We have seen an 18 per cent increase in the number of those taking up those trades, which proves the success of the NACs. A recent survey which was commissioned by my department, to listen to people, found that employers and indeed their new apprentices are highly satisfied with the work done by the new apprenticeship centres. Nine out of every 10 employers surveyed indicated that they would use the same NAC again. In fact, 93.1 per cent said they would employ a new apprentice again in the future, which is exactly what the government wants to see Australian businesses doing. This is why the ongoing success of the government's many measures to deal with the growth of new apprentices in the Australian economy has grown training in Australia from a pitiful 141,000 apprentices in 1995 to around 400,000 today.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Regional Services: Program Funding</title><page.no>84</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>14:56:00</time.stamp><page.no>84</page.no><name role="metadata">Thomson, Kelvin, MP</name><name role="display">Mr KELVIN THOMSON</name><name.id>UK6</name.id><electorate>Wills</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is to the Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Transport and Regional Services. Can the minister explain the involvement of the Tweed Shire Council's National Party mayor and the former National Party member for Richmond in the grant of $273,000 of taxpayers' money to Seawind, a South Tweed seafood company that has subsequently gone bust? What financial probity checks did the minister make before approving the grant to Seawind to ensure that taxpayers' money would not be wasted?</para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>84</page.no><name role="metadata">Anderson, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr ANDERSON</name><name.id>4K4</name.id><electorate>Gwydir</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Transport and Regional Services</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I thank the honourable member for his question. In essence, it goes to the question of checking and establishing whether or not programs are worthy and whether they are going to make a difference in terms of jobs and local outcomes. In this particular case, the normal probity arrangements and checks would have been taken—I am sure of that—</para></talk.start><para><inline font-style="italic">Opposition members interjecting—</inline></para><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>4K4</name.id><name role="display">Mr ANDERSON</name></talker><para>—Occasionally, with the best will in the world, companies do go under. I will undertake to check the veracity of the member for Wills's claim and come back to the House on it. The House might like to know that I checked with my department to see whether or not any of the offers made by the federal Labor Party to various constituencies around the country during the election campaign had been submitted for any analysis or costing. First amongst those offers was the $150 million they promised for the Murwillumbah-Casino railway line. There were no probity checks whatsoever; there was not even an analysis done by the shadow minister for transport at the time.</para></talk.start></continue><para><inline font-style="italic">Opposition members interjecting—</inline></para><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>4K4</name.id><name role="display">Mr ANDERSON</name></talker><para>—Oh, you did check it? Let us see it. Where is it?</para></talk.start></continue><para><inline font-style="italic">Opposition members interjecting—</inline></para><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>4K4</name.id><name role="display">Mr ANDERSON</name></talker><para>—It was not; it was done by the Leader of the Opposition and Mr Carr in New South Wales. We have not received any applications or requests for checking in relation to an offer of $1 million for a national centre of democracy at Ballarat; none for a $10 million commitment for a national museum of Indigenous culture in Cairns; nothing for the $1.5 million for a turtle interpretation centre in Queensland; $3 million for a sporting complex at Thuringowa; $6 million for the Rockhampton showgrounds; or $12.5 million to upgrade transport infrastructure at Blacktown. And the opposition have a go at us for a Tasmanian package of $12 million. What about their $54 million Tasmanian package? And it goes on and on. The hypocrisy of the Labor Party on this knows no bounds whatsoever. The Leader of the Opposition's motto is very simple: `Do as I say, not as I do—and I hope none of you notice that in my electorate I support the regional programs.' </para></talk.start></continue><para>I also think it is time the opposition started to tell us which programs they would withdraw funding from. They should go out and tell the people who have had the benefit of those programs which ones they do not support. They should go down to Mogo, in the member for Eden-Monaro's seat, and tell those people that the $97,000 that secured four full-time jobs in a zoo should be withdrawn, that they should all go back on welfare and that the tourism industry should just fold up and go back to where it was.</para><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>R36</name.id><name role="metadata">Albanese, Anthony, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Albanese</name></talker><para>—Leave the animals alone!</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The member for Grayndler is warned!</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>4K4</name.id><name role="display">Mr ANDERSON</name></talker><para>—There are proper processes in place, the opposition's own Senate inquiry is probing those processes, and I am sure the department will be only too happy to explain what processes are in place.</para></talk.start></continue></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Health and Ageing: Aged Care</title><page.no>85</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>15:00:00</time.stamp><page.no>85</page.no><name role="metadata">Markus, Louise, MP</name><name role="display">Mrs MARKUS</name><name.id>E07</name.id><electorate>Greenway</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is addressed to the Minister for Ageing. Would the minister inform the House how the government is supporting the aged care sector and ensuring high quality care for older Australians?</para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>85</page.no><name role="metadata">Bishop, Julie, MP</name><name role="display">Ms JULIE BISHOP</name><name.id>83P</name.id><electorate>Curtin</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Minister for Ageing</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I thank the member for Greenway for her question. What an outstanding local representative is the member for Greenway. Last year I visited St Elizabeth's Nursing Home and Hostel in her electorate. She is an outstanding advocate for aged care issues. Today I announced details of a key plank of the government's reform agenda on aged care—the conditions attaching to the $877 million funding boost announced in the last budget. This payment was in addition to the annually indexed aged care subsidy already provided by the government. In order to receive this extra payment aged care providers must prepare a financial report that is audited annually and made available to residents, they must provide and encourage training opportunities for all their staff and take part in work force surveys and work force reporting.</para></talk.start><para>This conditional adjustment payment means that there is more transparent financial reporting in the aged care sector. That will boost market confidence and encourage greater investment in the sector. It means that there is more funding available for aged care providers so that they can pay competitive wages to staff to ensure that we continue to attract and retain quality aged care staff and it means greater improvements in the quality of care.</para><para>This government is building consumer confidence and market confidence in the aged care sector. It is part of our ongoing reform agenda to ensure that we have a sustainable, flexible and innovative aged care sector—a leading model for aged care across the world. This is our government's reform agenda, and we are delivering on it.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Regional Services: Program funding</title><page.no>86</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>15:02:00</time.stamp><page.no>86</page.no><name role="metadata">Beazley, Kim, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BEAZLEY</name><name.id>PE4</name.id><electorate>Brand</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is to the Prime Minister and it concerns $660,000 the taxpayers would really love to get back. Is the Prime Minister aware that yesterday the Queensland Supreme Court gave possession to Beaudesert Rail creditors assets that included a diesel engine, carriages, machinery sheds and office equipment? Doesn't his statement yesterday that they had made some on-balance judgments to put an additional $660,000 into Beaudesert Rail, notwithstanding that the department had concluded it could not meet the financial viability criteria, make a complete mockery of the Regional Partnerships program guidelines? </para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>86</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HOWARD</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—No.</para></talk.start></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Employment: Work for the Dole</title><page.no>86</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>15:03:00</time.stamp><page.no>86</page.no><name role="metadata">Keenan, Michael, MP</name><name role="display">Mr KEENAN</name><name.id>E0J</name.id><electorate>Stirling</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—My question is addressed to the Minister for Workforce Participation. Would the minister inform the House of the benefits of work for the dole to young jobseekers such as those in my electorate of Stirling? Are there any alternative views?</para></talk.start><para><inline font-style="italic">Opposition members interjecting—</inline></para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>86</page.no><name role="metadata">Dutton, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr DUTTON</name><name.id>00AKI</name.id><electorate>Dickson</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Minister for Workforce Participation</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The interjections have started already, because we know the Labor Party hates the Work for the Dole program. On 327 occasions now someone across there has criticised that program. I have reported that to the House before. We are still looking for a commitment to this program from the member for Brand. I start by congratulating the member for Stirling on a fantastic result in his seat. It is great to have a live member in Stirling. He is somebody who has supported local community groups already—</para></talk.start><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>PE4</name.id><name role="metadata">Beazley, Kim, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Beazley</name></talker><para>—I rise on a point of order. I know that the previous member for Stirling is no longer here but that was an extraordinary slur on her condition and I ask that it be withdrawn.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—I think the minister might oblige on that request.</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>00AKI</name.id><name role="display">Mr DUTTON</name></talker><para>—Absolutely; no slur was intended, whatsoever. It goes to show how sensitive the Labor Party is about this program. This program is providing real results for young Australians, yet at every opportunity the opposition opposes this program. Recently I announced 339 new programs which will help 4,000 young people across this country to provide support to their local communities. This government remains absolutely committed to the Work for the Dole program. In the member for Stirling's electorate one of those programs relates to the assistance provided to the local PCYC—helping the local police in that community to work with the children to provide support around the administration of the centre. It is a wonderful program that contributes right around the country—to the relief aid in the tsunami affected areas right across Indonesia. If the opposition remains opposed to the Work for the Dole program, why don't they dispense with the semantics and come out and say where they stand. If they are opposed to it they should scrap it as part of their policy. This government is committed to the program because it is part of the reason we have been able to bring unemployment levels down by half compared to when the opposition leader was the employment services minister.</para></talk.start></continue><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>ZD4</name.id><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Howard</name></talker><para>—Mr Speaker, I ask that further questions be placed on the <inline font-style="italic">Notice Paper</inline>.</para></talk.start></interjection></answer></subdebate.1></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>QUESTIONS TO THE SPEAKER</title><type>Questions to the Speaker</type><page.no>86</page.no></debateinfo><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Question Time</title><page.no>86</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>15:06:00</time.stamp><page.no>86</page.no><name role="metadata">Tanner, Lindsay, MP</name><name role="display">Mr TANNER</name><name.id>YU5</name.id><electorate>Melbourne</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—Mr Speaker, during question time you required the honourable member for Griffith to rephrase a section of a question which sought to ask the government whether it was the government's position that a person who is not a member of this House, Mr Rod Barton, was lying. I wonder could you explain to the House which standing order this part of the question breached and whether it is now the position that a member is unable to ask a minister whether it is the government's position that a particular person who is not a member of this House or the Senate, or the Governor-General or the Queen, is lying? </para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>87</page.no><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name><name.id>10000</name.id><electorate>PO</electorate><party>N/A</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I would remind the honourable member that it is not my job to give instructions. It is my job to uphold the standing orders. You will note quite clearly that one of the standing orders on questions makes it clear that reflections on members should be on notice, so I asked the member for Griffith to rephrase the question rather than putting it on notice.</para></talk.start><para><inline font-style="italic">Opposition members interjecting—</inline></para><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—Any person of the public.</para></talk.start></continue></answer><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>87</page.no><name role="metadata">Tanner, Lindsay, MP</name><name role="display">Mr TANNER</name><name.id>YU5</name.id><electorate>Melbourne</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—Mr Speaker, I again ask you which standing order the question from the member for Griffith was in breach of.</para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>87</page.no><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name><name.id>10000</name.id><electorate>PO</electorate><party>N/A</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I have answered the question.</para></talk.start></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Parliament: Standards</title><page.no>87</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>15:07:00</time.stamp><page.no>87</page.no><name role="metadata">Ferguson, Martin, MP</name><name role="display">Mr MARTIN FERGUSON</name><name.id>LS4</name.id><electorate>Batman</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—Mr Speaker, I have a question concerning the operation of the standing orders and the standards of the House. I seek advice from you, and perhaps you would consider referring the matter to the Procedure Committee, as to whether it is appropriate during question time to conduct party ballots for the Liberal Party for trips, for example, to New York, including the candidates for Boothby, Grey, Paterson, Pearce and Cook. It would be appreciated if you would consider this issue and report back to the House or, alternatively, refer the matter to the Procedure Committee for advice.</para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>87</page.no><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name><name.id>10000</name.id><electorate>PO</electorate><party>N/A</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I thank the member for Batman. I am not aware that that would be covered by any standing order. I will make further inquiries and get to back to him if necessary.</para></talk.start></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Parliament: Standards</title><page.no>87</page.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>15:08:00</time.stamp><page.no>87</page.no><name role="metadata">O'Connor, Gavan, MP</name><name role="display">Mr GAVAN O'CONNOR</name><name.id>WU5</name.id><electorate>Corio</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—Mr Speaker, I draw your attention to the standing order that requires ministers to address their remarks through the chair. I note that the Deputy Prime Minister, during question time, answered questions put to him with his back to you, playing to his comrades in the National Party at the far end of the room. It is an obvious mark of disrespect to you, and I am raising the matter in the hope that the Deputy Prime Minister and other National Party members will show some respect to you.</para></talk.start></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>87</page.no><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name><name.id>10000</name.id><electorate>PO</electorate><party>N/A</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I thank the member for Corio for his question. I will endeavour to remind ministers that when they answer questions they should speak through the chair and, particularly, through the microphone.</para></talk.start></answer></subdebate.1></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>PERSONAL EXPLANATIONS</title><type>Personal Explanations</type><page.no>87</page.no></debateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>15:09:00</time.stamp><page.no>87</page.no><name role="metadata">Mr FITZGIBBON,MP</name><name role="display">Mr FITZGIBBON</name><name.id>8K6</name.id><electorate>Hunter</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—Mr Speaker, I wish to make a personal explanation.</para></talk.start><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—Does the honourable member claim to have been misrepresented?</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>8K6</name.id><name role="metadata">Mr FITZGIBBON,MP</name><name role="display">Mr FITZGIBBON</name></talker><para>—Yes.</para></talk.start></continue><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—Please proceed.</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>8K6</name.id><name role="metadata">Mr FITZGIBBON,MP</name><name role="display">Mr FITZGIBBON</name></talker><para>—The Assistant Treasurer, despite my clarification in later debate yesterday, issued a press release yesterday afternoon accusing me of describing a new capital allowance regime for heavy vehicle transport as `industry welfare'. As the <inline font-style="italic">Hansard</inline> record will show, Mr Speaker, what I said was that Labor will continue to support departures from the effective life regime when a sound economic or social cost has been made out, as we did in this case, but not when it represents no more than industry welfare.</para></talk.start></continue></speech></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>DOCUMENTS</title><type>Documents</type><page.no>88</page.no></debateinfo><para>Mr ABBOTT (Warringah—Leader of the House) (3.10 p.m.)—Documents are presented as listed in the schedule circulated to honourable members earlier today. Details of the documents will be recorded in the <inline font-style="italic">Votes and Proceedings</inline>. </para><para>Mr ABBOTT (Warringah—Leader of the House) (3.10 p.m.)—I present documents on the following subjects, being petitions which are not in accordance with the standing and sessional orders of the House:</para><quote><para>In relation to an immigration matter—from the member for Deakin—297 Petitioners</para><para>Concerning student income support—from the member for Page—83 Petitioners</para></quote></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>MATTERS OF PUBLIC IMPORTANCE</title><type>Matters of Public Importance</type><page.no>88</page.no></debateinfo><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Truth in Government</title><page.no>88</page.no></subdebateinfo><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—I have received a letter from the honourable member for Brand proposing that a definite matter of public importance be submitted to the House for discussion, namely:</para></talk.start><quote><para>The need for the government to be open and honest with the Australian people</para></quote><para>I call upon those members who approve of the proposed discussion to rise in their places.</para><para><inline font-style="italic">More than the number of members required by the standing orders having risen in their places—</inline></para></interjection><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>15:11:00</time.stamp><page.no>88</page.no><name role="metadata">Beazley, Kim, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BEAZLEY</name><name.id>PE4</name.id><electorate>Brand</electorate><party>ALP</party><role>Leader of the Opposition</role><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—`Truth in government'. We have opponents across the chamber from us who will say anything and do anything to get themselves elected. They will say anything, do anything, slander any reputation while in office to protect their political position. They will spend anything, under any set of conditions, and ignore any guidelines in order to secure certain amounts of money for their candidates to ensure they get elected.</para></talk.start><para>This government is unacquainted with the truth or any decent standard that would be expected of it by a public. It has abandoned truthfulness, it has abandoned good public policy and it has abandoned all proper processes. It rejects the advice of independent experts, it ignores criticism and it covers over any facts that do not fit its message. This government and the Prime Minister are obsessed with spin doctoring, with controlling every image and every story to suit their political interests, no matter what the cost. It does not matter to them if the cost is that hundreds of millions of dollars are diverted from urgently needed infrastructure into political slush funds. It does not matter to them if the cost is that they damage the reputation of dedicated public servants and service men and women. It does not matter to them if the cost is an ever-deepening public cynicism towards democratic institutions. If there is short-term political gain, the government will be in it.</para><para>Despite the government's obsession with secrecy, we sometimes find out things they do not want us to know. That has been happening through the Senate estimates process this week, a process that will be much diminished in value from the middle of this year when the government will assume absolute control of this parliament. We are seeing perhaps the last phase of the value of that institution in accountability terms in Australia, and we are going to be the poorer for it. When the facts do come out, they will paint a damning picture of a government that has contempt for integrity and openness and an obsession with spinning a message that always paints it in the most favourable light.</para><para>I want to address three issues that demonstrate the urgent need for this government to radically change its priorities and to start putting the interests of the Australian people above the interests of Liberal and National Party politicians. The first is the deliberate deception that this government has practised by promising to keep interest rates low while implementing policies that are increasing inflationary pressures and making an interest rate increase a serious possibility in the coming months by its actions. The second is the deliberate deception that this government practised last year in concealing the fact that Australian armed forces participated in the interrogation of Iraqi prisoners. The third is the deliberate deception that this government has practised by allocating hundreds of millions of dollars to spending programs that have been driven by one priority—political profit for politicians. </para><para>Let me deal with the first of those, on interest rates. All of us in this place were contestants at the last election or we would not be here. Day after day in that election campaign, we saw statement after statement by the government along the lines of that statement I quoted in question time. Here is another one:</para><quote><para>Well, we're certainly, first and foremost, we're offering a continuation of the low interest rates of the last eight and a half years.</para></quote><para>They slandered the Labor Party, which was the only political party that went into this election campaign with savings for its expenditure programs in order to reduce budgetary pressures on interest rates, through that campaign. They whipped up a fear campaign about it and they won the election. What do we find in the aftermath of that election? We find the Prime Minister here in this chamber with weasel words: `We didn't really say that. Oh, no, we didn't promise the Australian people that interest rates would not rise.' Let me tell him there are at least 10 million Australians out there who think he did, and a substantial number of them voted for him on that basis. But, no, he cites the weasel words. Every day in question time there is another exercise in hairsplitting. We heard a few of them affecting Defence personnel today, and all year we have heard the hairsplitting on the question of interest rates. But the Australian people do not believe the government and, when the government find themselves presiding over increased interest rates, they will know exactly who to blame.</para><para>The government understand this is about to happen to them, so off they go to find scapegoats. The unions are the scapegoats. We have the government's industrial relations legislation in operation. We have a quiet union movement in this country. What we have as well is a population that is not as skilled as it should be and that is creating the pressure, the glitches and the blockages in our economy now as companies that wish to invest in new developments find themselves without the work force that they need. It is not that they have an undisciplined work force; it is that they cannot get a skilled work force and blockages emerge from the infrastructure.</para><para>Yesterday, the Treasurer stood up in this place and discussed the coal loader in Queensland—very interesting. The statement he cited from the Queensland minister is about as old as the hills. It is the first time the Treasurer has managed to get up and discuss it in this place, but why did he discuss it? Because he has discovered what the opposition's infrastructure spokespersons and Treasury spokespersons have been talking about since the day they were appointed, and they have been joined by the OECD and by the Reserve Bank. One of the glitches in the economy at the moment is the manifest inattention by this government to the infrastructure needs of this nation that has been the hallmark of its rule, or its misrule, for the last nine years.</para><para>The government inherited an economy in which great changes had been made that drove it to be one of the exemplary economies in the growth of wealth of the last decade or so. There were bitter experiences for many of us who served in those governments as we took the hard decisions to make changes and we were, as a result, the targets of many of those who had suffered as those changes were made. But the rewards were all reaped in political terms by this government, and this government has trashed them. It has trashed those rewards as it has sought, every time an election has come round, to buy itself back into power. </para><para>As the Reserve Bank governor sits down and contemplates what he intends to do about the future, there is no question that one of the things he has at the back of his mind is the $66 billion that this government punched out of the budget surplus in one year flat to get itself re-elected. Did the government think that the $66 billion punched into the economy to rocket-fuel it would pass the attention of the Reserve Bank governor and that, after the election was over, he might not think about doing something about it? But what he does about it ought to be sheeted right home to our political opponents.</para><para>There is no need for interest rates to rise. They boast about interest rates, but our interest rates are about the highest in the industrialised world. On a comparative basis, we have an official rate of 5.2 per cent. It is around two per cent in the US and in Europe. The nearest rate to ours is the British, which is 4.75 per cent. The Japanese rate is 0.1 per cent. And we are talking about the possibility of a 50 basis point rise in those circumstances. Where is our international competitiveness here? What is going to happen to Australian businesses as a result of that? And it can all be sheeted back to that $66 billion punch and the other matters that I have been referring to that John Howard put out for his re-election campaign.</para><para>The icing on the cake of that $66 billion had to be that extraordinary campaign launch of his. I have seen a few rippers in my time, and the odd Labor Party leader has been responsible for one or two of them, but I have never seen money spent in a policy speech at the rate of $200 million a minute. That absolutely took the prize, that absolutely took the cake; and that was our political opponents.</para><para>Truth in government goes elsewhere as well. It can go to national security areas and to the honour with which civil servants are dealt. The Prime Minister attacked us in question time today as though we have been attacking Defence personnel. He got up and said, `What the Labor Party are trying to prove is that Australian Defence personnel were involved in torture at Abu Ghraib.' No, that is not it. We are on the same wavelength as Mr Barton—the person who has blown the whistle on the government—an honourable public servant. We are trying to prove that the Australian people were deceived and this parliament was deceived when the government said it knew nothing about it and was not informed of these things until they became public matters.</para><para>Why would we want to know if the government knew something about it beforehand? The reason is that we take our allied duties seriously. Anyone can see, and it certainly was obviously the case after this issue broke out, that this would hand our enemies an unsurpassed propaganda victory and, if there were an opportunity to give a sensible warning to our ally that this sort of behaviour would be 100 per cent counterproductive to the objectives we seek in our life-and-death struggle with militant, fundamentalist terror, we would want at least a performance by the government in that regard.</para><para>The government seeks always to evade responsibility. When you take upon yourself the sort of struggle that is now being engaged in in Iraq, however mistaken that may be, you take upon yourself every single element of it. You must know the detail of what is going on with all armed service personnel in the area. And if a fella has come back and is seriously concerned enough to get the secretary of his department to write to the American ambassador here to warn him that this is going on—to get them back in the United States to stop things happening in Abu Ghraib—why in God's name didn't you do something about it? Instead of running around trying to evade responsibility and cover your backsides, why don't you just take a bit of responsibility for the jobs that you have in hand and deal with the problems? </para><para>A question was asked by the honourable member for Griffith about the difference between interrogation and interviewing. If a chap who is manacled thinks an interrogation is being conducted when the bloke standing behind the fellow in front of him has a gun, does he think he is having a little chat—`This is just a small conversation; a chin wag about the state of the world'? Fair dinkum, you must really think that we have a very foolish Australian public to wander around in this place hairsplitting on a subject like that. It is very important that you are hairsplitting. Why do you hairsplit on that? Is it to arrive at the truth of what we were told about Abu Ghraib and to have a bit of analysis about how we might have done a bit better in this? Is that the reason? No; because if we accept that `interview' means `interrogate' then the Prime Minister has lied to parliament. If he has lied to parliament, even under all the conventions the government has trampled on, the normal consequence is that you resign. He does not want that. He does not want Senator Hill to have to resign, he does not want to have to resign himself, and so words are given different meanings and decent people have their reputations trampled upon. That is what has happened in this case.</para><para>Finally, we get the performance. I have got to get myself onto the tactics committee of the other side and pinch a few of the questions—like the one that was asked today of the Deputy Prime Minister. If anything ever exposed what they were on about with these regional rorts, that was an absolute ripper. The only person who did not feature in the announcements in Brand was the member for Brand. Everybody else had a chop. Every Liberal Party and National Party minister had his fingerprints on it. They all had a chop, but the honourable member for Brand missed out. The simple fact of the matter is this: you have used $400 million of taxpayers' funds to undermine your political opponents. In most countries, that is described as corruption. Unfortunately, the consequence of this is that it has stripped your capacity to deal with the infrastructure of this nation on a proper basis. That is what it has done. We do have problems like that coal loader in Queensland and we do have problems with the port-rail interface. Why? Because the Commonwealth has put all the funds for those purposes into the campaign treasuries of the National Party and the Liberal Party, looting royally, and incompetently, I might say, as we have revealed in case after case in this place, and then has misled the Australian people about what it is up to. <inline font-style="italic">(Time expired)</inline></para><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">Causley, Ian (The DEPUTY SPEAKER)</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para><inline font-weight="bold"> (Hon. I.R. Causley)</inline>—I remind the Leader of the Opposition of the point of order by the member for Corio about the member not addressing the chair. I do not think he addressed the chair once.</para></talk.start></interjection></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>15:26:00</time.stamp><page.no>92</page.no><name role="metadata">Abbott, Tony, MP</name><name role="display">Mr ABBOTT</name><name.id>EZ5</name.id><electorate>Warringah</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Leader of the House</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—We have seen the Leader of the Opposition get very, very excited and get very, very worked up, and we have had the hot air, interrupted by the falsetto laugh, but the fact of the matter is that he has called the government just about every pejorative adjective in the book. He said we were unscrupulous, he said we were corrupt, he said we were secretive and he said we were dictatorial. I thought to myself, `Which government is he talking about?' Is it the Iranian government, is it the Libyan government or is it the North Korean government? We are supposed to believe all this is true of the government of Australia, a pacific democracy, a government which has just been re-elected by the people of Australia with an increased majority. </para></talk.start><para>In the end, what is the Leader of the Opposition's real complaint? His real complaint is that this government won and that opposition lost. His real complaint is that for the fourth time members opposite have failed to secure the trust of the Australian people. So, rather than accepting the truth that members opposite simply are not up to it and that the last four times members opposite simply have not put an adequate case to the Australian people for their election, rather than accept that simple, democratic truth, he has to pretend that somehow `they was robbed'. `We was robbed' is the essential claim that the Leader of the Opposition is making now. He made it in 1998; he made it in 1996. It is this constant, tired refrain: `We was robbed.' I say to the Leader of the Opposition and his colleagues: get over it; this government won and it is time for members opposite to do the hard work of reconstructing themselves as a credible alternative government.</para><para>The matter of public importance to which the Leader of the Opposition was speaking is:</para><quote><para>The need for the Government to be open and honest with the Australian people.</para></quote><para>Yes, it is important to be open and honest with the Australian people. Honesty and openness must be demanded by people who are open and honest themselves. I would like to read from a document that was being widely distributed on election night:</para><quote><para>There can be no denying that last year the Labor Party was deeply divided. No-one can make that claim now and that is one of Mark Latham's greatest achievements. We believe Mark Latham ran a very strong campaign. He demonstrated that he has discipline, focus and is inclusive.</para></quote><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>WF6</name.id><name role="metadata">Danby, Michael, MP</name><name role="display"></name></talker></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">Causley, Ian (The DEPUTY SPEAKER)</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para><inline font-weight="bold"> (Hon. I.R. Causley)</inline>—The member for Melbourne Ports is warned!</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>EZ5</name.id><name role="metadata">Abbott, Tony, MP</name><name role="display">Mr ABBOTT</name></talker><para>—It continues:</para></talk.start></continue><quote><para>He broke the campaign mould. He was the first leader in more than a decade to hold open community forums during a campaign. Many events like these were unscripted. He showed real leadership during the campaign. He had a story to tell on how Labor would govern Australia, and he told it. People are no longer in any doubt about what the Labor Party stands for and we will be able to build on that.</para></quote><para>These people who claim that there is nothing more important than being open and honest are the same people who distributed this document. It is a document distributed by the secretariat of the Australian Labor Party to all frontbenchers and spokesmen on election night. Plainly, it is a tissue of lies, an absolute fabrication from start to finish. The Labor Party were so united that their leader was dumped humiliatingly, acrimoniously and unprecedentedly just a couple of months after the election campaign.</para><para>The fact of the matter is that these people opposite, huffing and puffing hysterically about the alleged lies and deceit of this government, do not come to this debate with clean hands. We have seen from the Leader of the Opposition over the last couple of weeks a bad case of political schizophrenia because obviously there are two Kims. There is Brand Kim, who is desperately seeking, desperately demanding, Regional Partnerships grants, desperately trying to claim the credit for $1.1 million worth of Regional Partnerships grants in his electorate, writing to the Deputy Prime Minister demanding that the government provide Regional Partnerships grants to his electorate, distributing to his electorate newsletters that try to claim credit for the award of Regional Partnerships grants in his electorate, and then there is Canberra Kim, who tries to suggest that all of this is some kind of giant boondoggle, that this is some kind of giant election slush fund. You cannot have it both ways: it is impossible to be in favour of Regional Partnerships grants in your electorate and opposed to Regional Partnerships grants in this parliament. The Leader of the Opposition stands exposed yet again, as he has stood so many times in this parliament, as a hypocrite, as a two-timer, as someone who says one thing in the electorate and another thing in this parliament. The Australian people know him, they have rejected him and they are not going to let him get away with this kind of treatment of the parliament and the people for that much longer. </para><para>The lie to the claims from members opposite was given today in a most interesting opinion piece on the op-ed page of the <inline font-style="italic">Australian Financial Review. </inline>One of the more credible, one of the more honourable and one of the more honest members of the Australian Labor Party is the member for Melbourne—a member of this parliament who, if the Leader of the Opposition himself had more strength and more integrity, would be on the frontbench of the Australian Labor Party. He is misguided in many respects, but he is honest and he is honourable. He tells the truth: he says what he means and means what he says. What did the member for Melbourne say today in the <inline font-style="italic">Australian Financial Review</inline> of this whole tedious campaign that has been run by the Leader of the Opposition over the past fortnight? I quote:</para><quote><para>Sadly, neither I nor the Labor Party have been entirely pure in these matters. Since losing office in 1996, our manifestos have contained similar promises of specific local grants. As opposition transport spokesman, I promised to fund a study into pilot training at Launceston Airport and a rail research institute in Adelaide.</para></quote><para>He goes on to say:</para><quote><para>It's about time we got serious about the misuse of money ...</para></quote><para>He has given the lie to the entire Labor Party campaign of the last fortnight—guilty as charged, he says of the Australian Labor Party. This is not a guilty government; this is a guilty opposition. Indeed, if there is any guilt in this, and I do not believe that there is, it is a guilty parliament. So let us have no more of this two-timing cant from members opposite about some alleged problem with the Regional Partnerships grant program.</para><para>It is important that people who come into this parliament talking about the need for openness and honesty have been open and honest themselves. We had a press release yesterday from none other than the member for Lalor, the shadow minister for health, who says:</para><quote><para>At the Pink Ribbon Breakfast on the 1st of October 2004 the Minister for Health, Tony Abbott, announced that the Howard Government would commit $90 000 over 4 years to the NOCN—</para></quote><para>the National Ovarian Cancer Network. I happened to look at the press release that was put out for that very function, which says:</para><quote><para>The Minister for Health and Ageing, Tony Abbott, announced today that the Government would provide an additional $3 million over four years towards the National Breast Cancer Centre and an additional $600,000 for the Breast Cancer Network Australia.</para></quote><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>83L</name.id><name role="metadata">Gillard, Julia, MP</name><name role="display"></name></talker></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The member for Lalor!</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>EZ5</name.id><name role="metadata">Abbott, Tony, MP</name><name role="display">Mr ABBOTT</name></talker><para>—I looked everywhere in this press release for the $90,000 that I allegedly promised at the Pink Ribbon Breakfast on 1 October 2004. Having made a false claim, the member for Lalor then desperately ran around yesterday afternoon, trying to find some factual justification for the false claim that I had misled this worthy outfit. </para></talk.start></continue><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>83L</name.id><name role="metadata">Gillard, Julia, MP</name><name role="display"></name></talker></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The member for Lalor!</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>EZ5</name.id><name role="metadata">Abbott, Tony, MP</name><name role="display">Mr ABBOTT</name></talker><para>—She is still claiming it today—this person who boasts of being open and honest with the Australian people, this person who waxes self-righteous daily about her virtue and the alleged perfidy of the Australian government. Today she sends me a letter. It says:</para></talk.start></continue><quote><para>... On the 14th or 15th October 2004, Mr Barnes—</para></quote><para>of my office—</para><quote><para>confirmed that funding as sought for the 2005 Awareness Week would be supplied.</para></quote><para>This is a far cry from the claim made in the press release yesterday where she was caught out—</para><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>83L</name.id><name role="metadata">Gillard, Julia, MP</name><name role="display">Ms Gillard</name></talker><para>—But you still promised it.</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>EZ5</name.id><name role="metadata">Abbott, Tony, MP</name><name role="display">Mr ABBOTT</name></talker><para>—where she was caught out—</para></talk.start></continue><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>83L</name.id><name role="metadata">Gillard, Julia, MP</name><name role="display">Ms Gillard</name></talker><para>—You still promised it.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The member for Lalor seems to think she has a right to interject at any time. I warn her!</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>EZ5</name.id><name role="metadata">Abbott, Tony, MP</name><name role="display">Mr ABBOTT</name></talker><para>—in a blatant untruth. If she were still a lawyer, she would be struck off for the kind of behaviour—</para></talk.start></continue><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>83L</name.id><name role="metadata">Gillard, Julia, MP</name><name role="display">Ms Gillard</name></talker><para>—That's all right, is it?</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>EZ5</name.id><name role="metadata">Abbott, Tony, MP</name><name role="display">Mr ABBOTT</name></talker><para>—that she has been guilty of over the last couple of days.</para></talk.start></continue><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The member for Lalor is now challenging the chair. I remind her of standing order 94(a). She is the Manager of Opposition Business in the House. She gets some leniency in this place, but she continually interjects.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>IJ4</name.id><name role="metadata">Snowdon, Warren, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Snowdon</name></talker><para>—Mr Deputy Speaker, I rise on a point of order.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—Member for Lingiari, if this is a frivolous point of order, I will—</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>IJ4</name.id><name role="metadata">Snowdon, Warren, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Snowdon</name></talker><para>—I ask him to withdraw that comment about the member's legal profession.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—What was that comment? I did not hear it.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>IJ4</name.id><name role="metadata">Snowdon, Warren, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Snowdon</name></talker><para>—He made a derogatory remark.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—I was calling the member for Lalor to order. If she was quiet, I might have heard it.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>IJ4</name.id><name role="metadata">Snowdon, Warren, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Snowdon</name></talker><para>—I heard it.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>QI4</name.id><name role="metadata">Price, Roger, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Price</name></talker><para>—Mr Deputy Speaker—</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The member for Chifley seems to be in a hurry to speak to the point of order.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>QI4</name.id><name role="metadata">Price, Roger, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Price</name></talker><para>—Very much so. The Leader of the House reflected on the member for Lalor in a way that requires a—</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—I am just dealing with that. Will the member withdraw it?</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>EZ5</name.id><name role="metadata">Abbott, Tony, MP</name><name role="display">Mr ABBOTT</name></talker><para>—If it offends people, given the decline in legal standards perhaps, I will withdraw. But lest everyone—</para></talk.start></continue><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>QI4</name.id><name role="metadata">Price, Roger, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Price</name></talker><para>—I rise on a point of order—</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—If this is frivolous, I will deal with it.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>QI4</name.id><name role="metadata">Price, Roger, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Price</name></talker><para>—The withdrawal needs to be unqualified.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The member withdrew the comment. The member for Chifley will resume his seat.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>QI4</name.id><name role="metadata">Price, Roger, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Price</name></talker><para>—It was not unqualified—</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The member for Chifley will remove himself from the House under standing order 94(a)!</para></talk.start><para><inline font-style="italic">The member for </inline><inline font-style="italic">Chifley</inline><inline font-style="italic"> then left the chamber</inline><inline font-style="italic">.</inline></para></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id> EZ5</name.id><name role="metadata">Abbott, Tony, MP</name><name role="display">Mr ABBOTT</name></talker><para>—Lest anyone had been listening to the caterwauling that we have had from members opposite—</para></talk.start></continue><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>IJ4</name.id><name role="metadata">Snowdon, Warren, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Snowdon</name></talker><para>—Tell us about Archbishop Pell: did you see him or not?</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The member for Lingiari!</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>EZ5</name.id><name role="metadata">Abbott, Tony, MP</name><name role="display">Mr ABBOTT</name></talker><para>—let me table the emails between my office and the Ovarian Cancer Network. I will tell you what these emails will reveal. These emails will reveal a worthy organisation that wanted funds for a good cause. They will reveal an office which tried very hard to help this organisation and will continue to try to help this organisation. I say to the Ovarian Cancer Network that there will be a program put swiftly in place, as this government promised during the election campaign. They are welcome to apply to that program, and I hope they do get support, because they are a good organisation. I table these emails which completely give the lie to the claims made by the member for Lalor. I also table a letter that she gave me today, and I table the press release that she put out yesterday.</para></talk.start></continue><para>It is very clear: nothing has been said in this chamber or elsewhere by the opposition over the last fortnight to indicate that this is anything other than a good government getting on with the job of governing this country—getting on with the job, putting its election commitments in place. There is no evidence that anyone on the frontbench of this government has ever answered questions other than honestly on the basis of the best knowledge available to that minister at that time. As the Prime Minister said so well in this chamber today, there is no evidence that Senator Hill has done anything other than patiently and comprehensively answer questions put to him on the basis of the best advice that he had at the time.</para><para>This is an opposition which has become somewhat hysterical. What is behind all the activities of the last few days? It is not concern for the people of Iraq. It is not concern for Cornelia Rau. It is not concern for the dental health of the people of New South Wales. All that matters to them is trying to prove that the Prime Minister is an incompetent liar. I think they need to get over their fixation with Prime Minister Howard. I think they need to have a long, hard look at themselves. In particular, the Leader of the Opposition needs to have a long, hard look at himself and try to prove that he is different from the person that the Australian people do know well and have rejected so often. <inline font-style="italic">(Time expired)</inline></para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>15:41:00</time.stamp><page.no>95</page.no><name role="metadata">Thomson, Kelvin, MP</name><name role="display">Mr KELVIN THOMSON</name><name.id>UK6</name.id><electorate>Wills</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I want to complement the Leader of the Opposition's contribution to this debate by talking about the need for us to get honesty from this government with the Australian people in relation to Regional Partnerships, which has degenerated into an all-singing, all-dancing $400 million Howard government slush fund. If you have got the contacts, if you are in the know, there is no limit to what you can get it to fund. It has allocated $138,000 for a day-care centre for dogs in Brisbane. It has allocated $231,000 to build a tomato greenhouse at Port Macquarie. It has allocated $271,000 to create a pet food business. It has allocated money for a private zoo, money for a golf course, money for lights for tennis courts and money for child-care centres, doctors surgeries and X-ray companies. It has allocated $550,000 for a mushroom farm south of Cairns.</para></talk.start><para>Of course, most of us were given the mushroom treatment about Regional Partnerships: we were kept in the dark. They did not advertise it on TV, or radio or in the newspapers. They certainly did not write to Labor or any other non-government MPs telling us this $400 million program existed. I wish they had written to me. Last year I needed to get a housing loan; I would have gone to Regional Partnerships if only I had known about it! </para><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>WF6</name.id><name role="metadata">Danby, Michael, MP</name><name role="display"></name></talker></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The member for Melbourne Ports has been warned!</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>UK6</name.id><name role="metadata">Thomson, Kelvin, MP</name><name role="display">Mr KELVIN THOMSON</name></talker><para>—Yesterday the Queensland Supreme Court ordered that the creditors of the Beaudesert railway be given possession of Beaudesert Rail's diesel engine, carriages, machinery, sheds and office equipment. The Beaudesert railway is now left with just a steam engine, which is itself security for an outstanding debt to the Queensland government. What a monument to this government's financial mismanagement—a sorry tale of government ineptitude and incompetence, of throwing good taxpayers' money after bad. We had the Prime Minister in here yesterday telling the House he made an `on-balance judgment' to provide a further $660,000 of taxpayers' money to Beaudesert Rail. Never mind that this made a complete joke of the Regional Partnerships guidelines about the need for financial viability, never mind that the department believed it was not financially viable, never mind that the provisional liquidator did not believe it was financially viable, never mind its failure to properly acquit the $5 million Centenary of Federation funds: the Prime Minister made an `on-balance judgment' to put another $660,000 of taxpayers' money into this lemon.</para></talk.start></continue><para>Why did he do it? He did it to save the Liberal member for Forde from embarrassment in the lead-up to an election. You see, she had her name all over the original $5 million Centenary of Federation grant to get the Beaudesert Rail project up and going. When she heard that this project was about to go off the rails and the $5 million was going to be wasted, she was no doubt mortified. She is the person who persuaded the Prime Minister to first offer a $400,000 loan and later turn it into a $660,000 grant—$660,000 to save the face of the member for Forde. Menelaus thought Helen of Troy's face worthy of the launch of a thousand ships. The Prime Minister thought the member for Forde's face worthy of $660,000 of taxpayers' money!</para><para>The 13 June 2003 report of the provisional liquidator makes this absolutely clear. He says that, after his appointment, he was able to conclude that Beaudesert Rail could not pay its creditors merely from trading. He says that he contacted Mrs Kay Elson, the federal member for Forde, to discuss the possibility of receiving further funds. He says: `In a discussion with Ms Elson and Mr Ron Munn, the Mayor of Beaudesert, it was clearly put to me that by keeping the train trading, albeit at a loss, it would significantly enhance the prospects of receiving federal government funding.' The provisional liquidator then became caught between the concerns of creditors, on the one hand—he says that `the committee of creditors were understandably concerned that we were trading at a loss'; they were trading while insolvent—and, on the other hand, the urgings of the member for Forde to keep the train going.</para><para>The provisional liquidator decided to bring things to a head. He said that, unless something concrete was received by 5 June 2003, Beaudesert Rail should cease business and market its assets for sale. The next day, he said, `It was made clear to me by Mr Munn and Ms Elson that approval of government funding was a matter of days away and that this funding was to save Beaudesert Rail and to close down would make it more difficult to obtain the funding, if not impossible.' On Friday, 6 June, he said, `I received a letter from Ms Elson advising that government funding was imminent and I made the decision to trade the business over the weekend to see if this was the case.' Honourable members, I am sure, can feel the air of crisis here. On 12 June 2003, the provisional liquidator received a letter from the Prime Minister making a conditional offer of a $400,000 loan. </para><para>It is absolutely clear from the provisional liquidator's report that the actions of the member for Forde and the Prime Minister compromised the government and, therefore, Australian taxpayers in this matter. The reason Beaudesert Rail kept running during this period, its losses increasing with each passing week, was because the member for Forde and the Prime Minister had made representations to the provisional liquidator. Just imagine if, after all that, the government had said, `We've examined your project, and we think it's a dog, and we're not going to give it any more money,' the creditors would have been outraged, and with good reason. So we come to the end of the line for $5.7 million of taxpayers' money. Where the Prime Minister should have been interrogating the member for Forde over that money, it looks like he did not even bother to interview her.</para><para>Where there is a rort, you just feel it in your bones, you know the National Party is going to be in there somewhere—and so it is here. The Beaudesert Rail project had been spearheaded by Joy Drescher, a former National Party candidate for state parliament, who was elected mayor of Beaudesert earlier this year. Yesterday the member for Grayndler urged the Prime Minister to carpe diem—to seize the day—on the issue of climate change. But the National Party has its own motto. It is not carpe diem; it is carpe prosciutto—Latin for `seize the pork'. The member for Hotham, who fancies himself as a bit of a Latin scholar, thinks it should be carpe porchetta—but perhaps he is just advertising a restaurant chain. The National Party is so reliable in this that I have developed my own law of physics, which says: `Where there's a coalition trough, there's a National Party snout.' Now I know it is not as elegant or as important as Einstein's law of relativity or Newton's law of gravity, but it holds good for the overwhelming majority of Howard government programs.</para><para>And so it is that we heard today that it is not just the National Party mayor of Beaudesert but the National Party mayor of Tweed Heads, south of the border, Mr Warren Polglase, who recommended a $273,000 Dairy Assistance Program grant to Seawind, a South Tweed seafood company which has now gone bust. Mr Polglase is a very active man. He is the mayor of Tweed Shire Council, the local National Party Electorate Council chair and a member of the Northern Rivers Area Consultative Committee. He managed to get himself appointed as an executive officer or a project officer to administer the Dairy Assistance Program.</para><para>We understand that this position was advertised but that no interviews—certainly no interrogations—for the position were ever held. Warren Polglase just got the job. Minister Anderson needs to inform the parliament and the Australian people just what selection process Mr Polglase went through before he was given this position. Mr Polglase has all the hallmarks of the Queensland National Party under Joh Bjelke-Petersen. If you read what has been happening in the New South Wales inquiry, you will discover that he is something of a colourful National Party identity. But, as the executive officer for the Dairy Assistance Program, he managed to recommend $88,000 in Dairy Regional Assistance grant money to prominent National Party supporters to add farm-stay accommodation to their tea tree farm and to recommend $273,000 of taxpayers' money to Seawind, a South Tweed seafood company that has subsequently gone bust. </para><para>My time is coming to a close but, as there was a bit of enthusiasm for the nursery rhyme last week, I will conclude with a verse:</para><quote><para>The Ballad of Beaudesert Rail</para><para>They say it comes out on the nights of full moon</para><para>The ghost train of Beaudesert from its rusting cocoon</para><para>It once used to run amid whoops amid hollers</para><para>Till it chewed up 5 million of taxpayers' dollars</para><para>The Deputy PM put it back on the track</para><para>With six hundred grand more that went straight up the stack</para><para>So now it sits idle a monument stored</para><para>And nobody comes when they shout “All aboard”</para><para>And they talk about rorts and they talk about fraud</para><para>Of a train with one passenger, the Member here for Forde</para><para>And it's just a classic case of throwing good money after bad</para><para>And how voters they were conned, and taxpayers they were had.</para><para>But there's still hope for it yet tho much ill of it we speak</para><para>Build a rail line to Dobell? Let it dredge the Tumbi Creek! <inline font-style="italic">(Time expired)</inline></para></quote></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>15:52:00</time.stamp><page.no>98</page.no><name role="metadata">Baird, Bruce, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BAIRD</name><name.id>MP6</name.id><electorate>Cook</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—It is clear that the member for Wills should not give up his day job. As a poet he has no chance at all. This matter of public importance, which says, `The need for the government to be open and honest with the Australian people,' is a joke—the ALP talking about honesty and integrity in government! They should be the last ones to talk about it. In fact, we all remember the lead-up to the 1993 election, when the tax cuts were going to become `l-a-w law'. There were going to be no tax increases at all. You could rest on it—Paul Keating went out and told the Australian public: `You can trust this Labor government. You can rely on it. We will deliver on our promises. There will be no tax increases.' Of course, once the election— <inline font-style="italic">(Quorum formed)</inline></para></talk.start><para>It is very clear that the opposition do not want to hear the truth about what they promised in 1993 in terms of l-a-w law. Labor promised there were going to be tax cuts and what happened? They did not happen at all. Then, of course, when they went to the 1996 election the current Leader of the Opposition, the then minister for finance, told us that there was a surplus of $10.1 billion. He said that frequently around the country. What was the reality of it? In fact, a week after this government came to office we found it was a $10.3 billion deficit. So much for honesty. It was only a $20 billion lie—not bad—and it was the Leader of the Opposition who got up and said it.</para><para>Of course, we remember that wonderful institution Centenary House. It is just a prime example of honesty and integrity in government. It is like a symbol. If you went into the old East Block, there would be a symbol of the working man there to show what they are about. I think in future there will be tours to Centenary House to show people: this is what the Labor Party in office believed was appropriate integrity, honesty and openness for the Australian people. It was called a $43 billion rort. And they are the ones who are lecturing us on honesty.</para><para>Regarding the regional grants that we are now talking about, there were some 800 applications from coalition held seats and 200 from Labor held seats. They were too busy having their lattes and chardonnays to actually help people fill in their applications. <inline font-style="italic">(Quorum formed)</inline> Again the Labor Party do not want to hear the truth. The Labor Party did not assist their communities to apply for regional grants. The fact is that the percentage of applications that were approved for Labor seats and the percentage approved for coalition seats was exactly the same. There was clearly no bias; it was independently audited three times by KPMG. There were three reviews which made no findings of impropriety. </para><para>By contrast, we remember old Ros Kelly, the then member for Canberra. Did she know how to rort. She was the master of rort with the old whiteboard: `We'll have five for the Labor Party, one for the coalition, 10 for the Labor Party.' They took the whiteboard to great excellence but she did not survive. That was the member for Canberra who taught us all about what she thought was truth and honesty in government. It shows quite clearly that they have no understanding of what truth and honesty are.</para><para>In the last election they made $40 billion of promises and they said that PricewaterhouseCoopers was going to do a total audit of the costings and they indicated that they were properly funded. PricewaterhouseCoopers had to put out a statement saying that that was wrong, that all that they were required to do was to add up the amount. There was no verification of whether the funding was appropriate or the claims they made as to where the funding was. A lot of it was purely bogus money all the way through. They failed to submit their policies to Treasury and Finance before the deadline set by the department. They did not put their whole tax policy before the deadline or their child-care policy, their schools policy or their defence policy. Labor even refused to submit Medicare Gold.</para><para>In the debate today we have the Leader of the Opposition, a former finance minister, talking about interest rates. He accused this government in outrageous terms. He talked about the increases in interest rates that are happening, and of course there has been no announcement by the Reserve Bank at all about interest rate increases. We remember what the interest rates were under the other side—17 per cent. For small business it went up to 21 per cent. Under this government the amount is five to 6½ per cent. The Leader of the Opposition wants to indicate his economic credentials, but it is clear he knows nothing about interest rates.</para><para>On the issues of credibility, honesty and reliability, it is this side of the House that sets the example. The Charter of Budget Honesty that we provided set out the parameters. It showed the lies, the fraud, the dishonesty, the rorting of the previous government. We have shown what integrity in government is really about. The mob opposite are just producing a total sham. It is time they decided to get with the program and decide that honesty in government is the way to go. <inline font-style="italic">(Time expired)</inline></para><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">Causley, Ian (The DEPUTY SPEAKER)</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para><inline font-weight="bold"> (Hon. I.R. Causley)</inline>—Order! The discussion is now concluded.</para></talk.start></interjection></speech></subdebate.1></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>COMMITTEES</title><type>Committees</type><page.no>99</page.no></debateinfo><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Members' Interests Committee</title><page.no>99</page.no></subdebateinfo><subdebate.2><subdebateinfo><title>Report</title><page.no>99</page.no></subdebateinfo><para>Mr CIOBO (Moncrieff) (4.02 p.m.)—In accordance with standing order 220, on behalf of the Committee of Members' Interests, I present the report on the operations of the committee for 2004, together with the minutes of proceedings.</para><quote><para>Ordered that the report be made a Parliamentary Paper.</para></quote></subdebate.2></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Publications Committee</title><page.no>100</page.no></subdebateinfo><subdebate.2><subdebateinfo><title>Report</title><page.no>100</page.no></subdebateinfo><para>Mrs DRAPER (Makin) (4.02 p.m.)—I present the report from the Publications Committee sitting in conference with the Publications Committee of the Senate. Copies of the report are being placed on the table. </para><para>Report—by leave—adopted.</para></subdebate.2></subdebate.1></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>GOVERNOR-GENERAL'S SPEECH</title><type>Governor-General's Speech</type><page.no>100</page.no></debateinfo><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Address-in-Reply</title><page.no>100</page.no></subdebateinfo><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">Causley, Ian (The DEPUTY SPEAKER)</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para><inline font-weight="bold"> (Hon. I.R. Causley)</inline>—I have to report that the order of the day for the resumption of debate on the address-in-reply has been returned to the House from the Main Committee. I present a certified copy of the report.</para></talk.start><para>Ordered that the order of the day be considered immediately.</para></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">Causley, Ian (The DEPUTY SPEAKER)</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The question is that the address be agreed to.</para></talk.start><para>Question agreed to.</para></interjection></subdebate.1></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>APPROPRIATION BILL (NO. 3) 2004-2005</title><type>Bills</type><page.no>100</page.no><id.no>R2279</id.no><cognate><cognateinfo><title>APPROPRIATION BILL (NO. 4) 2004-2005</title><type>Bills</type><id.no>R2278</id.no></cognateinfo></cognate><cognate><cognateinfo><title>APPROPRIATION (PARLIAMENTARY DEPARTMENTS) BILL (NO. 2) 2004-2005</title><type>Bills</type><id.no>R2277</id.no></cognateinfo></cognate><cognate><cognateinfo><title>APPROPRIATION BILL (NO. 4) 2004-2005</title><type>Bills</type></cognateinfo></cognate></debateinfo><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Second Reading</title><page.no>100</page.no></subdebateinfo><para>Debate resumed.</para><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>16:04:00</time.stamp><page.no>100</page.no><name role="metadata">Baldwin, Robert, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BALDWIN</name><name.id>LL6</name.id><electorate>Paterson</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—Prior to question time I raised the issue of road works and road funding in my electorate. During the election there was another commitment made, a commitment to a football stadium, but it was made by the opposition. The stadium we are talking about used to be called Marathon Stadium; it is now called Energy Australia Stadium. The state government, which own this facility and are responsible for it, have already put in some $32 million. They seem to demand that the federal government also contribute $32 million towards their facility. I am not against providing money for a football stadium but, as I said to my constituents during the election—and I said it before and I said it during and I say it after the election—I put the issues and interests of my electorate first, second, third and last.</para></talk.start><para>The football stadium is not in my electorate. In fact it is not a responsibility of this government. On the Central Coast the Graham Park Stadium that was built at Gosford was built for around $23 million in total. I have to ask: why is it that only half a stadium can be built for $32 million and why the cost blow-out to $60 million? Should the board of the International Sports Centre Trust achieve the funding from the state government then I wish them well, because there is no doubt that the area does deserve a world-class football stadium. But it should be funded by those that own the stadium.</para><para>The issues that are important to my electorate are roads, health and education. That is what we committed to; that is what we were determined to deliver to the people of Paterson. I spoke before about road funding and I spoke about the money that had been offered to the councils of Port Stephens, Dungog and Great Lakes. We have put $10 million on the table which is to be matched by the state government with an additional $10 million. The funding is broken up into three groupings. Two million dollars is for Great Lakes Shire. <inline font-style="italic">(Quorum formed)</inline></para><para>This will probably go down as the greatest hour of contribution from the member for Shortland: the greatest contribution she can make is to draw the chair's attention to the state of the House. On that side of the House we have an impotent member of parliament who can deliver nothing to her electorate. That is the same member who under the Regional Solutions program condemned this government for providing no packages to her electorate. Mr Deputy Speaker, do you know why no packages were delivered to her electorate? It was because she had not even bothered to work with her community to put in any applications. That is the sort of member that she is. She is impotent and should not be in this place. If it were not for the fact that she had such a safe seat she would not be here. She is a disgrace as a member. She cannot even convince her colleagues in the New South Wales government to deliver projects in the Hunter. </para><para>Road funding suffers in the Hunter under the Carr state Labor government, of which she was a member prior to coming to this place—and she has done nothing since to help to deliver projects. The football stadium that I spoke about is the responsibility of the Carr Labor government and, again, she has done nothing to represent her constituents in obtaining money from the state Labor government. She sits there, whines, whinges and delivers nothing on behalf of her constituents in the seat of Shortland. It is absolutely disgraceful. As I said, perhaps the best contribution she has made in this place is bringing on three quorums because she is bored and ineffective as a member of parliament.</para><para>I am proud of the road funding that I deliver to my electorate. As I said, we got a commitment of $10 million for the areas—</para><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>83N</name.id><name role="metadata">Hall, Jill, MP</name><name role="display">Ms Hall</name></talker><para>—Mr Deputy Speaker, I once again draw your attention to the state of the House.</para></talk.start><para><inline font-style="italic">The bells being rung—</inline></para></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">Causley, Ian (The DEPUTY SPEAKER)</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para><inline font-weight="bold"> (Hon. I.R. Causley)</inline>—I remind the member for Shortland that I think she is being a little bit frivolous at the present time.</para></talk.start><para><inline font-style="italic">(Quorum formed)</inline></para></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>LL6</name.id><name role="metadata">Baldwin, Robert, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BALDWIN</name></talker><para>—We have just seen the member for Shortland make another valued contribution to this place in stopping free speech and debate.</para></talk.start></continue><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>8K6</name.id><name role="metadata">Fitzgibbon, Joel, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Fitzgibbon</name></talker><para>—Mr Deputy Speaker, I rise on a point of order. I understand the standing orders require each member to speak from their place. The member for Paterson is clearly not doing so and I ask you to bring him back to order.</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>LL6</name.id><name role="metadata">Baldwin, Robert, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BALDWIN</name></talker><para>—I suggest the member for Hunter go and get a set of glasses or read the seating plan.</para></talk.start></continue><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The member for Paterson is in his place. The member for Hunter will remove himself from the House under standing order 94(a) for being ridiculous.</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>LL6</name.id><name role="metadata">Baldwin, Robert, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BALDWIN</name></talker><para>—And justly done, Mr Deputy Speaker, because he, too, is an embarrassment and does nothing for this House.</para></talk.start></continue><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—I will name the member for Hunter if he does not leave.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>8K6</name.id><name role="metadata">Fitzgibbon, Joel, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Fitzgibbon</name></talker><para>—He is clearly not in his place, Mr Deputy Speaker.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">DEPUTY SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—The member for Paterson is in his place. The member for Hunter will remove himself from the House under standing order 94(a).</para></talk.start><para><inline font-style="italic">The member for Hunter then left the chamber.</inline></para></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>LL6</name.id><name role="metadata">Baldwin, Robert, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BALDWIN</name></talker><para>—That was another valued contribution from an impotent member of parliament from the Hunter Valley. I stand up proudly for the Hunter Valley and I deliver things. I try to represent my constituents with honour. Mr Deputy Speaker, you have just seen two efforts from two members of the Hunter that are disgraceful in terms of allowing free speech and allowing me to represent my constituents in this place. I was speaking about road funding, what we have delivered and what we have promised, but I can bet that the state Labor government will not match our $10 million that we are putting into this community.</para></talk.start></continue><para>Why did we have to do that? We had to do it because we put $20 million into the Bucketts Way, which the member for Hunter, who has just left the chamber under your instructions, opposed each and every step of the way. The state government refused to contribute to their road, the Bucketts Way. But work is carrying on and the difference that it is making is that there has been a reduction in fatalities on the Bucketts Way. That is the best reason to invest in roads: to save people's lives, to make them safer and to improve the economic conditions of every person that travels on them. The $10 million that we are offering to the local councils includes $2 million for the Lakes Way—a road that is in very poor state. But the state government seems to wash its hands of that one, which is a major road for tourism through Bulahdelah to Pacific Palms through the Forster-Tuncurry area. </para><para>But do we hear a word from the state Labor government? Not a word. We are putting $2 million into Port Stephens Council for the road between Raymond Terrace and Glen Oak. In addition, $6 million will go to the Dungog Council for the road from Glen Oak up through to Dungog. This is an area that was heavily affected by the decision of the former Prime Minister to shut down the timber industry. That was the first nail in the coffin for the township of Dungog. The second was when, in the New South Wales parliament, the member for Shortland's friend Bob Carr moved for dairy deregulation. That was the second thing that hurt and hit my township.</para><para>I do not sit back; I get on the front foot and drive for economic improvement in my area. I want to create jobs in my area, so I lobbied and lobbied and have been able to deliver $10 million worth of road funding. The question was put to me when the members for Shortland and Hunter stood up proudly and said, `We want to fund a football stadium.' The Labor federal government was going to throw $30 million into a football stadium. I said I would rather put $10 million into roads because that will help save lives; that will improve the economic conditions of those towns that those roads serve. That is money well spent and well invested in our community, and I am determined to deliver on it.</para><para>But there is a hitch. Because the member for Shortland's friend Bob Carr would not commit money to match it on the Bucketts Way, we had to make it a condition of approval. What have they said so far? The recently ousted minister for roads, Carl Scully, said, `I'm not going to fund it.' Now we have a new Minister for Roads in New South Wales, Michael Costa. He is also the minister for the Hunter. Let us hope he has a different attitude towards saving people's lives and improving roads and economic conditions in regional and rural areas. After all, he is not only the roads minister, he is the minister for the Hunter. Guess what they have just done—and this is why I doubt we are going to get anything. The Newcastle Knights just made him their patron. So his focus will be on a football stadium not on the fatalities. He will not be interested in saving lives in my electorate.</para><para>The other issue I have is that the state government in New South Wales have absolutely no hesitation in spending another $1 billion on a tunnel under Sydney to improve traffic flow. It does not save any lives; it just improves traffic flow. Can you imagine what a billion dollars of road funding from the New South Wales government would do in rural and regional areas? It would go a long way towards fixing and finishing off the road between Sydney and Brisbane—the Pacific Highway. The member for Hunter talks about F3 extension through Branxton—</para><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>83N</name.id><name role="metadata">Hall, Jill, MP</name><name role="display"></name></talker></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">Causley, Ian (The DEPUTY SPEAKER)</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para><inline font-weight="bold"> (Hon. I.R. Causley)</inline>—I am not going to take a point of order from the member for Shortland. We have had enough quorums. If you read House procedure you will see that I am allowed to do that. </para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>LL6</name.id><name role="metadata">Baldwin, Robert, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BALDWIN</name></talker><para>—To the gallery: you have just seen the fifth great contribution from the member for Shorthand, who has nothing to say, nothing to deliver and absolutely no talent when it comes to this place. She must be the slave of the New South Wales Labor Party, the slave of the Carr government, because when I talk about road funding and what I want to deliver into my region she attempts to shut me down each and every step of the way because she does not want to embarrass the Labor government in New South Wales. The attitude from the opposition has been disgraceful, but they will never stop me standing up for the people that I represent, pushing for the issues that are important to them and making sure that I give them the best possible representation I can in this place. I will never ever be silenced.</para></talk.start></continue></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>16:19:00</time.stamp><page.no>103</page.no><name role="metadata">Murphy, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr MURPHY</name><name.id>83D</name.id><electorate>Lowe</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—In this debate on the <inline ref="R2279">Appropriation Bill (No. 3) 2004-2005</inline> and related bills I wanted to raise two very important issues regarding the communications portfolio but the enemy, time, will prevent me from getting to the second issue. The first issue relates to the Australian Broadcasting Authority and its failure to grant a radio licence for Sydney frequency 1386AM. I foreshadow that the second issue I will raise, if I do not get time to do so today, concerns the government's failure to protect free-to-air television viewers from a loophole in the antisiphoning regime.</para></talk.start><para>There is a long history attached to the ABA's failure to grant a radio licence for Sydney frequency 1386AM. I am advised that on 25 May 2001 the ABA formed a preliminary view that an additional wide coverage community radio service should be made available in Sydney and called for public comment as to the suitable use of 1386AM for community radio. I am advised that on 27 July 2001 the ABA received several submissions, including one from Sydney Christian Broadcasters Ltd, also known as Rhema Sydney, on behalf of Sydney's estimated 900,000 churchgoing Christians. I am also advised that on 27 December 2001 the ABA received a revised draft variation to the Sydney radio licence area plan, proposing alternative sites for the community radio station. After receiving further submissions, the ABA continued to announce its support for a community radio station.</para><para>In March 2002 the ABA decided to make 1386AM available as a community broadcasting service instead of a narrowcasting service. On 15 July 2002 the ABA invited new applications for the Sydney-wide community radio licence transmitting on the 1386AM band. Again, fresh submissions were called for. On 26 March 2003 the ABA decided not to allocate radio licence 1386AM. In each case, Radio Rhema made submissions. In the final decision, the ABA was concerned about the location of a transmission station in the Sydney suburb of Homebush in my electorate of Lowe, allegedly because of concerns about proximity to new homes. On this basis, a decision was deferred for 12 months.</para><para>I am further advised that, in March 2003, eight applicants bid for the allocation of a Sydney community radio operator licence on frequency 1386 megahertz on the amplitude modulation, or AM, band. At that time, the ABA rejected all eight licence applicants. This rejection is of itself not unusual, but the failure of the ABA to grant a temporary licence was unusual. Incredibly, on 22 April 2004 the ABA called for yet another round of public comment. To this very day, there has still been no decision by the ABA to grant this radio licence.</para><para>By far the main contender in the application process is Rhema Sydney. The narrowing of bids to two main contenders follows other bidders dropping out. Put simply, Rhema Sydney has demonstrated overwhelming public interest. Rhema Sydney's application greatly outweighed all other applications in responses from the general public of Sydney, who strongly called for Rhema Sydney to be granted the 1386AM licence. In its submission, Rhema Sydney notes that it has in excess of 4,000 members and over 750 letters in support representing close to 460,000 individuals in the greater Sydney region. </para><para>I am advised that an estimated 2.4 million Sydney residents identify themselves as Christian—that is, some 66 per cent of the Sydney metropolitan population. I am advised that an estimated 1.8 million Sydney residents attend church services at least at Easter or Christmas. Thus it may be said there are in Sydney nearly two million Christians who adhere to the main feast days on the Christian calendar. In addition, an estimated 900,000 people in Sydney are reported to attend Christian church services at least monthly.</para><para>Compounding the fact that there is a high percentage of Christians in the Sydney metropolitan area, a large number of the population are social service recipients who rely on broadcast information. Such broadcast services include the necessity for talkback radio and other media access. The average percentage of Christians in any one Sydney electorate is between 25 and 30 per cent. In my electorate of Lowe, the percentage of practising Christians reaches nearly 50 per cent. Finally, there are an estimated 2,000 Christian places of worship throughout Sydney.</para><para>In every sense, the Christian voice is frustrated in its ability to be heard. With reference to 2CBA FM, it is often claimed that Sydney already has one Christian radio station. With respect, this is a false argument. 2CBA FM does a wonderful job. However, its target audience and scope is much narrower than the proposed broadcasting service's community of interest. Firstly, it is intended that Rhema Sydney will service the broader Sydney Christian community, who have long suffered without a voice, to broadcast their services and address their mass-market needs. Secondly, Rhema Sydney intends to cater for the larger, different and cross-denominational Christian markets, each of which have demonstrably different needs and interests within the greater Sydney metropolitan area. Programming will include talkback, alternative journalists' views on news and other public affairs items, and it will give the large Christian community a voice on the public airwaves. Moreover, Rhema Sydney intends to be a voice for people with disabilities, older Australians, youth and those marginalised in our society.</para><para>I call on the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts to intervene in this matter and accept the overwhelming support of the Sydney community and the demonstrable public interest in the granting of a temporary licence to Rhema Sydney on radio frequency 1386AM. The ABA has prevaricated, obfuscated and simply refused to admit that the Rhema proposal shines above any of the other bidders. The Rhema application easily outweighs the other contenders in size, public support and sheer quality.</para><para>The facts are undeniable: there is a great unmet need for Christian radio broadcasting in the Sydney metropolitan area. There is, in my opinion, utterly no justification whatsoever for refusing to grant Rhema Sydney a radio licence or at least a temporary licence. The necessity for the ABA to call for public submissions four times is absurd. The information gathered and the submissions received—many of them from members of this House—all point to the needs of the supporters of clearly the largest and most comprehensive submission for a licence for a radio station. I urge the minister to recognise the cross-party support, including support from members of her own coalition colleagues, in granting Rhema Sydney this transmission licence. </para><para>Mr Speaker, on another matter, you would be aware of my longstanding campaign to protect the public interest and Australia's democracy by exposing the Howard government's pandering to the interests of the major media proprietors in tearing down Australia's cross-media laws. Another appalling example of the Howard government's determination to serve the interests of the major media proprietors, ahead of the interests of the Australian people, is the cynical way the government has managed the broadcasting services antisiphoning list. The antisiphoning list is supposed to protect Australian households who do not have access to pay television from being denied important sporting events on free-to-air television. The antisiphoning list is designed to protect free-to-air television viewers by guaranteeing the rights of free-to-air television channels—that is, Nine, Seven, Ten, the ABC and SBS—to buy the broadcast rights to sporting events listed on the antisiphoning list. Some examples of events on the antisiphoning list, which is current until December 2010, include the Olympic Games, the Melbourne Cup, Australian rugby union and cricket test matches, the 2006 FIFA World Cup and rugby league and Australian rules football matches.</para><para>It is important to understand that the antisiphoning list does not guarantee that an event will be on free-to-air television. If the free-to-air broadcasters decline to purchase rights to listed events, the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts may delist such events, allowing pay television providers to acquire the rights to televise the event. Moreover, of far greater importance, especially to the millions of Australians who have always enjoyed the coverage of nationally significant sporting events on free-to-air television, is the loophole in the antisiphoning laws. This loophole has, very sadly, all but ensured that for the first time in more than 33 years Australia's Ashes test cricket series in England from July to September 2005 will not be broadcast on free-to-air television, despite the fact that it is on the antisiphoning list. How has this happened? Free-to-air broadcasters blame a loophole in the antisiphoning laws. Remember that the antisiphoning regime was established to ensure important sporting events, such as the Ashes cricket, would not become exclusive to pay-TV licensees, such as Foxtel.</para><para>Debate interrupted.</para></speech></subdebate.1></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>ADJOURNMENT</title><type>Adjournment</type><page.no>105</page.no></debateinfo><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—Order! It being 4.30 p.m., I propose the question:</para></talk.start><motion><para>That the House do now adjourn.</para></motion></interjection><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>ACT 2005 Cuboree</title><title>Bushfires: Eyre Peninsula</title><page.no>105</page.no></subdebateinfo><title>Bushfires: Eyre Peninsula</title><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>16:30:00</time.stamp><page.no>105</page.no><name role="metadata">Ellis, Annette, MP</name><name role="display">Ms ANNETTE ELLIS</name><name.id>5K6</name.id><electorate>Canberra</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—This evening I want to talk about an event held in the ACT during January, called the `Dream On' Cuboree for the ACT for 2005. Mr Peter Harris, a leading member of the scouting community in the ACT, came up with the original concept of a cuboree some years ago, and this most recent event was the seventh cuboree to be held. They are held every three years and we have witnessed growing participation and popularity each time. In fact, other states and territories are now holding or developing similar cuborees within their own jurisdictions.</para></talk.start><para>I had the pleasure of visiting the camp site during this three- to four-day event in the middle of January. The cuboree was held at the Kangaroo Flat camping ground here in Canberra—an area that was very savagely affected by the 18 January 2003 fires which occurred in the ACT. It is an absolute testament to the dedication and determination of everyone involved in the scouting movement in Canberra, under the leadership of the Chief Commissioner of Scouts ACT, Neville Tomkins, that they could even imagine going ahead and holding a cuboree of this size on this site, given the damage that was incurred just over two years ago. </para><para>The theme for this year's cuboree was `Dream on' with activities around the camp site encouraging the youngsters to establish their dreams, learn to have the courage to strive for them and learn how to encourage others in their team to dare to dream with them. A time capsule from the 1996 cuboree, containing the hopes and the dreams of cubs at that particular function, was dug up by some who were there at that time.</para><para>Altogether 1,150 people, including more than 800 cubs, plus leaders and volunteers, attended this cuboree. That is a pretty large number of folk under tents for three to four days in the heat of January in Canberra. If any member is planning a similarly large event, I can assure them that I have a recipe available from the people who ran this cuboree, which will produce spaghetti bolognaise for 1,150 people. The recipe starts with 195 kilograms of mince and 140 kilograms of spaghetti. That gives you an idea of the enormous size of this particular event.</para><para>When I visited, with other guests for the afternoon, I was absolutely moved by the enthusiasm of the leaders and the volunteers in ensuring that these young people from the ACT, New South Wales and some areas of South Australia, who came to participate in this three-yearly event, had the best time and learnt a great deal. There was a massive camaraderie and it was all a testament to the people who organised it.</para><para>On a second issue, I would like to make brief reference to the recent very tragic fires in South Australia. As the member for Canberra, I can assure the House and the member for Grey, Mr Wakelin, of my concern and compassion on behalf of the community here towards the community in South Australia and the Eyre Peninsula. The events there brought back bad memories for us and we know the sort of trauma that they were facing during those tragic fires in South Australia.</para><para>I have to commend the ACT government. They very quickly got in touch with the authorities in South Australia and offered ACT SES assistance. A public servant, Di Butcher, who achieved a great deal in successfully establishing and running the ACT Bushfire Recovery Centre, has, I believe, visited South Australia—at their wish—on several occasions to assist them to set up a similar sort of arrangement in that area of South Australia. We learnt a great deal through the necessities of the events surrounding the fires here in January 2003 and we were only too happy to offer whatever support, compassion and sympathy we could.</para><para>The residents of Duffy—part of my constituency that was very severely hit by the fires of 2003—immediately started fundraising and I believe they have already raised over $2,000, and that amount is increasing. The Duffy residents suffered the sort of damage that epitomised what was unfortunately felt here in Canberra and they immediately wanted to step in and offer some sort of support to those people on the Eyre Peninsula—and they are doing so, along with other people in my constituency. I take the opportunity to offer, on behalf of my constituents, our sympathies to those people who were so severely and tragically affected on the Eyre Peninsula in South Australia, and our ongoing support in any way that we can offer, given our experience. </para></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Mrs Melinda Poor</title><page.no>107</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>16:35:00</time.stamp><page.no>107</page.no><name role="metadata">Keenan, Michael, MP</name><name role="display">Mr KEENAN</name><name.id>E0J</name.id><electorate>Stirling</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—Yesterday in this House the member for Wills made reference to one of my constituents, Mrs Melinda Poor, who is also the Liberal candidate for the state seat of Balcatta in the upcoming election. The member for Wills recounted the events that occurred when Mrs Poor called into a radio station where the former member for Stirling and I were having a live debate. He believes her call caused a great deal of electoral grief for the Labor member for Stirling.</para></talk.start><para>I might remind the House of what actually transpired. The debate between the former member and me occurred not long after the Labor Party released their new family tax package. Astonishingly, this package would have disadvantaged struggling families in many areas of my electorate and around Australia. Mrs Poor called ABC radio to express her concern that her husband and three children would be roughly $500 worse off under the Labor Party's policy. At that time she was pregnant with her fourth child and when the baby was born she would have become roughly $1,000 worse off under Labor's policy. So Mrs Poor, quite rightly, called her local member and asked her what she thought of local families being disadvantaged in this way.</para><para>The former member for Stirling replied that the Labor Party would need to look at changing the package. At the time, this rightly caused a media storm as the opposition struggled to explain why they would adopt such a punitive tax regime. Following the former member for Stirling's comments, the Labor Party gagged her and she was not allowed to talk to the media for rest of the campaign. My campaign team and I really had a laugh when the Labor Party would not even let her finish a prearranged commitment to do a 90-second pre-recorded interview about her hobbies.</para><para>I would suggest to the member for Wills that it was not one of my constituents calling talkback radio to truthfully express her concern about how her family was going to suffer under a Labor government that caused the former member for Stirling electoral grief. It was the person who dreamed up Labor's failed electoral platform plus the actions of the former member that were to blame. The people of Stirling were not prepared to wear a party that attacked the living standards of those described by one Perth reporter as `world-class battlers'.</para><para>As to the concerns expressed that Mrs Poor and I had met before she called the radio, it is well known that we did. What Mrs Poor actually said later in the same article quoted by the member for Wills is that we did not know each other well. Fortunately, though, since that time I have come to know Mrs Poor because I have been campaigning with her as she is the Liberal candidate for Balcatta. I have spent time campaigning and listening to the concerns that the people of Stirling have about the Gallop state Labor government. I can tell the member for Wills that the people of the state electorate of Balcatta are sick of the indecision, the committees, the inquiries, the scoping studies, the reports and the total inability of the state Labor government to make decisions and to get on with the job of governing the great state of Western Australia. They are crying out to be represented by real people from their own communities who understand their needs and aspirations—exactly the sort of candidate represented by Mrs Poor. So I predict that, just as the people of Stirling rejected federal Labor, the people of WA will reject state Labor on 26 February and vote for Colin Barnett and his Liberal team to give us decisions, not more delays. </para></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>China: Mine Safety</title><page.no>108</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>16:39:00</time.stamp><page.no>108</page.no><name role="metadata">Ferguson, Martin, MP</name><name role="display">Mr MARTIN FERGUSON</name><name.id>LS4</name.id><electorate>Batman</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I rise this evening to talk on the issue of mine safety in China. At a time when Australia's relationship with China is becoming increasingly important to our economic future, I address the House this evening on a subject that must not be ignored in the context of negotiating a bilateral trade agreement, future investment flows and the production and manufacture of our traded resources, goods and services. That subject is, of course, human rights and core labour standards.</para></talk.start><para>Earlier this week a massive gas explosion ripped through the Sunjiawan coalmine in north-eastern China, killing more than 200 workers. This is a great tragedy for the families of those workers and their communities, and I am sure all Australians extend their deepest sympathy to them. The incident itself is particularly concerning because the Sunjiawan colliery is one of the bigger, more modern mines in China and because the blast follows a complete overhaul of safety ordered by the Prime Minister. This followed two earlier underground disasters late last year in which 166 miners were killed in Shaanxi and 148 killed in Henan. Officially, and interestingly, it is reported that more than 6,000 workers were killed in coalmines alone in China last year. But human rights and labour organisations claim that the real figure is closer to 20,000 deaths per year.</para><para>I hope we would agree on both sides of the parliament that the main goal of economic development and trade is to advance the human condition. I hope we would also agree that respect for human life and the protection of human rights is and must remain at the core of all our public policy. As the President of the ACTU noted earlier this week, free trade advocates would argue that the market will automatically provide for improvements in living standards for working people and for the protection of their human rights. This ignores the fact that all markets are actually regulated at some level. For example, the World Trade Organisation establishes trade rules incorporating a dispute resolution process and an enforcement mechanism, and those rules are supported by all the major nations. Similarly, the International Labour Office promulgates international labour standards to assure human rights and effective minimum standards for working people and employer representatives, yet these rules are seen by the major nations as a fetter on market forces.</para><para>Our government, unfortunately, refuses to sign ILO Convention 176, the Safety and Health in Mines Convention, not because our mining industry cannot meet it but because it is a government ideologically opposed to the rights of working men and women to guaranteed minimum labour standards and to the right of the ILO to promote them. This is a government committed to dragging Australian labour standards, including health and safety, down to the lowest common denominator of the trading nations. This is unacceptable to the opposition and it is unacceptable to the great majority of working men and women in Australia. We in the Labor party believe in the right to collectively bargain and in the need for effective minimum standards to provide the market with parameters that ensure working men and women get a fair share of the fruits of their endeavours. Core labour standards are also essential to guarantee more sustainable development and rising standards of living for people in poorer countries. There is no trickle-down effect.</para><para>At the moment China is the key market supporting Australia's resources boom, but it is also a potential competitor in resources trade and it is certainly a competitor in manufacturing. It is therefore incumbent on the government, when entering discussions with China about bilateral trade, to also talk about equal core labour standards that uphold the rights of working people to a safe workplace, the right to fair minimum wages and conditions and the right to collectively bargain. It is time for the government, too, to look at the track record of companies on labour practices when they invest in this country, particularly in the area of health and safety. This is one of the areas in which the Treasurer and the Foreign Investment Review Board could, and should, impose conditions on foreign investment in the nation's best interest. </para><para>It is time for Australia to play a bigger role in international labour markets, particularly in promoting health and safety in the workplace and respect for human life. International trade negotiations are one of the key avenues we can and must use to do this. It is now up to our trade negotiators in the proposed Australia-China free trade agreement to have regard to these accepted minimum international standards, core working standards developed by a tripartite process at the International Labour Office—employer, worker and government representatives—standards which any decent human being would expect. <inline font-style="italic">(Time expired)</inline></para></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Mr Mamdouh Habib</title><page.no>1</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>16:44:00</time.stamp><page.no>1</page.no><name role="metadata">Wood, Jason, MP</name><name role="display">Mr WOOD</name><name.id>E0F</name.id><electorate>La Trobe</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I stand here today to highlight the threats we face in the war on terrorism. As a former senior sergeant with the Victoria Police Counter Terrorism Coordination Unit, this issue is particularly close to me. Australians abroad have endured much heartache at the hands of terrorists from the September 11 plane crashes in America to the bombing of the Sari nightclub in Bali. The threat of terrorism still hangs over Australia, and our darkest hour may be yet to come.</para></talk.start><para>The release of Mamdouh Habib from Guantanamo Bay and his recent interviews raise the dilemma: is he a terrorist or a person who for no reason has been targeted by authorities both here and abroad? As Habib was recently released and has spoken openly about his experiences in detention, which have been well reported in the media and by the Australian Labor Party, I feel it is important to look at what we currently know about his experiences prior to his arrest in Pakistan in 2001.</para><para>In 1991, while in New York, Habib was invited by Ibrahim el-Gabrowny to rally support outside the courthouse where el-Gabrowny's cousin el-Sayyid Nosair was standing trial for the murder of Rabbi Meir Kahane. Apart from Habib and el-Gabrowny, Nosair's supporters in the courtroom included Mahmud Abouhalima. Abouhalima, el-Gabrowny and Habib were all followers of Omar Abdul Rahman, otherwise known as the `blind sheikh'—a militant cleric who calls for his followers to kill the enemies of God. Habib continued to have contact with el-Gabrowny and Omar Abdul Rahman after leaving New York. He even rallied other members of his Sydney mosque to help Rahman financially and to protest against his imprisonment.</para><para>On 26 February 1993, a bombing at the World Trade Centre in New York killed six people and injured over 1,000. Habib's friends, Abouhalima, el-Gabrowny and Rahman were all later arrested, charged and convicted for their involvement with the World Trade Centre bombing in 1993. Back in Australia, Sheikh Abu Ayman, head of the Haldon Street prayer hall in Lakemba, told the ABC's <inline font-style="italic">Four Corners </inline>program entitled `Worst of the Worst?' that Habib was lobbying for members to join a jihad and that he had turned up to the prayer hall wearing a ninja outfit on one occasion and an Osama bin Laden t-shirt on another. </para><para>Habib would later assist fundraising efforts for the Chechen rebels. There are reported links between the Chechnya rebels and al-Qaeda but, regardless, Chechen rebels have been responsible for a range of terrorist attacks, from the 700 hostages taken at the Moscow theatre in October 2002 to the Beslan school massacre in September 2004, where over 320 people, half of them children, were killed.</para><para>Habib's behaviour at the Haldon Street prayer hall led to Sheikh Abu Ayman banning him from the group. In 2000, Habib travelled to Pakistan for two months and upon his return announced his plans to go to Afghanistan to join the bin Laden camp. Mr Habib's friend Ibrahim Fraser told <inline font-style="italic">Four Corners </inline>that, in a conversation they had had, Habib had explained that he wanted to live in a bin Laden camp and that it would be a good life.</para><para>On 29 July 2001, Habib again visited Pakistan. It is believed that during this visit Mr Habib travelled to Afghanistan, as well as to Pakistan, and participated in an advanced al-Qaeda training course. Habib was captured after the September 11 attacks in Pakistan with two Germans: Ibrahim Diab and Bekim Ademi. Diab and Ademi were part of the Hamburg al-Qaeda cell led by Mohammed Atta, the lead hijacker in the September 11 attacks. Diab and Ademi were arrested after participating in an al-Qaeda training camp near Kabul.</para><para>Habib has not provided details as to why he was in Afghanistan, preferring to keep this a mystery, even during Channel 9's <inline font-style="italic">60 Minutes</inline><inline font-style="italic">,</inline><inline font-style="italic"></inline>where they paid him for half a story. The accounts of Mamdouh Habib's whereabouts over the past decade suggest a long association with figures tied to the al-Qaeda network, a keen interest in fundraising for convicted terrorist figures, and a person who has tried to recruit others to support a jihad holy war and who has a travel itinerary based around Afghanistan, which at the time was a haven for terrorists. It is a shame that <inline font-style="italic">60 Minutes</inline>, with their $200,000 terrorist money, and the Australian Labor Party have let Habib's lies get in the way of the truth.</para><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>JK6</name.id><name role="metadata">McClelland, Robert, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McClelland</name></talker><para>—Mr Speaker, I raise a point of order. I ask that the member for La Trobe withdraw his last comment accusing the Labor Party of being associated with lies concerning Mamdouh Habib. That is clearly offensive to representatives of the Labor Party, and it should be withdrawn.</para></talk.start></interjection><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—In deference to the member for Barton, I ask the member for La Trobe to withdraw that last statement.</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>E0F</name.id><name role="metadata">Wood, Jason, MP</name><name role="display">Mr WOOD</name></talker><para>—On the Speaker's request, without condition, I withdraw.</para></talk.start></continue></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Mr Mark Latham</title><page.no>2</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>16:49:00</time.stamp><page.no>2</page.no><name role="metadata">Albanese, Anthony, MP</name><name role="display">Mr ALBANESE</name><name.id>R36</name.id><electorate>Grayndler</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I rise tonight to pay tribute to the parliamentary career ended prematurely by the ill health of Mark Latham, the member for Werriwa. Mark was elected on 29 January 1994. It was appropriate that he was the member for Werriwa given that his mentor—the great Gough Whitlam—represented that seat with such distinction, including as Prime Minister in the years between 1972 and 1975. Mark Latham's service federally followed other public service, in particular his service as a local councillor on Liverpool council between 1987 and 1994 and as mayor from 1991.</para></talk.start><para>Mark had humble origins. He was proud of being a `houso'. He never shied away from being the boy from Green Valley. He was a person of ideas. He was a prolific writer. He helped write five books, most notably <inline font-style="italic">Civilising global capital: new thinking for Australian Labor</inline>. He was a great communicator verbally, and I think this was his greatest asset. He was articulate, clever, incisive, passionate and humorous. He could be tough. He was devastating on his opponents, but he could also be gentle, as he was when he spoke about his mum, and that certainly endeared him to me on a personal level. </para><para>I did not always agree with Mark's views—far from it. We had major disagreements over economic policy and social policy both within and outside the forums of the Australian Labor Party. Mark, however, was always prepared to engage in political debate. He was indeed a great political figure. Whether you agreed with him or not, he always made a difference; you noticed that Mark Latham was there, both within and outside the party.</para><para>One of his last public forums was in my electorate of Grayndler, at Leichhardt Town Hall, on Monday, 22 November last year. We sent out invitations. People thought it was rather odd that I was doorknocking just after the election. Some 600 or 700 people filled the hall—we do not know, because it was packed. Many people were turned away. He engaged on a whole range of issues. He took questions from all comers.</para><para>I did not vote for him to be leader of the Labor Party. I believed that Kim Beazley was the best prospect to win the prime ministership. But as the leader he certainly set the agenda. He had the Howard government on the run over issues such as parliamentary superannuation and the free trade agreement, where he came up with a clever and principled solution to some of the internal disagreements the Labor Party had of moving amendments to protect the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme and to protect our cultural content. In the end, the government had to cave in to a Labor position. He led a principled position in opposition to the Iraq war. I marched with Mark, young Oliver and my family at the demonstration in Sydney where more than a quarter of a million people marched in favour of peace just before that war began.</para><para>It is unfortunate that Mark's career has been cut short by ill health. I wish him, his wife, Janine, and his wonderful two boys, Oliver and Isaac, all the best. Parliamentary life is very hard; it can be particularly hard on people's health. Mark has made a decision that is in the interests of himself and his family. I am sure that all parliamentarians wish him well.</para></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Paterson Electorate: Jetstar Fleet Maintenance Base</title><page.no>111</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>16:54:00</time.stamp><page.no>111</page.no><name role="metadata">Baldwin, Robert, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BALDWIN</name><name.id>LL6</name.id><electorate>Paterson</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I advise the House of the announcement by Jetstar at Williamtown Airport on 11 February to expand the heavy maintenance hangar at Newcastle. That is an investment of $29 million. The question is: why did they take the opportunity to choose Newcastle? There was extensive lobbying for the hangar facility for the maintenance of the A320 fleet to be located in New Zealand, in Singapore, in Hong Kong or in another area of Australia. What came through was the ability of the people in the Hunter—the skill sets that we have in the Hunter.</para></talk.start><para>There are currently 82 people working in highly skilled jobs at the Jetstar facility at Newcastle airport. What is impressive is that 25 of those people are apprentices. They are committed to developing a skills base that will serve the country well. The announcement of the $29 million investment at Newcastle airport to service the A320 fleet will lead to an additional 50 jobs over five years, and I understand that more apprenticeships will be rolled out over that period. I am pleased that this will involve upskilling young people in our local area.</para><para>We also have in my electorate, on the other side of the airstrip, RAAF Base Williamtown. One of the key aspects of RAAF Base Williamtown, and it is the premier RAAF base in Australia, is that a lot of highly skilled technicians get posted there. They discover the lifestyle of the Hunter Valley. I think I am correct in saying that one of the highest exit rates from the Air Force is to Williamtown—whether or not they go to another posting afterwards, they come back to our region, to Medowie and Salamander Bay. Those high levels of skills allowed British Aerospace to set up and build the Hawk lead-in fighters. We have a magnificent facility in our region that can service, build and develop aircraft. This project will expand on that. I can remember when this hangar facility was originally started by Impulse Airlines to service the Beechcraft 1900 aircraft. When QantasLink took over Impulse Airlines the aircraft were shifted up to the B717s—a new aircraft brought into the Australian fleet—and now we are moving to the A320s. </para><para>I am concerned at the reports of an open skies agreement between Australia and Singapore. If agreed to, this agreement will see an open arrangement for Singapore Airlines to fly from the east coast of Australia to the west coast of the USA. Singapore's Minister for Transport, Mr Yew Cheow Tong, has met with our government officials this week in Canberra. He said:</para><quote><para>It will give travellers a wider choice. I think it will result in lower fares and it will bring in additional visitors into Australia ... It is good for the economy and I do think they [the government] recognise that. There is scope for a lot more tourists in Australia.</para></quote><para>I do not dispute that, but I have to stand up for the people in my electorate. I have to stand up for the skills base on which Jetstar and Qantas have made their decision to invest in my electorate. I do not want to see competition at the expense of jobs at the airport in my electorate.</para><para>Today Qantas posted its half-yearly results to 31 December. On a revenue base of $6.4 billion, it has announced a profit before tax of $601.3 million. There are competitive pressures in the airline industry, and part of that competitive pressure is to maintain a profit so that it can service the needs of its shareholders. Qantas will be establishing 400 new flight attendants, to be based out of London. If we open up our airways to other countries—countries whose airlines are subsidised by their governments—Qantas will have to look further offshore to reduce its costs. I fear that those jobs in maintenance may end up being located offshore. We had to bid strongly against New Zealand, against Hong Kong and against Singapore to have the fleet maintenance base in Australia. I say to our Deputy Prime Minister and the Minister for Industry, Tourism and Resources: do not proceed with the open skies policy, because it will be to the detriment of my workers. <inline font-style="italic">(Time expired)</inline></para><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">SPEAKER, The</name><name role="display">The SPEAKER</name></talker><para>—Order! It being 5.00 p.m., the debate is interrupted.</para></talk.start><para><inline font-weight="bold">House adjourned at 5.00 p.m.</inline></para></interjection></speech></subdebate.1></debate></chamber.xscript><maincomm.xscript><business.start><day.start>2005-02-17</day.start><para>—————</para><para><inline font-weight="bold">The DEPUTY SPEAKER (Hon. I.R. Causley) </inline>took the chair at 9.40 a.m.</para></business.start><debate><debateinfo><title>STATEMENTS BY MEMBERS</title><type>Statements by Members</type><page.no>119</page.no></debateinfo><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Sister Janet Mead</title><page.no>119</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>09:40:00</time.stamp><page.no>119</page.no><name role="metadata">Georganas, Steve, MP</name><name role="display">Mr GEORGANAS</name><name.id>DZY</name.id><electorate>Hindmarsh</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I rise today to talk about one of the most amazing people I have had the good fortune to meet. Sister Janet Mead of the Sisters of Mercy was last year made South Australian of the year. She accepted the honour in Glenelg, which is within the electorate of Hindmarsh. I think of Sister Mead as South Australia's very own Mother Theresa. I know that if she reads this speech she will chastise me, because her humility is also key to the way she lives her life and the work that she does. When most of us walk down the street and see a bedraggled unkempt man stumbling towards us we instantly put up all of the barriers we can. Without thinking, we see this person as different, as bad and as a danger to us, so we ignore him, pretend we do not see him and tell ourselves that there is nothing we can do to help him. We think that it is up to him to pull himself out of the life he lives and learn how to live like the rest of us. Of course that is complete rubbish; it is all about creating reasons to turn our backs on someone in need.</para></talk.start><para>Sister Janet Mead does not tell herself those sorts of lies. She spends her life with the poorest, most marginalised and most isolated people in our society. She works with the Adelaide Day Care Centre for Homeless Persons, the Brian Burdekin Clinic and Westcare. She helps homeless people overcome the tremendous challenges they face as they live their lives. The Adelaide day care centre has created a community for homeless people. Amongst other things, they can share a cooked lunch, work in the vegie garden or fix old furniture.</para><para>It is easy to misunderstand this work as some sort of sacrifice on the part of Sister Mead, but she feels fortunate to live her life in this way. She speaks of having learned so much from the people she works with. She says that she has learned a view of the world that places love above status—what a lesson for all of us whose lives are entangled in this place. Sister Mead teaches us that what she does is within reach of all of us. It is possible to find our open-heartedness and give a little, even for those who have forgotten that they ever had a soft spot. She teaches us that, in doing so, we can grow. One day we might be brave enough to give a smile to someone who scares us and another day we might be able to make a donation or buy an edition of the <inline font-style="italic">Big Issue</inline>. In doing so, we open our hearts enough to make our lives and the lives of those we love a little easier because that is what happens when we give to others without any agenda or any expectation of getting something back.</para><para>Sister Janet Mead says she reaps the most amazing rewards from the people she works with. She tells a story of a homeless man who told her, `Life's journey is not to arrive at the grave safely in a well-preserved body but to skid in sideways, totally worn out, shouting “Holy hell, what a ride!”' We have all had the good fortune at one time or another to meet someone whose generosity and openness could make us realise that something was not quite right in our lives. Sister Janet Mead is one of those people. For all the fear that we put in the space between ourselves and anyone else who we perceive to be different from us, Sister Janet Mead teaches that we are fooling ourselves and tricking ourselves out of learning that when we ignore suffering we contribute to it.</para><para>As a society we have a great deal to learn about becoming a community. Increasingly people are finding that the teachings of Christianity can help us to connect with our world, but as we do that we must be watchful that we do not close off from others who we perceive to have lost their way. When we do help those people we must be watchful that we do not define Christian values too narrowly because, as Sister Janet Mead demonstrates each day, Jesus Christ would have turned his back on no-one. <inline font-style="italic">(Time expired)</inline></para></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Hinkler Electorate</title><page.no>114</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>09:43:00</time.stamp><page.no>114</page.no><name role="metadata">Neville, Paul, MP</name><name role="display">Mr NEVILLE</name><name.id>KV5</name.id><electorate>Hinkler</electorate><party>NATS</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—Honourable members would know I am not one easily given to hubris, but I would like to highlight the clearest possible demonstration of a turnaround of fortunes of two sectors of my electorate of Hinkler in Central Queensland. Since the Howard government came to office there have been huge improvements in national indicators such as unemployment, interest rates and inflation. We are now seeing this filter down into areas which have had endemic levels of unemployment in the past.</para></talk.start><para>My electorate of Hinkler, and for that matter the entire Wide Bay-Burnett region, is one such area. But the Wide Bay-Burnett region has experienced the biggest percentage drop in unemployment in Australia in the past 12 months, and my electorate has just had the best percentage increase in bulk-billing rates in Queensland and one of the best in Australia over the last 12 months. Wide Bay-Burnett's unemployment rate now sits at six per cent, down a full 3.6 per cent in December 2004 from December 2003. Over the same period, employment numbers, now at 99,100, increased by 10.4 per cent—a remarkable figure. This can be clearly attributed to sound economic management of the nation, which has given businesses the confidence to invest in regional areas and to provide much needed local employment.</para><para>The region has also gone ahead in the health sphere, with Hinkler's bulk-billing rate going up by 12.8 per cent between December 2003 and December 2004, and it now stands at 60.5 per cent. This might not seem significant to many members but consider this: Hinkler's bulk-billing rate has gone up by 16.9 per cent since 2002 when, in many other parts of the nation, it went down. I am confident we will see further improvements because we have not yet seen the full effect of the coalition's additional $7.65 payment for concession card holders and children under 16 or the annual impact of the doctors being paid the full schedule fee.</para><para>These two indicators fly in the face of the ALP's doom and gloom message that they put out in my electorate during the election campaign. It is the clearest possible demonstration that they were wrong. The area has often been targeted as one of the worst unemployment areas in Australia; it had endemic unemployment. We now see the electorate, as a result of our economic management, coming out of that. I congratulate the government on its focus and on behalf of my electors I thank the government for the improvements that have made an area that was very much challenged in past years a better one. <inline font-style="italic">(Time expired)</inline></para></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Health: Dental Services</title><page.no>114</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>09:46:00</time.stamp><page.no>114</page.no><name role="metadata">Bird, Sharon, MP</name><name role="display">Ms BIRD</name><name.id>DZP</name.id><electorate>Cunningham</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—Some questions need to be seriously asked at this point in time and in this place. What kind of country do we live in when a government minister tells citizens with a serious health problem that they should hope that some charitable doctor—or, in this case, dentist—will come forward to solve their problem? What kind of country do we live in that a government can spend $66 billion in a matter of minutes in an effort to get re-elected but hopes that a charitable person will come forward and pick up the slack for an area of serious government neglect? What depths have we sunk to as a society when we will not spend any money to fix the teeth of low-income earners and pensioners even after 14 years of economic growth, record high tax revenues and a $4 billion surplus? </para></talk.start><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>AK6</name.id><name role="metadata">Gash, Joanna, MP</name><name role="display">Mrs Gash</name></talker><para>—That's the state government's job.</para></talk.start></interjection><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>DZP</name.id><name role="metadata">Bird, Sharon, MP</name><name role="display">Ms BIRD</name></talker><para>—Not under the Constitution, the member for Gilmore. Australia is that kind of country in the year 2005. The serious dereliction of public dental health that has emerged in the last few days is, sadly, not a new story. Since the year 2000, the Illawarrra Dental Health Action Group has been campaigning to `stop the rot'. As recently as the last election campaign, my attention was drawn to the case of a pensioner in Wollongong, in addition to the case that was reported in yesterday's <inline font-style="italic">Sydney Morning Herald</inline>, who had two teeth remaining. He has been patiently waiting for his dentures to be made, because he could not afford to pay for them himself. He was not complaining but he was certainly keen to tell me that he dreamed of the day when he could again enjoy a steak or even a piece of fruit.</para></talk.start></continue><para>When Mr Abbott told John Laws on Tuesday, `There are lots of tragedies in life,' he could not have been more correct, but the biggest tragedy faced by this country right now in health is that we have a completely uncaring minister. At the last election, Labor pledged $300 million towards a Commonwealth dental program in an attempt to fix the decay that the government has allowed to set in and to cut the waiting lists among low-income earners and pensioners, which was a successful program of the former Keating government.</para><para>The government and the minister have acknowledged that the Keating government's program was a success—that is, until it was axed in 1997. The program reduced waiting lists and gave those in our community who could least afford it the opportunity to access dental health services that can reasonably be expected to be available in a modern first-world country. When times get a bit tough, the government is often quick to blame the states, but a cursory glance at section 51 of the Constitution shows that the powers of the federal government extend to dental services. I am sure they would not want to give away other sections of section 51, such as trade, tax, telephones and trademarks, so why the flick pass on dental health? <inline font-style="italic">(Time expired)</inline></para></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Flinders Electorate: Education and Training</title><page.no>115</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>09:49:00</time.stamp><page.no>115</page.no><name role="metadata">Hunt, Gregory, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HUNT</name><name.id>00AMV</name.id><electorate>Flinders</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister for the Environment and Heritage</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I want to talk today about the potential for technical college education within and servicing the electorate of Flinders. I want to set out the need, the opportunity and the steps forward. The need is very clear. The technical college education at state level has largely been failing young people on the Mornington Peninsula, at the top of Westernport and on Bass Coast. That is a result of changes made over a decade ago, but the gaps are there. In the towns of Hastings and Koo Wee Rup and on the Bass Coast there is a young population with needs to develop skills, be they in welding, plumbing, some form of manufacturing, engineering, marine, maritime or IT.</para></talk.start><para>In relation to that need, there are two very clear proposals which I wish to present to the House today. The first is for a technical college, under the Australian technical college system, based in the south-east of Melbourne. That college would have, at the very least, two annexes which are relevant to my electorate. The first of those would be an annex in the town of Hastings, under the Australian technical college proposal, in conjunction with Westernport Secondary College. This is something to which I am committed and for which I want to fight. What I believe about this is that if an annex of an Australian technical college were constructed at Westernport Secondary College, the opportunity would exist to help students with a marine and maritime focus to cooperate with BlueScope Steel, the Mornington Peninsula Shire, Westernport Secondary and all of the maritime related companies and firms within the area. I think that, in conjunction with a campus at Pakenham servicing Koo Wee Rup, Clyde, Devon Meadows and Lang Lang, which would have a building and agricultural focus, this is a tremendous opportunity. </para><para>The second part of the proposal is to service the Bass Coast region through the town of Wonthaggi. I believe that there is potential for an annex for a Gippsland based Australian technical college. The government is committed to a Gippsland based Australian technical college. My argument, in conjunction with Russell Broadbent, the member for McMillan, is that we should push to have some representation through a local annex in Wonthaggi. That would be a tremendous boost for the people of Phillip Island, San Remo, Granville, the hills areas, Dalyston, Kilcunda and Wonthaggi. I put those two proposals on the table. I endorse them and I am going to fight for them.</para></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Rural and Regional Australia: Population</title><page.no>116</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>09:52:00</time.stamp><page.no>116</page.no><name role="metadata">Grierson, Sharon, MP</name><name role="display">Ms GRIERSON</name><name.id>00AMP</name.id><electorate>Newcastle</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I would like to draw the House's attention to the declining birth rates in regional Australia, particularly in the Hunter-New England region, in which my electorate of Newcastle is located. The latest figures show that between 1999 and 2003 the number of mothers giving birth per year in the Hunter-New England region fell by 4.7 per cent. Statewide the figure fell by 1.1 per cent. That means the number of mothers giving birth in our region is declining more than four times faster than it is in the rest of the state. Sadly, this trend is evident in other regions of New South Wales. If it continues, regions do face the danger of terminal decline and Australia is in danger of losing one of the most important aspects of its identity.</para></talk.start><para>For a government whose junior partner is The Nationals, it is shameful that the regions do face annihilation. For a government that prides itself on family values, we have seen precious few policies to assist regional families or sustain rural and regional communities. Young people move away to gain education and do not return. Job insecurity drives people to the cities, and skills and knowledge disappear with them. Health and disability services dwindle, and the increasing costs of isolation and distance continue unchecked. Vital infrastructure that links regional communities and provides expanded market opportunities is neglected or removed. And what is the first off the block in the reform agenda of this newly re-elected government? We have had a hypocritical moral values debate about abortion, tighter wages control through a new industrial relations regime, tax cuts for the wealthy and competition deregulation that will make it harder for small business. What we do need are clever policy ideas and reform that boost productivity by sustaining regional economies, by supporting family friendly workplaces and by reducing the economic barriers to having children—not the same tired old agenda that the government will be bringing back and ramming through the Senate from July.</para><para>The Rural Doctors Association of Australia tells us that the number of GP obstetricians in New South Wales has halved since 1996. In fact the greatest medical work force shortages are in regional Australia. Recent estimates of the cost of seeing a child born last year through education from preschool to university suggest a price tag of $200,000. If you add the cost for regional parents of sending their children away for education, it will be even more. Expenditure per child-care place under the Howard government has dropped by a massive 10.2 per cent, and now we find that parents will not see a cent of the promised 30 per cent rebate on child-care fees until the 2006-07 financial year. </para><para>The essentials of raising children have become much more difficult under the Howard government. Is it any wonder then that the Australian Institute of Family Studies reports that one of the main factors dissuading people from starting a family is economic insecurity. Yet the report also found that 90 per cent of people surveyed want to have children. We must get our family policies right, especially in our regions, to allow people to fulfil their parenting dreams. The Howard government's cynical regional rorts scheme may have bought it another term in government, but it will never be a substitute for the real policies needed to help families in regional Australia. <inline font-style="italic">(Time expired)</inline></para></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Medicare: Bulk-Billing</title><page.no>117</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>09:55:00</time.stamp><page.no>117</page.no><name role="metadata">Slipper, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr SLIPPER</name><name.id>0V5</name.id><electorate>Fisher</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The member for Newcastle is quite correct when she points out that the declining birth rate is one of the challenges that we face as a nation. The combination of the ageing population and the declining birth rate present policy challenges which this government has commenced to addressed. I do, however, wonder where the member for Newcastle stands on the issue of the Medicare funding of abortions, which is of course a conscience vote—as it should be—in this place. The fact that we have 100,000 abortions in this country each year no doubt does move in some direction towards reducing the national birth rate. However, I did not rise in this chamber to talk about that particular topic at this time.</para></talk.start><para>I am pleased to announce that the bulk-billing rate in my electorate of Fisher has continued to rise as a result of the Howard government's investment in Medicare and is now at 70.2 per cent. The bulk-billing rate in Fisher increased 10.3 percentage points in 2004 compared with 2003. This latest increase shows that the Howard government's investment in Medicare is delivering more affordable GP services for everyone living on the Sunshine Coast and in surrounding regions. This increase in Fisher reflects the national trend. The health minister has done a wonderful job in helping to boost the rate of bulk-billing. The national GP bulk-billing rate is at its highest level in 2½ years. The rate increased again during the December quarter 2004 and is now 72.4 per cent, an increase of 5.9 percentage points since the government introduced its Medicare package a year ago. The national GP bulk-billing rate for people 65 years of age and over also increased during the December quarter to its highest level in almost four years of 82.7 per cent, an increase of 8.7 percentage points on the December quarter of 2003.</para><para>Locally, as well as nationally, more than seven out of 10 GP attendances are being bulk-billed, and across the nation more than eight out of 10 GP attendances for people over 65 are being bulk-billed. This is the first time in 10 years that the national bulk-billing rate has increased over four successive quarters. GPs who bulk-bill Commonwealth concession card holders and children under 16 receive an extra $5.10 or $7.65, depending on their location. This is in addition to a recent increase in the Medicare rebate to $30.85. GPs now have more incentive to bulk-bill their patients—for example, if a GP in Tasmania bulk-bills a concession card holder or child then he or she will receive $38.50. This compares with a rate of $25.70 in November 2003. Since the introduction of bulk-billing incentives, all states and territories have experienced an increase in GP bulk-billing rates. In my state of Queensland, the most wonderful part of the country in which to live, the bulk-billing rate has increased by 7.6 percentage points to 69.3 per cent. The government do have the recipe right. We are delivering for Australians, particularly those Australians who are fortunate enough to live on Queensland's wonderful Sunshine Coast. </para><interjection><talk.start><talker><name.id>10000</name.id><name role="metadata">Causley, Ian (The DEPUTY SPEAKER)</name><name role="display">The DEPUTY SPEAKER</name></talker><para><inline font-weight="bold"> (Hon. I.R. Causley)</inline>—Order! In accordance with standing order 193 the time for members' statements has concluded.</para></talk.start></interjection></speech></subdebate.1></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>GOVERNOR-GENERAL'S SPEECH</title><type>Governor-General's Speech</type><page.no>118</page.no></debateinfo><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Address-in-Reply</title><page.no>118</page.no></subdebateinfo><para>Debate resumed from 16 February, on motion by <inline font-weight="bold">Mrs Markus</inline>:</para><motion><para>That the address be agreed to.</para></motion><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>09:59:00</time.stamp><page.no>118</page.no><name role="metadata">Baldwin, Robert, MP</name><name role="display">Mr BALDWIN</name><name.id>LL6</name.id><electorate>Paterson</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—It is a pleasure to be able to stand in this chamber once again and make an address-in-reply as the re-elected member for Paterson. Paterson's curse is a weed which, no doubt, Mr Deputy Speaker Causley, in your role as a rural member, you would only too well understand. It is a noxious weed to livestock. It spreads like another suburban weed, lantana—and like lantana its flowers are purple. When you see a field of it off in the distance and do not know what it is, you might think it is rather picturesque. But, as you would know, Mr Deputy Speaker, it is a curse.</para></talk.start><para>It is a curse because it is virtually impossible to get rid of and it can kill off your livestock. Paterson's curse also applied to the federal seat of Paterson, which, since it was recreated in 1993, had not been won by the sitting member once. Last year, I broke politics' Paterson's curse. I want to recognise that there are many new members in this parliament and I want to remark on the people that they have replaced. When I was voted out in 1998 it took me a long time to come to terms with failure. For the first time I had to take a long hard look at what I did when I was the member for Paterson. I have done that again this time around and I can honestly say it is much nicer to analyse the results from my current position, as opposed to the position I was in after the election in 1998.</para><para>We in the coalition showed that elections in marginal seats do not start when the election is called—they run over the entire term. We—my staff and I—worked very hard to attract more funding, better services and better representation over the entire three-year period. We never gave up fighting for the things that were important to the people in Paterson. It is a fight we will continue over the next term of this government and beyond. We have a hunger to improve services and get more funding for areas such as aged care, roads and health.</para><para>Paterson has four local government areas in its boundaries: Port Stephens, Dungog, Gloucester, and Great Lakes, as well as small parts of the cities of Maitland and Newcastle. Two of these areas are coastal, two are rural and the parts of Maitland and Newcastle are regional, almost urban. The coastal communities are largely made up of retirees. The bay areas of Fullerton Cove, Stockton Bight, Fingal Bay, Shoal Bay, Nelson Bay, Salamander Bay, Tanilba Bay and Lemon Tree Passage are attracting more affluent retirees. In Foster-Tuncurry in the north the retirees are not as affluent as they are in the south. Statistics show they are about five years older on average than their counterparts in the lower part of the electorate. The Maitland area, including Thornton and Morpeth, is a more prosperous area. Thornton is one of the fastest growing suburbs in the state and there are many young families in the suburb. </para><para>Beresfield, Woodbury and Tarro are older suburbs that are affordable for low-income earners and still in an area which is close to health, transport and education facilities. The shire of Gloucester is a farming area for mainly dairy and beef. Farmers have done it tough over the past two years or so, with many experiencing hardship as a result of the drought and dairy deregulation. Every small town along the Bucketts Way—Limeburners Creek, Allworth, Booral, Stroud, Stroud Road, Wards River, Craven and Stratford—has a popular hall, a voting place and a need for better roads, schools and, indeed, basic access to health care. Every small community along the Pacific Highway, whether it be Karuah, North Arm Cove, Tea Gardens, Hawks Nest, Nerong, Bulahdelah, Wootton, Coolongolook or Nabiac, has a hall, church or a meeting place. These communities may have a rural fire service or a church volunteer group. They may have a popular hall which is maintained by a small number of hardworking community committees.</para><para>The results for Paterson in the 2004 election varied from a primary vote swing to me of two per cent in the areas which were traditionally liberal to around 12 per cent in the areas which I would have considered Labor heartland. I am deeply humbled by the result. Although the election was in October last year this has been my first opportunity in the parliament to thank those who have helped me in the campaign. We expect our staff to know a little about a lot of things. We expect them to know about tax, telecommunications and Centrelink, to have a good local knowledge of our electorates, to keep us informed and on time and to get us to the right place. We ask them to work incredibly long hours during the sitting weeks and the non-sitting weeks. Then we back up and expect them to put in three times the effort during an election.</para><para>I want to personally thank my staff—Mike, Anna and Julia—for being such a tremendous support to me and our community over the past years. I also want to thank my campaign team for their tremendous work: Bob Geoghegan, the campaign director and John Murphy, the treasurer. On the advisory team I want to thank Josh Hodges, Sally Dover, Michelle Moffatt, Daryl Lewis and Peter West. I want to thank Sally Dover's husband, Gary, and Alan Ray for driving my mobile office around the electorate for me when Daryl could not. And thank you to Alan's better half, Marty Ray, for keeping him company. It was a sad day when the mobile office rolled and was written off a week out from polling day. But, within days, I had a replacement on the road to make sure the people did not forget me and were not denied access.</para><para>On polling day, there were around 600 people working for me in the electorate of Paterson, and I sincerely thank them for all their help. I cannot name them all in the time allowed, but there are some community leaders that I would like to thank—Ross Presgrave; Margaret Godsmark; Gerry Jermon; Sue Slater; Jan McWilliams; Peter Mason and his wife, Anne Mason; Trevor and Jacquie Wark; Sean and Robyn Brennan—who have all become community leaders through the Port Stephens crime forum work. Doreen Bradley, a natural leader in her community who has been recognised with an OAM, has become a great supporter because we stood up and fought for the issues that were important to her and her community.</para><para>I would like to thank the Young Liberals team, who letterboxed the hilliest parts of our electorate. My thanks also go out to the former state director, Scott Morrison, who managed the state secretariat better than it had ever been managed before. We will miss you. At the end, I owe especial thanks to my brothers and sisters in Christ in the Raymond Terrace Christian Life Centre, in particular my pastors, Colin Haddow and Rod Smith. All members in this House need the support of their families, and my especial thanks go to my wife, Cynthia, who gives me unconditional support, my twin sons, David and Robbie—I had the proudest moment last Sunday in witnessing their first parade as naval cadets from training ship <inline font-style="italic">Tobruk</inline>—and of course my daughter, Samantha. I thank them all. </para><para>Now that we are well and truly on our way in this new term of government, I want to highlight some of the issues that we are fighting for in Paterson. Firstly, I will address the issue of schools and RAAF Base Williamtown. Salt Ash Public School in my electorate is affected by aircraft noise from the RAAF weapons range at Salt Ash. This has been the case for a number of years, which is why it was a ridiculous state of affairs when the New South Wales government had just completed building a new classroom without noise amelioration. The Minister for Defence and I announced that we would fix the New South Wales government's botched job and build a new library, this time with appropriate noise insulation. The Salt Ash Weapons Range has had a significant impact on the learning of children at that school and also the Williamtown Public School, for which I have also successfully lobbied for amelioration measures.</para><para>In the case of other schools in my area, the P&amp;Cs are almost tearing their hair out, trying to get the right facilities for their children. Grahamstown Public School was built only 10 years ago by the state government, long after the base was built, so it included noise attenuation measures. But it was built without airconditioning. This means that in summer they cannot shut the doors because it is too hot, and in the winter they cannot shut the doors because the fumes from the gas heater are dangerous. That is why I am so pleased that the public schools will now be able to apply directly to the Australian government for funds instead of going through the state government, as a part of our $700 million package. This means that Grahamstown Public School P&amp;C can apply for funding for airconditioning directly from the Australian government and not worry about the New South Wales education department deeming it not to be a priority.</para><para>The P&amp;Cs of all of the schools in my electorate, whether they be in Dungog, Medowie, Gloucester, Stroud Road, Forster or Bulahdelah, to mention a few, can apply for funding. Last year, we faced the hottest November on record, yet the roll-out program for airconditioning in schools is over four or five years. But, for the first time, parents and teachers do not have to worry about any roll-out program developed by an overpaid policy officer in an airconditioned office in Sydney. We will deliver results.</para><para>The other issue I would like to raise in relation to education is my continued push for a high school in the Medowie-Tilligerry area. Finally, we have the state government waking up to the fact that this is a growing and developing area, with a number of students, that will support the existence of a high school.</para><para>Turning my attention now to health matters in my electorate, I received letters of congratulation from a pensioner in Salamander Bay. I sorted out a Medicare matter for him earlier in the year, and in the process of the correspondence he made some remarks about politicians and how we do not look after our constituents. I did not hear anything from this pensioner until about one week after the election, when he wrote to me and thanked me for my help. He said he voted for me on the back of that help. I was flummoxed, because I thought he had voted informal or, worse, for a minor party. </para><para>His comments about bulk-billing and the cost of visiting a doctor helped me give the Prime Minister and health minister feedback on what we should do with Medicare. Even though bulk-billing has risen from 53.3 per cent to 59.7 per cent, no doctors are bulk-billing in the bay area, and a policy which did not recognise bulk-billing black spots would not work. People would have to change doctors to get the benefit of a policy. A full rebate will work for people like Claude.</para><para>I mentioned that in the top end of my electorate there were many who are considered frail aged. One of my volunteers, Richard, who did some letterboxing for me, is 78 years of age. But he is one of the many older Australians who no longer drives but walks everywhere. Some older drivers elect to have a restricted licence which gets them to the nearest business district. I want to thank the health minister for recognising this mobility issue and announcing a Medicare office for the Forster-Tuncurry area. Richard will now be able to walk to the Medicare office to claim his rebate.</para><para>But there are still holes in the health service in this area. We need public hospital facilities in the Great Lakes area, and I will keep on pushing our state government for some action. We have a private hospital in Forster called Cape Hawke Hospital. It has a complete floor of beds waiting to be developed. It defies logic why the state government will not enter into an arrangement to lease these beds to provide access for all in our community. The state government seem to think that hospital facilities in Taree are adequate for the burgeoning population in Forster-Tuncurry, Smiths Lakes and the Pacific Palms areas, but they simply do not understand. In the lower part of my electorate, Port Stephens desperately needs a hospital, but the New South Wales government will not even fund a feasibility study into whether the population in this area warrants a fully fledged hospital. The polyclinic at Nelson Bay, like our local schools, has had to fundraise to get airconditioning.</para><para>Turning my attention to telephones, we clearly want to improve communications in communities like Hawkes Nest, Tea Gardens, Vasey and Gresford. They need the internet to do business, both with business and the government. They need reliable landlines in case of emergencies and a mobile phone service that is not full of patches. A reliable communications service via the internet and a phone is just as vital in rural communities as good roads. In fact, I would argue that reliable internet and telephone services are more vital in towns further away from the city than they are in the city itself. I am not sure if many people in city electorates are aware of this, but some milk manufacturers now expect dairy farmers to submit their tenders via the internet. Any city member who argues that you cannot realistically expect a city-quality service in the bush should tell that to the milk manufacturers.</para><para>The difference between high-speed internet access and dial-up could be worth tens of thousands of dollars to a dairy farmer. I say this emphatically because areas such as Dungog and Gloucester have done it tough with deregulation. I would like to commend the former minister for communications and the current minister for continuing to upgrade the facilities to provide the internet to rural areas and for continuing to fix mobile telephone black spots. The geography of my electorate consists of hills and valleys. This causes mobile phone black spots, and both Vasey and Gresford have had new mobile phone towers switched on.</para><para>If there is one issue in my electorate that used to cause a huge amount of frustration with my constituents, and in some places it still does, it is that of television reception. For many of the elderly in my electorate television is their only source of entertainment and information. It sounds a bit fickle but, if a retiree is 80 and bedridden, this is the only form of entertainment and information that they have. For everyone else, staying in touch via the news or watching one or two favourite programs a year is all they expect. Earlier this year the new television booster tower for Stroud was switched on. It is still being adjusted to ensure a perfect picture every time, but at least it is up. Funding has been approved for similar towers in Booral, Elizabeth Beach and Smiths Lakes, which are operational. Funding of almost $750,000 was announced in mid-2004 for a television tower for the bay area in my electorate. It is a project that I am committed to. I will keep lobbying all of the stakeholders until we have the digital retransmission facility established on Gan Gan Hill. </para><para>In the area of aged care I am determined to get more aged care beds and funding for my electorate as a part of the government's roll-out of beds over the next three years. The minister for ageing has done a tremendous job since taking over this portfolio, continuing the work of former ministers and ensuring this area is well funded to support the growing needs throughout Australia. Many people come to retire in my electorate. The provision of aged care services that they may need in later years is an important part of their decision to move to communities such as Forster-Tuncurry and Port Stephens. If a person needs a nursing home they want to get into one near their families and friends. This is critically important.</para><para>I would also like to express my absolute zeal for bed places for couples. After years of marriage, raising a family and spending every night together, it is right that people can spend their nursing home days together too. The number of aged care places in the electorate of Paterson has doubled under the Howard government. Over the next three years it will increase substantially, with 940 places to be distributed in the Hunter region and 765 to be distributed in the mid North Coast region as part of the government's $2.2 billion Investing in Australia's Aged Care: More Places, Better Care Program.</para><para>We have had developments open up in the past six months, including the Port Stephens Gardens Nursing Centre in Salamander Bay, which is a 120-bed facility, and the opening of the Kularoo Gardens expansion in Forster. In the near future we hope to see Barclay Gardens in Tuncurry open, the expansion of the Myall Lodge in Hawks Nest, the expansion of the Great Lakes Nursing Home in Bulahdelah and the expansion of the Lara Aged Care Facility in Dungog—not forgetting the recently opened expansion of the GLAICA nursing home in Tuncurry.</para><para>I will continue to fight for one of the most important issues in my electorate, and that is roads. I have fought for a great deal of funding for projects in my electorate, such as the $20 million investment in Buckett's Way and the $25 million investment for Weakley's Drive. These projects, when completed, will bring great benefits to many communities. No-one should underestimate the importance of improved roads to the economies of regional areas. There are roads in the Dungog Shire—about which Mayor Steve Low and I have spoken on many occasions—which council cannot afford to fix on their current income. To make matters worse, they are ineligible for state government funding for particular roads.</para><para>Then there is the popular tourist route of Lakes Way, which links the Pacific Highway and Forster-Tuncurry with communities such as Pacific Palms and Smiths Lake. Tourist operators have told me how they tell motorists to take the alternative Pacific Highway route, instead of the scenic Lake's Way, because of concerns for their safety. To assist councils that cover these particular roads, the Australian government made a commitment during the election for $10 million to be spread across the Dungog, Port Stephens and Great Lakes shires, a commitment which must be matched by the state government. I have written to the New South Wales Minister for Roads, Michael Costa, about this project and the need for their support. I am hoping that he will take up our offer and improve the roads in my electorate. </para><para>In conclusion, health, communications, aged care and roads are just some of the issues I will continue to fight for in Paterson in this term of government. This is my first consecutive term as a member of parliament, and I want to let my constituents know that I am just as motivated this time as I was the very first day I was elected to this parliament. I would like to thank the people of Paterson for putting their faith in me, and everyone—from staff to volunteers—who has helped me along the way. It is an honour to represent the people of Paterson in this place of government, and that honour should never be treated lightly. I will give them the service that not only they expect but, more importantly, they deserve.</para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>10:18:00</time.stamp><page.no>123</page.no><name role="metadata">Stone, Dr Sharman, MP</name><name role="display">Dr STONE</name><name.id>EM6</name.id><electorate>Murray</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister for Finance and Administration</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I want to use this opportunity today to talk about some very serious issues affecting the Australian economy. We all know that Australia has traditionally addressed skills shortages through mass migration programs. From the 1950s, public infrastructure—for example, the huge Snowy Mountains scheme—was built using migrant labour, with many individuals, but also families, moving away from the war-torn zones of the Northern Hemisphere. Those people—they were often skilled but some were not skilled—worked initially on a whole range of government supported programs before moving into the wider economy. As we know, the original migrants who came in that period and their descendents form the backbone of our society today.</para></talk.start><para>We are very grateful for the mix and the cultural diversity that that migration wave brought, especially to areas like the great Goulburn and Murray valleys in my electorate, which are probably two of the most multiracial and multicultural communities in Australia. We are proud of that. That diversity has brought a richness of culture and resulted in a tolerant society. Our economy has been built on the hard work of these people, who have come to this country often with nothing more than a cardboard suitcase and a will to work.</para><para>Today Australia shares with most other developed economies a significant and growing shortage of skilled workers. This is a problem that is acknowledged throughout the OECD. Over a million skilled Australians—mostly younger people—are working offshore, taking opportunities for professional advancement, perhaps with better pay. Certainly it is a chance for them to develop their careers, but we hope they will come back. On the other side of the coin, Australia depends on the flow from other countries of, in particular, health service professionals. Most rural and regional hospitals, particularly those in the public hospital system and certainly those in my part of the world, depend on overseas trained doctors. For example, over 70 per cent of the doctors in Goulburn Valley Health, which is the main Shepparton public hospital, are from overseas. They are very welcome and we appreciate their presence. Our health services would collapse without them.</para><para>Successive Australian governments have tackled the skills shortages. I mentioned at the beginning of my remarks the mass migrations of the fifties and a little before then. No government has as conscientiously and successfully tackled the skills shortages, especially for rural and regional Australia, as the Howard government. I commend in particular the Regional Skilled Migration Scheme and the recent changes which have allowed offshore students to stay in Australia, under certain careful criteria, if they have employment in a rural area. I commend the Howard government for understanding that we need skilled migrants to come into this country and work in rural and regional Australia. </para><para>What I am equally concerned about is the unskilled labour category, comprising those who are prepared to do manual work, particularly the seasonal manual work that is absolutely essential for our horticulture industry, in which I include vegetables, nursery production, fruit and nuts and some viticulture. Some vines are able to be machine picked. In 2000, the gross value of production of horticulture was $5.5 billion, with a farm gate value of $4.7 billion. This production is dependent on access to labour in the form of pickers, pruners, planters and people who are prepared to work in packing sheds. This is seasonal work. Unfortunately farm enterprises typically cannot afford, or do not have the work, to offer jobs for a whole season. There is often a peak period in which they require a certain number of pickers—in the case of the Goulburn Valley, some 8,000 to 10,000 pickers and, in the following months, about half that number to do pruning. Without that labour, quite simply our horticultural industries cannot expand. They cannot take advantage of the growing access to the fresh fruit and vegetable, nut and honey markets that we have worked hard to develop access to.</para><para>We have a serious issue of illegal workers in the harvest areas. As we speak, a number of raids are going on in my electorate of Murray and in the neighbouring electorate of Mallee. Just two days ago some 40 or so illegal workers were picked up on some vegetable farms. Those workers came from Cambodia, Thailand and other near neighbours in Asia. They were cutting and harvesting vegetables—a high-value crop for domestic and export markets. Those farmers, those property owners, now have no labour. Those crops will need to be ploughed in. They cannot obtain additional or alternative labour. Of course they were not aware that those people were illegal. Some of them had been employed for over four years and they had been obtained through a contract labour hire service. It was the understanding of the farmers that those workers had the right to work in Australia. Sadly, it turns out they did not. Of course the owners of those properties do not support illegal work in Australia. On the other hand, they are faced with this extraordinary dilemma. How do they produce magnificent product in regions where the irrigation infrastructure has been built at public expense over a hundred years, where they have the soils, the climate and the clean green image? All is there for them to prosper but they cannot obtain the labour.</para><para>A number of countries, particularly many of our competitors in agricultural production, have overcome this problem with visas and market labour programs that bring in seasonal workers. Most countries have temporary worker programs for both high- and low-skilled workers. Some have separate programs for IT professionals, health-care workers, managers and executives, but there are special programs for farm workers—and also for maids and caregivers in some countries. There is always a concern in Australia that an overseas worker might literally `disappear' into the economy after their visa expires, because we are such a multiracial, multicultural society and we have such a huge continent. Obviously compliance issues are very difficult in Australia because we are such an open country in terms of movement. But other countries have come up with some quite careful and workable solutions—obviously negotiated with the home country and with the workers themselves. The negotiations have included such conditions as withholding part of their payments—this is of course with the workers' permission—until they are literally on their way back to their home country; not having families arrive with the workers but just having individuals come so that there is a greater incentive for them to return; and compliance with a temporary work visa creating the opportunity to return year after year, for perhaps six or nine months of the year, to work as a seasonal worker. </para><para>While I am talking about horticulture—fruit growing, vegetable growing, nuts, harvesting and table grapes—the same issues also affect Australia's hospitality industry, where there is a chronic shortage of workers, and our rag trade. But let me focus at the moment on the issue that most significantly affects my electorate, which is the access to labour for horticulture. I want to mention a couple of programs used by other countries. Canada, for example, has the Commonwealth Caribbean and Mexican Agricultural Seasonal Workers Program, or ASWP. It has allowed Canadian farmers to import foreign workers for up to eight months a year from the Caribbean since 1966 and from Mexico since 1974. About 80 per cent of these ASWP migrants are employed in fruit, vegetable and tobacco farms in Ontario. Their average stay in Canada is four months.</para><para>Mexicans are recruited and employed under the terms of a government-to-government memorandum of understanding that makes the Mexican Ministry of Labor responsible for recruiting workers and negotiating their wages with Human Resources Development Canada, a government agency. The admissions process begins with farm employers applying to local Human Resources centres for certification to employ the foreign workers, at least eight weeks before they are needed. There is, of course, always a preference for Canadian workers under the Canadians First policy, but if there is evidence that no Canadian nationals are available then farmers may access these foreign workers. They must pay them an agreed piece rate or the prevailing wage.</para><para>There can be absolutely no intention of exploiting labour from countries where salaries or piece work payments may be substantially lower than in the Australian economy. Their housing, their access to health services and every other condition of their work must be equivalent to Australian working standards. There must be no possibility of exploitation of these people. In the Canadian experience, migrants are given entry papers in their countries of origin, and a special Foreign Agricultural Resource Management Services agency affiliate arranges to transport these workers to Canada and to the employer who has applied for them. Farmers advance the cost of transportation from Mexico to Canada and deduct four per cent of workers' wages to cover the transport costs. Farmers also deduct payroll taxes and insurance costs from their workers' pay, and there is a 14-day probation period after their arrival.</para><para>Other countries have similar sorts of programs. Swiss programs, for example, are long established, and indeed that country totally depends on foreign workers. In December 2001, foreigners in the Swiss work force represented 25 per cent of all workers. Of those, 20 per cent had renewable one-year work permits and 18 per cent were border commuters. Switzerland's agriculture based industries could not continue without these workers, but there are certain conditions of compliance associated with their programs.</para><para>With regard to the French programs, the numbers of seasonal foreign workers admitted for employment in agriculture rise and fall. In 1972 a peak of 138,000 seasonal foreign workers were admitted into France. Two-thirds came from Spain; two-thirds were employed to do the grape harvest. The admission process began with French farmers having their need for foreign workers certified by local labour officers. Spanish workers were then requested by name by French employers, and many arrived by train in work crews that could shift from employer to employer. French employers paid for worker transportation and provided housing. It has been noted that the recruitment of seasonal foreign workers for agriculture was not halted with the recruitment of foreign workers who came in for other purposes. There has been a shrinking and expanding of the need for workers in France for agriculture, but in the late 1990s almost 11,000 seasonal foreign workers were admitted. In fact, in 2001, there were 11,000 seasonal workers for agriculture; half came from Morocco and 43 per cent came from Poland. </para><para>I want to emphasise the success of programs in other countries. Many of us are also aware of the longstanding guest worker programs in countries such as the United States, in particular—and I have already mentioned Canada. They have a very well-known program where they try very hard to ensure the rights of workers and to ensure that those who come through the borders illegally are not exploited but, rather, go through a legal process. That gives the farmers access to seasonal work, which means that the Californian industries have survived and thrived, many of them in competition with Australia's agribusiness.</para><para>Israel also has a longstanding worker program, where teams of workers arrive from the Middle East and other neighbouring countries for only, on some occasions, four months of work on their kibbutzim to meet the seasonal peaks of their horticultural demand. The workers return with apparently very little loss in terms of overstaying. Israel's horticultural industry's prosperity is linked to their access to this labour.</para><para>I have been speaking to our Minister for Immigration and Multicultural and Indigenous Affairs. She is very aware of this problem and is concerned about making sure that we have immigration programs in Australia that do not lead to overstaying or exploitation. We, of course, have sex industry problems in Australia, where illegal workers are brought into this country. Women are very significantly exploited when this happens, but we have introduced sex slavery legislation into this House to ensure that we can properly prosecute those who use illegal workers in our country in the sex industry.</para><para>These are very serious issues associated with guest workers that I know our government is keen to address and will address. I want to make the point, however, that enforcing compliance, with the so-called raids that are undertaken in horticulture to find illegal workers, is costly. Perhaps the cost is more than that of administering a scheme of introduced seasonal workers where the rules are very carefully thought through. If we take the very best of the systems that have been introduced overseas, we can then solve a number of problems. We can have our multibillion dollar horticultural industry thrive and our export industries grow. We can remove the incentive for illegal overstays, and we can perhaps build on our relationships with our near neighbours, particularly in Asian countries such as Indonesia, the Philippines and Malaysia, who have numbers of workers only too willing to come to Australia for short terms. We can build relationships further, with close connections between certain districts and regions in those countries and our horticultural regions in Australia. The need is very great, and I know we will find a solution. I look forward to working with the minister in developing a solution to this problem. I want to say that the John Howard government is one of the first to be serious about regional employment issues, and I commend the skilled migration programs that are bringing us workers for the first time in decades. But the seasonal worker program now needs serious attention. </para><para>Dr SOUTHCOTT (Boothby) (10.35 a.m.)—I move:</para><motion><para>That further proceedings be conducted in the House</para></motion><para>Question agreed to.</para></speech></subdebate.1></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>INDIAN OCEAN TSUNAMI</title><type>Miscellaneous</type><page.no>127</page.no></debateinfo><para>Debate resumed from 8 February, on motion by<inline font-weight="bold"> Mr Pearce</inline>:</para><motion><para>That the House take note of the document.</para></motion><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>10:36:00</time.stamp><page.no>127</page.no><name role="metadata">Ellis, Annette, MP</name><name role="display">Ms ANNETTE ELLIS</name><name.id>5K6</name.id><electorate>Canberra</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I am very pleased to have this opportunity to add my voice to those in this and the other place who have already expressed their deep shock and sadness at the events of 26 December 2004. When the death toll was estimated in the thousands, I was shocked by the magnitude of the disaster. As the number of victims increased with every hour, day and news bulletin, my shock, and that of others, turned to utter disbelief. I fear that the final human cost of this disaster will never be truly known. Having spent 2½ years in Bangkok during my time with the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade some years ago, I have a very deep affection and respect for the people of Thailand. There is no way to describe the sadness I feel at the thought of such a warm people, so generous in nature and rich in culture, having such a tragedy inflicted upon them. Sadly, they were not the only country so afflicted.</para></talk.start><para>Sections of the Australian and international communities have expressed in a variety of ways their support for those affected. Very soon after 26 December, I had the opportunity and the privilege here in my electorate of Canberra to attend interfaith services at the Royal Thai Embassy; St Christopher's Catholic Church, in Manuka; the City Uniting Church; the Indonesian Embassy; and the Mandir Society, in Mawson. I was immensely impressed by the level of attendance, given that one of those services was held on the morning of 1 January, New Year's Day, at a time when everybody was very much in holiday mode. Yet, when these services came along and offered an opportunity for people to gather, it became very evident that people really needed to do that. For my own part I appreciated very much the efforts behind each of those services that I attended. I understood very clearly, from my own personal feelings, the importance of gathering. Sitting at home and watching the news was one thing, but I cannot overstate how important it was to have the opportunity to get together with other people, some of whom were personally affected through family connections in some of the countries affected.</para><para>The tsunami did not respect national borders, ethnic, cultural or political differences. The water claimed the lives of people from many different religions, backgrounds and nationalities. The response to this catastrophe has been that the geographic and cultural barriers disregarded by the tsunami are also being disregarded by those seeking to support and to help repair the damage. As each country affected by the rising water began to assess the enormous task of rebuilding, in this country alone churches, synagogues, mosques, scout groups, schools, pubs, workplaces, sporting groups, neighbourhoods—every level of our society—began fundraising. I know all members of this House will join me in saying that we were both amazed and pleased by the level of generosity shown by Canberra residents and the generosity that has been mirrored around the country.</para><para>It is interesting to note that money was collected from such huge events as WaveAid right down to children collecting in their neighbourhood streets. It was a response we have never needed to see before, but it warms the heart to know that it happened. I would like to express my support, as others in this place have already, for the measures taken by the Australian government in response to the events of 26 December. I would also like to thank the government departments and individuals whose reaction to this crisis can make us all so proud. </para><para>Many Canberra residents returned early from their hard-earned leave as government departments reacted to the disaster. Being the national capital, Canberra is also home to the majority of Commonwealth public servants in this country. It is fair to say, and I do not think anybody will mind me reflecting in this way, that it can sometimes be fashionable to knock public servants—and I do not mean just politicians; I mean anybody around the country. It is quite often a bit of sport. However, the reaction of those people working in all areas of the Public Service over that period might put that kind of practice to bed for ever. There has never been a better demonstration of absolute dedication to a job or to providing a service than was seen at all levels of the public service sector following this terrible disaster.</para><para>Acting to help seems to have been an automatic reaction to the crisis rather than a conscious decision. These people simply saw what was required and went to work to respond. In the days following 26 December, the people at the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade worked tirelessly to provide information to Australians seeking news of loved ones in the affected regions. To put things into perspective, I am informed that shortly after the Bali bombing the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade received around 35,000 calls. By 10 January this year, that same call centre had received over 82,000 calls, an enormous level of response and work required.</para><para>Some of the first help to get to Thailand came from the ACT hospital trauma section. Three of our medical trauma specialists were up there very quickly assisting with triage to help assist and move people as quickly as they could in those important first few days following the effect that was felt in southern Thailand. RAAF personnel were among the first Australians sent to Indonesia to help, and Australian Defence Force personnel remain in some of the worst affected areas providing, medical, logistical and other relief services. They will be there for some time. The AFP was also very involved and remains so. While so many Australians were justifiably attempting to return home as quickly as possible, the Australian armed services were preparing to send people just as quickly into Banda Aceh. I understand that some forensics teams that lent their services to the Indonesian government in the wake of the Bali bombing are now conducting DNA tests to identify, as much as possible, the unnamed victims of the tsunami. They are performing a truly unenviable task, and I believe no words expressed here can adequately describe the courage or the quality of character displayed by those people.</para><para>A Canberra resident—in fact, a constituent of mine—Percy Samara-Wickrama is a retired engineer originally from Galle in Sri Lanka. Percy has contributed to aid projects in Bosnia and Kosovo with an aid organisation known as RedR—Registered Engineers for Disaster Relief. Percy returned to Sri Lanka, to Galle, very soon after the disaster to assist in the rebuilding of two villages as part of a project called Operation Hope. One hundred per cent of funds donated to Operation Hope will go towards rebuilding those villages with a view to sustaining their long-term recovery. All administration costs are being met by Percy's family, such is his determination to help the area he was born in. I know from discussions that my officers had with Percy's son that the effort to set up Operation Hope has been enormous, and I commend very strongly the work that Percy and his family have done in that personal way to dedicate themselves to something they truly believe in. </para><para>I know that the ACT community, both through the business and professional community and just folk living out there in the electorate, are all getting behind Operation Hope and doing what they can. They can actually see a direct connection between their efforts to support this particular enterprise and the actual, physical rebuilding of a couple of villages within Percy's family's original area in Sri Lanka. I know that even local WIN TV have been following the progress of this very closely, and I commend that very strongly. This is just one example. There are so many other examples around the country where people are doing similar things.</para><para>If I or anyone else in this place were to try to name every organisation, government department or individual who deserved specific praise, I am sure we would all be here far longer than any of us have time allowed for any one speech on this issue. While the challenge of rebuilding may well be the greatest ever presented by a natural disaster on this planet, companies, charities and ordinary citizens have proved and are proving that we can and will meet this challenge. I again want to make reference to the level of response that we are seeing through all of our communities. Every one of the members and senators within this place could stand up and cite examples from their own communities where there have been wonderful responses. The type that I think epitomises it most for me has been not necessarily from here but just the photos in the papers of children setting up lemonade stalls in streets. At any level that people can, they want to be involved and they need to be involved. We can be very proud, as Australians, of seeing the sort of human response that is coming from our Australian community to this terrible disaster.</para><para>I would like once more to extend my condolences to the nations affected by this disaster. All of those nations have been named in the parliament, and I do not need to go through those again. Suffice it to say that there are far too many, and the tragic outcome is still being measured in many of those countries. I want to record, as well, on behalf of my electorate, my gratitude to our armed forces, our charities and the people of my community and of Australia generally for their collective response to this tragedy.</para><para>In conclusion, whilst the response has been, as I have said, so warm-hearted, the difficulty now, I think, will be to continue that response into the months and the years to come. The dimension of this disaster is such that things are not going to be rebuilt overnight. Continuing connection to these communities around the Indian Ocean rim is going to be needed for some years to come. I think we all are going to need to do what we can to support the ongoing rebuilding and the ongoing call for help in re-establishing lives, communities, buildings, business enterprises and community and social networks. All of those things are going to take time. I have every confidence that the Australian community will be in a position to continue that connection with these people for the years to come, because that is what is going to be required.</para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>10:48:00</time.stamp><page.no>129</page.no><name role="metadata">Fawcett, David, MP</name><name role="display">Mr FAWCETT</name><name.id>DYU</name.id><electorate>Wakefield</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I rise to support the motion moved by the Prime Minister and endorse the comments of the previous speakers. Many speakers have rightly lauded the excellent work of the Australian Defence Force medical and engineering teams who have worked tirelessly to bring about real change in the areas devastated by the Boxing Day tsunami. Today, however, I wish to particularly highlight the significant contribution by the men and women of the Australian Army Aviation Corps and the Royal Australian Air Force Air Lift Group. These people deploy and operate with little publicity, but they are often the main source of mobility in areas where the ADF have served Australia, such as the drought relief in Papua New Guinea, operations in Bougainville, the Solomon Islands, Iraq, East Timor and, most recently, Banda Aceh. </para></talk.start><para>Members of 36 and 37 Squadron of the Air Lift Group have flown Hercules aircraft on a continual basis to deliver aid and to evacuate people whose lives have been devastated by the tsunami. Over 1,100 tonnes of aid have been sent from Australia to Sumatra, much of it carried by the aircraft of the Air Lift Group. Elements of the 16th Brigade Army Aviation were some of the first ADF assets deployed to Sumatra. Within days of the tsunami, 47 members of A Squadron, Fifth Aviation Regiment, had returned from leave and been deployed with four Iroquois helicopters to commence operations from Banda Aceh airport.</para><para>Members of 173 Surveillance Squadron had deployed a Super King Air aircraft to operate from Medan. To date, these Army aviators have carried over 100,000 kilograms of food, water and medical supplies as well as carrying out numerous life-saving medical evacuation flights. I should also mention the actions of Major James Brown, the A Squadron Detachment Commander, who was one of the first people on the scene when a U.S. Navy Seahawk helicopter crashed. In his actions rescuing the crew from the wreckage, he sustained injuries which required his repatriation to Australia. I wish him a full and speedy recovery.</para><para>In acknowledging and thanking the members of the Army Aviation Corps and the Air Lift Group, and the maintenance engineers who support them, I wish also to thank their families. The long period of concurrent deployments around the world of ADF aviation assets has put a huge strain on families—often young families—who remain at home. They cope with a number of pressures and uncertainties unique to having a family member deployed on operations, as well as the normal aspects of family life. I wish to take this opportunity to place on record my thanks to them for their sacrifice which allows the ADF to, yet again, play a significant part in contributing to our region and making all Australians proud.</para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>10:51:00</time.stamp><page.no>130</page.no><name role="metadata">Hatton, Michael, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HATTON</name><name.id>LN6</name.id><electorate>Blaxland</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—First of all, I would like to congratulate the Prime Minister on putting this motion before the chamber. I am sure that every single member of the House would support this motion. Certainly for my own part I can say that I endorse every jot and every particle of this motion, as I also endorsed every action that the Prime Minister and the government took in the wake of the tsunami of 26 December. The action was timely, appropriate and necessary in the face of a disaster that was then not seen to be as great as it now has been revealed to be in the fullness of time. Almost 300,000 people have had their lives destroyed and their communities devastated. The timeliness of the response and its appropriateness is what any government should have delivered—coalition or Labor. So I congratulate the Prime Minister. I also congratulate the parliamentary secretary, the member for Dunkley, Bruce Billson, who carried most of the government's practical response during the immediate aftermath of the tsunami. In doing so, I underline the fact that this is a bipartisan response to an absolutely overwhelming natural disaster.</para></talk.start><para>There are particulars within this motion that I will come back to. I simply want to look in the first instance at point (1) which says:</para><para>That the House: </para><para>(1)	extends to all Australians who suffered personal losses during the tragic 26 December Indian Ocean tsunami disaster its profound sympathy in their bereavement and wishes a speedy recovery to the injured ...</para><para>Luckily, in this disaster the level of loss of life for Australians was comparatively small when you look at the other countries affected. Sweden of course had so many thousands of its people who had their lives simply ripped away from them because they went to one destination in Thailand. Germans suffered too—not in equal measure, but still a large number of people lost their lives. Given Australians' propensity to travel to South-East Asia—and, indeed, to Thailand, one of the affected countries—and to spend their holiday periods there, we were lucky that more were not lost. I have been to Phuket with my wife. I stayed at the Sheraton resort which was devastated by this tsunami. I have stood on the beach. I swam in the water. I have been in the position of those people who, almost in the twinkling of an eye, had their lives completely turned around. It is instructive in a way to step back and think about our situation and the situation of others in current circumstances, and consider how things were different before modern communications were operating in terms of the localised responses to such things.</para><para>A little while I ago stood on a headland at Balmoral Beach, out on a rocky area near the end, just past the children's pool, and I looked out towards the Heads and back to the escarpment at Balmoral. I was thinking about the deep ocean trench between Australia and New Zealand and the fact that the eruption of an earthquake within that trench could cause a tsunami to come onto Australian beaches, and that I could be in the situation that all those hundreds of thousands of people were—here one minute, gone the next. The predictability of this is extremely low unless you have proper and effective monitoring systems, as there are in the Pacific. So at least we have those things in place and have had for a long period.</para><para>It is quite apparent that one of the major problems in the regions affected—in Banda Aceh in Indonesia, in Thailand and less so for those countries that were further away and, indeed, the ones that we did not hear about much at all—was the lack of an early warning. I had contemplated going on a holiday in Mauritius during that period. Mauritius was slightly affected but had plenty of warning because of what was apparent with regard to what happened in Banda Aceh and Thailand. It also hit the Seychelles, another Indian Ocean holiday place primarily used by people from France and other parts of Europe, and it hit the African coast as well. The result and impact there were much less, not because of the intensity of the waves but because of the early warning.</para><para>For all those Australians who lost their lives because there was not an early warning system in place, I join with all of those others from the opposition and from the government side who have said that there should be a priority placed on creating the same type of early warning system in the Indian Ocean as we have had in the Pacific Ocean for many years. We have friends who have relatives living in Thailand. Indeed, they run a business on the beach. It just so happened that on that morning, because they were caught up, they were not down on the beach running the business. They had to get children from school and they were further into the hinterland. By luck, their lives were saved. But, for all of those people who were doing the very normal thing of enjoying their holidays, when something like this emerges and sweeps them away so rapidly it is really hard to comprehend the immensity of it. I really could not get a handle on the strength of the waves or their impact until I looked at the footage. Certain camera angles can show it to you, and it was only a couple of weeks down the track that some of the home footage shot by people who were there gave a better indication of what happened in particular places. </para><para>One of the things that stands out is that the world now is very different to what it was previously. In the past, going back to prehistoric times, there were of course always natural disasters, some of which wiped out hundreds of thousands of people. But when they happened two key things were different from the situation today. The first is that in the hunter-gatherer period people were effectively in small bands. The density of the population worldwide was much less. It was not until the agricultural revolution and the creation of settled communities that we had an increasing density of population and an increasing number of people in the population who could be affected locally in one place. So in prehistoric times there were fewer people to be so affected and, because they existed in scattered bands and moved through the environment in a way that did not have as much impact as settled communities, there was less chance of being caught up in these kinds of disasters. More importantly, no-one knew what happened to individual groups of people because they were isolated from their fellows.</para><para>It is only in the period of modern civilisations, not just civilisations post the agricultural revolution but those with speedy communications, that you can get a handle on what happens in fundamental natural disasters. You only need to go back 100 years or more and the reality was that people did not hear about major natural disasters, whether it was the eruption of Vesuvius or Mount Etna or the great disaster caused by Krakatoa, until either the physical evidence was present before them—and that took some time, for instance, in regard to Krakatoa—or the associated tsunamis had happened as a result of those earthquake events in the Indian Ocean or the Pacific. There was a great deal of lag time before people found out about them. As for trying to get help and support, there was not the modern response that there has been to this tsunami.</para><para>Because of modern communications, we know about, can feel about and have empathy for those people who lost their lives or had their places destroyed. As the previous speaker indicated, with their modern transport systems, the Australian defence forces were able to take aid and assistance—medical aid, food and water—to people desperately in need of it. What the government did, supported by the opposition in a nonpartisan way, in moving as swiftly as possible to go to the aid of those people most in need of our help, was a tremendous achievement. It was an achievement that goes to the core of an Australian response—the fact that people wholeheartedly and rapidly went to the assistance of others and did so in a period when normally the country would be on holiday.</para><para>Associated with that was a very clear understanding, not only of the logistical problems that there would be in Banda Aceh, for instance, but also of the fact that targeted assistance was necessary in those places most seriously affected by the tsunami because they were the most proximate. The province of Banda Aceh suffered directly because it was closest to the undersea earthquake and had less warning time than anywhere else. Given the nature of the topography, it had a very wide area that was completely devastated, to the point where there is virtually nothing left standing. I think it is right and appropriate that Australian aid has been primarily focused there.</para><para>We also know that there has been a substantial effort in Sri Lanka, and there has been some effort as well in relation to Thailand. In fact, the Thai government have indicated that the thing we could do to help the most would be to encourage people to go on holiday to those areas again—to take up the normal response that one would see. The Thai government have the ability to rebuild their infrastructure and to handle their own demands and needs in this area themselves. But they want people to come back. They want to re-establish a sense of the necessity to support these tourist destinations by people travelling to them. </para><para>That will not happen easily unless there is a sense of sureness on the part of those people who would travel there—that is, a sense that the places are rebuilt, that they are safer in terms of the general safety of water, food and so on and that they have readily available services. For an event like this, coming with no signal, no clarion call and no time for people to respond, an early warning system must be built. In that way, people can be sure, if they are going to those places to relax and rebuild themselves in a holiday mode, that they will not have the idea that this could happen to them. The lives of all those hundreds of thousands of innocent people who were killed in this disaster should not have been lost only for this to happen again in the same way. It is absolutely critical to all of those people—not only in holiday areas but in areas like Banda Aceh, with people leading very normal lives, going about their activities—that they are able to rebuild in the hills or more mountainous areas or, indeed, on the plain again. But it is also critical that they have some protection through the use of available technologies as well as the use of our intelligence and abilities to predict these incidents and their effects better than we can.</para><para>Part of the human aspect of this is that although the early warning system for the underground earthquake registered in Australia, the results were misinterpreted. First, they thought that it was not as great as it was. Second, they did not think there would be a tsunami effect because, when you look at the gradings for seismic activity, there is an exponential factor with respect to their gravity. For example, a size seven is entirely different from a size 7½ or a size eight—or in this case, one going on for a size nine. It is always probable in human affairs that, even with the best attention to such things, people will get them wrong. This experience has been so grave and so disastrous for the entire region and those communities involved that it is imperative that we get it right.</para><para>It is also imperative that we continue to do as we have done, and that is to build and strengthen the relationship between Australia and Indonesia so that Indonesians of goodwill will understand, as they have in the past, that the present involvement of Australia and its future involvement will be to build with them to allow them to renovate, reinvigorate and rejuvenate their people and their circumstances, particularly in Banda Aceh, so that as good neighbours and good citizens of the world we can renew what was destroyed and open up for the survivors a life that is open, free and not dominated by the fear of this happening again.</para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>11:06:00</time.stamp><page.no>133</page.no><name role="metadata">Hunt, Gregory, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HUNT</name><name.id>00AMV</name.id><electorate>Flinders</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister for the Environment and Heritage</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—In considering and remembering the tragedy of Boxing Day, the tsunami and the human loss, I recall the words of John Donne from 400 years ago. John Donne was an English cleric, author and poet. He wrote:</para></talk.start><quote><para>No man is an island, entire of himself; every man is a piece of the continent, a part of the main. If a clod be washed away by the sea, Europe is the less, as well as if a promontory were ... any man's death diminishes me, because I am involved in mankind, and therefore never send to know for whom the bell tolls; it tolls for thee. </para></quote><para>Those words, 400 years old, are as relevant today—and sadly perhaps more relevant than they were then—as one could imagine. On Boxing Day we saw that, and we saw a response which echoed the words as well, which was perhaps the bright light in an otherwise tragic episode in human history. In speaking to this motion of condolence to the tsunami victims I want to refer to three things: I want to talk briefly about the tragedy, and then about the Australian response and finally, in my role as Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister for the Environment and Heritage, I want to refer to the steps forward, as I have carriage in my area of the Bureau of Meteorology, which has a significant role in warning people about the possible arrival and consequences of natural disasters.</para><para>The tragedy, as we are all aware, has probably taken 300,000 lives, and that figure may continue to grow. That figure of 300,000 was most profoundly registered in the province of Banda Aceh in Indonesia, which suffered an almost instantaneous double of earthquake and tsunami. Nothing could have been done then or now, and probably not within the next 500 years, to warn people of that kind of arrival. The process from earthquake to tsunami was almost instantaneous—within a period of 20 minutes. However, there is always a response. As we radiate out from the epicentre through the Indian Ocean region we see that there was a time lapse. We will be able to deal with and improve our warning systems on that front. However, the tragedy that affected Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand, Sri Lanka in large part, India and to a lesser extent Burma, the Maldives and even as far away as the Seychelles and the African coast, reminds us of who we are and what we have lost. It brings us together in a way that was not sought, but which is in some way uplifting.</para><para>This brings me to the second point, which is about the response. It has shown us the capacity we have as individuals, as countries, as citizens and as communities to respond in times of crisis. Sure, there was an Australian government response—which was right, appropriate, just and generous—but that is not the real focus. The real focus is what occurred in every one of our electorates. In every electorate around Australia, in every community, there was an outpouring of generosity and grief for those whom we may have not known and will never know. There was an emotional response and a practical response.</para><para>I want to acknowledge some of the practical responses within my own electorate of Flinders. Firstly, the Phillip Island <inline font-style="italic">Advertiser</inline> staff, led by the editor, Anne Oswin, worked with a series of community groups such as Rotary to create a table, which they then covered with $2 coins in the main street. That table was filled multiple times. Over the course of January it generated approximately $50,000 and led to that small community contributing a total of $100,000 to the international Red Cross. It was one little community, one small island and one simple activity. I commend Anne Oswin and the staff of the <inline font-style="italic">Advertiser</inline>, the volunteers from Rotary and all the other volunteer groups on the island. That is one example of local generosity that was replicated throughout Australia. That generosity was replicated through corporate giving and at the national level.</para><para>Whilst the government has given resources, what I think is extraordinary at the national level is the role that Australia's defence personnel have played. They have given their time, they have been drawn away from their families and they have been on the front line. The defence and medical personnel, whether it is in Banda Aceh or in other parts of the region, have played an extraordinary role. I thank them, I commend them and I acknowledge their work. </para><para>I also want to look at the steps forward. The outpouring of compassion and the response has been quick, clear and practical, and it has been uniform across the country. But the real question at this moment in history, at the beginning of the 21st century, is: what are our options for trying to avoid these sorts of disasters happening again? In Banda Aceh, nothing could be done to deal with an immediate crisis and natural disaster of this magnitude. When there is an earthquake and immediate tsunami, there will be a human tragedy. Let us not pretend that we can avoid that at this stage in our history. We simply do not have the capacity to predict an earthquake accurately to the day or the hour. We talk in decades and centuries in terms of probability.</para><para>But there are perhaps three critical steps that we can take moving forwards, which deal not just with tsunami warning systems but with the whole notion of disaster warning systems. They proceed along three fronts. The first element in any early warning system is monitoring. This is perhaps the easiest part to get right. There is a Pacific tsunami warning system based in Hawaii, but there has been no such similar thing within the Indian Ocean region. The reasons are: firstly, history and the lack of apparent need—human history is seen in the present century over decades, not over eons; and secondly, because it is a developing region and it has not been seen as a priority. We now know, with the benefit of hindsight, that it must be a priority—that we have to view our responsibilities to future generations in terms of centuries and eons, not just in terms of immediate needs. The once in a century or once in 500 year natural disaster could be now or it could be at any other time within that frame.</para><para>It is possible to provide the technological warning. That exists within the Pacific system. Australia is playing a role in coordinating through the International Oceanographic Commission that set of skills and is working towards the capabilities and the technological options within the Indian Ocean region. A system will be set up. We have already been involved through meetings in Kobe on the World Conference on Disaster Reduction and in Phuket. We will be involved in other meetings in establishing that Indian Ocean regional tsunami warning system but also more broadly in the entire disaster system.</para><para>The second element of any warning system, other than the technological capability, is education—that is, what to do in the event of an active, live warning. We have within Australia two very good models of that—bushfire and cyclone events. They need to be advanced, but in terms of public education these models can be exported and replicated throughout the Indian Ocean region. We have already committed to do that. There is a lot more to do, but we will be doing that sort of public education. We will be working within each individual country to try to encourage the development of such systems.</para><para>The third and most difficult part of any warning system is about what you might call the last mile—how you get the technology or the ability to communicate with people in rural villages in a short time frame over the last mile. We do have, through mobile technology—and I am glad that the member for Wentworth is here; he is one of the pioneers within Australia and one of the most knowledgeable people in this field—the capacity to push messages out to every mobile device and every fixed line device over the last mile through automated systems. Only this morning, I was exploring with a number of people how we can do that throughout the Indian Ocean region and also within Australia. That is something which we have not embraced yet and which we must embrace. It is the next generation of wholesale warning. But these are rural villages. These are developing parts of the world, so we also need to work on general broadcast facilities within these villages. Again, that was something we were looking at this morning. </para><para>There is a lot more to be done. These systems will not be perfect because, if we face a genuine, immediate natural disaster, there is no warning and no capacity to avoid that which is immediate. But where there is any sort of delay between event and consequence, the capacity to provide warning is something which we can do. We see now that the Indian Ocean region is vulnerable, that this was not something of the fantastic and the imaginary but potential and real. Krakatoa is not something of history; unfortunately, it is something of our present. So that is the future, that is what we have to work towards and that is what we are working towards.</para><para>Ultimately, I want to return to where I began: the notion that no man is an island and each man's death diminishes me because I am of mankind. That sentiment is with us. It is something which we forget and something which unfortunately it too often takes a tragedy to resurrect within our thinking and our being. The lesson of the last month is that, as a society, we have within us an extraordinary capacity. If we can in any way on all sides of this chamber do whatever we can to work together to try to encourage that sentiment and to encourage that sense of national unity and common humanity, then we will be doing something of real meaning for future generations. I thank all of those people, most simply signified by the people of Phillip Island, members of the Phillip Island <inline font-style="italic">Advertiser</inline> and Phillip Island Rotary for their generosity, because they tell us what we can be and they tell us what we should be.</para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>11:18:00</time.stamp><page.no>136</page.no><name role="metadata">Gillard, Julia, MP</name><name role="display">Ms GILLARD</name><name.id>83L</name.id><electorate>Lalor</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—Today I rise to speak on this motion in my capacity as shadow minister for health and member for Lalor, but perhaps most importantly as a human being. You would not be a human being unless you felt a strong emotional reaction to the dreadful tragedy that unfolded on our TV screens and on the pages of our newspapers from Boxing Day on. We can all probably identify different moments of that coverage which emotionally affected us. I certainly remember the Australian woman who came back to Australia with her two children but described a moment of indescribable horror when she needed to work out which child she would hold on to and which child she would let go—an almost unimaginable thing for a mother to do that we know in popular culture as <inline font-style="italic">Sophie's Choice</inline>. Fortunately for her, both of her children survived but in devastation where so many did not.</para></talk.start><para>We know that the devastation affected our region broadly: Indonesia, Thailand, Sri Lanka, India, Bangladesh, Burma, the Maldives, East Africa, Kenya, the Seychelles, Somalia, Madagascar, and Tanzania. The tsunami hit across our region and caused an almost unimaginable loss of life—about 290,000 people, with possibly more deaths to be recorded, and 240,000 people in Indonesia alone.</para><para>I am sure we are all aware now that the unofficial Australian death toll is 24, with relatives having confirmed six deaths on top of the 18 deaths officially listed by DFAT. We know that grave concerns remain for 10 Australians who were in tsunami affected areas and whose bodies have not been identified or are still subject to formal victim identification processes. As has been remarked by many speakers in this debate, the outpouring of generosity from Australians confronted with this tragedy was huge—huge at both the community and the official level. That is something for which Australia can be proud. All of us have stories of seeing people put in amounts of money that were probably almost beyond their capacity to donate at one time to one cause. But so moved were they that Australians were hugely generous in response to this tragedy. The Australian government, with the full support of the opposition, of course, announced a $1 billion program, the Australia-Indonesia partnership for reconstruction and redevelopment. It is a five-year commitment and the single largest aid package in Australia's history. We should be rightly proud of that as a country. </para><para>I would particularly like to direct my remarks to the work that was done in the health and medical area as an immediate response to the tsunami. Obviously, with a disaster like this there is not only dealing with the immediate loss of life but also dealing with people who are injured and the loss of critical infrastructure—such as that providing fresh water—and the consequences that has for the prospects of major disease outbreaks. Of course, one of the greatest risks facing the survivors of the tsunami was disease arising from the water or airborne diseases. The lack of fresh water and sanitation meant that outbreaks of communicable diseases such as cholera and typhoid were, rightly, very greatly feared as the next big killer after the devastation of the tsunami itself.</para><para>As recently as 4 February this year, the World Health Organisation has reported that there have been no outbreaks of disease in tsunami affected areas. That can be seen to be due to the unprecedented level of assistance from the world and from Australia to prevent that kind of catastrophe happening. Incidents of tetanus, measles and malaria have occurred but these appear to be controlled; the ability to react quickly has been crucial in ensuring their control. Australia has provided aid in the health and medical area to reduce risk. Particularly, we provided a water purification plant, capable of producing up to 480,000 litres of water a day, for distribution to the devastated communities in Banda Aceh. We also sourced and delivered 129,000 20-litre water containers to Banda Aceh to keep the supply of fresh water flowing.</para><para>There has been funding provided for a water and sanitation specialist to undertake an assessment and provide support for the provincial administration in addressing the immediate water supply and sanitation needs in Aceh. The World Health Organisation has formulated a mental health response for the people of Banda Aceh. Given the level of devastation in this region, the World Health Organisation is assessing mental health needs, training community leaders and ensuring the Aceh psychiatric hospital is equipped to deal with the longer-term effects of a disaster on this scale. Australia directly provided a 90-bed Australian Defence Force field hospital in Banda Aceh; funding for a team of 24 Australian doctors to provide urgent medical assistance; funding for a health assessment team, including specialists in health sector coordination, psychosocial support, child protection and infectious disease; and pharmaceuticals and medical supplies to Banda Aceh.</para><para>We have provided tetanus immunisation to treat and prevent the disease at the request of the World Health Organisation. We have provided medical supplies for the general hospital in Medan for the treatment of tsunami victims airlifted from Banda Aceh. We have provided support for re-establishing a procurement and medical supply distribution network in Banda Aceh and provided vital infrastructure and human resources for that purpose. We have supported the restoration of government mental health services by engaging a psychosocial trauma support specialist to undertake an assessment of the mental hospital and mental health needs more broadly in Banda Aceh. We have provided support for the restoration of government maternal health services by engaging a maternal health specialist, Kerry Ross, to conduct a rapid assessment of maternal health needs, focusing on midwife capacity, in the Aceh province. We have provided support for government engagement in infectious disease surveillance and control, and we have provided support for an infectious disease specialist from the Mentor, a malaria prevention non-government organisation which is now working on the issue of the malaria risk. </para><para>All of these things have been provided by Australia with Australian aid efforts. I would like to take the opportunity to congratulate all of those who have been involved in providing these services. Efforts of such enormous dimension require not only people on the ground providing the services but coordination. Huge amounts of work and rapid responses are needed. Hundreds of people, possibly thousands, have been involved in these individual health and medical efforts that I have reported to the House today. Each of those individuals deserves our great congratulation.</para><para>Whilst we are very proud of the rapid response, we know that there are ongoing issues that we need to deal with as a result of the tsunami. Some of those are in the health and medical area. As we move from the wave of the tsunami and the devastation it left to the time beyond, one of the deepest concerns is the mental health needs of those who have survived. When people have had their lives destroyed, when they have lost loved ones, when they have perhaps lost all of their family, there is obviously a need for ongoing mental health assistance and support.</para><para>The second ongoing challenge for us is to ensure that we look after children's health and wellbeing. In the Banda Aceh camps, where about four million people live, about three per cent, or 120,000, are children younger than five. UNICEF has warned that 12.7 per cent of children surveyed at camps in and around the provincial capital of Banda Aceh suffer malnutrition, which stunts growth, retards mental development and weakens the immune system. UNICEF has warned that conditions could be even worse outside the provincial capital and calls the situation a `critical emergency' requiring immediate intervention. So, as we have responded to the immediate challenge, now the task is to respond to some of these longer term challenges in the areas of children's health and mental health and the physical rebuilding that is required across the region.</para><para>Other members have referred to particular contributions that people in their electorates have made to the aid effort. I would like to take the opportunity to do the same. In my local community there was an immediate response to the fundraising effort, as I am sure there was across Australia. The Hudson family of Werribee were holidaying in Phuket at the time of the tsunami. Luckily they all survived. The Hudson family are good mates of mine—notwithstanding the fact that I run into them every election day handing out Liberal how-to-vote cards—but I do not take it personally. They are good friends, and it was good to see them all return to Australia safe and well.</para><para>The Morris and Freeman families of Werribee, who were holidaying in Phuket, stayed to help with the clean-up. My electorate is home to many members of the Sri Lankan community in Melbourne and obviously they were particularly affected and particularly concerned about the fate of their family members. A Melton resident, Rozanne Short, who is a Sri Lankan community member, helped with fundraising efforts locally, particularly within the Sri Lankan community.</para><para>The Point Cook Residents Association have been involved in a pattern of providing ongoing assistance. They are going to have a fun run in March, a trivia night in June, a bike-a-thon in October and a Christmas twilight function in December. So they have dedicated their functions across the whole year to fundraising for the tsunami. Local Wyndham residents Justine Colley and Jacquie Cook have coordinated fundraising efforts in the Werribee area. The Hoppers Crossing Cricket Club had a special match against the Sri Lankan community on Australia Day. St Andrews Primary School sold pancakes on Pancake Tuesday, and the proceeds of that are going to tsunami victims. So the efforts across my community continue, and I am sure that they are going to continue across this year and hopefully beyond, because that is what is going to be required to ensure that we help rebuild our neighbours from this disaster. </para><para>Whilst I am on my feet can I take the opportunity to also pass on my condolences to those who were affected by the South Australian bushfires. As members of this House might know, whilst I am a proud Victorian now, representing a Victorian seat, I grew up in South Australia. My parents and sister lived—it was not our family home—for a lot of their lives in the hills area. When you have got family members who live in those parts of Adelaide you always worry about bushfires. I was particularly concerned about family members when we faced the horror of Ash Wednesday all those years ago. Knowing what it is like to live with that kind of apprehension, I did feel a particular emotional call when we saw the devastation that flowed from the bushfires on the Eyre Peninsula, killing nine people and causing about $50 million worth of damage. So I take the opportunity to record my condolences to the surviving family members of people who lost their lives, and also to those who have been affected economically and in other ways by what was a very big bushfire disaster, even by Australian standards—and we are a nation that knows about big bushfire disasters almost more than any other nation on earth.</para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>11:32:00</time.stamp><page.no>139</page.no><name role="metadata">Turnbull, Malcolm, MP</name><name role="display">Mr TURNBULL</name><name.id>885</name.id><electorate>Wentworth</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—On 16 January after the terrible disaster of Boxing Day, there was a ceremony at North Bondi Surf Club at Bondi Beach. It was held in the ocean. A group of board-riders paddled out, formed a circle and cast a wreath into the ocean. It was a very poignant ceremony because of course nobody better understands than lifesavers the way in which the ocean not only entices us as a place to play and to sport ourselves in the sun but also is a very dangerous place. I think that might be why Australians have been so generous and have been filled with so much empathy and compassion for the victims of this disaster. Most of us live on the coast, most of us are very familiar with the sea and most of us recognise that as not only a place for enjoyment and a place for sport but also an element that can turn on you very quickly, be it a wave, a storm, a tide or, in this case, for the people of the Indian Ocean's rim, a gigantic tidal wave.</para></talk.start><para>I think we all recognise that these disasters can happen anywhere in the world. `There but for the grace of God go I' is a very important point. In Sydney Harbour there are giant sandstone boulders which were, geologists believe, thrown up over the cliffs, over the foreshore, into Sydney Harbour by giant waves. There is no reason to believe that the next tidal wave could not be hitting our shores or any part of it. It is hard to know—I am not a geologist, let alone a seismologist—but one has to ask why the big shift, the earthquake, that occurred off the coast of Tasmania did not itself create a tidal wave. Perhaps the next one will. Our hearts go out as humans. As the member for Flinders just said, we share a common humanity with all of the victims of this earthquake, as we do with the victims of all disasters. It is that humanity that ties us together all around the world, regardless of where we live. But we also share a special bond because of our understanding of the sea and our recognition of what the sea can do. </para><para>My wife and I had a very immediate connection with the disaster. A friend of ours who is a constituent of mine, a young woman called Cassie McGann, was staying in a place called Hikkaduwa in Sri Lanka. She rang my wife and left a message on Lucy's mobile phone. Her message went: `I'm sitting on a rooftop in Hikkaduwa. There's been an enormous wave and the waters are rising. Hundreds of people are dying. I don't know what's happened. I borrowed this phone from a French woman, but I think the battery is running out.' Then, indeed, it did run out and we heard no more from her. In the disaster we immediately thought, `How can we find her?' I have to say that the diplomats at the Australian High Commission in Colombo were outstanding. They were not just looking for her, of course; they were looking for all the Australians. But they immediately had teams of their staff going up and down that coast with vehicles, calling out, `Any Aussies? Any Brits? Anyone who speaks English? Are there any foreigners?' They were gathering them all together. Mercifully and miraculously, Cassie was found. She had managed to get to high ground, as, indeed, most Australians did.</para><para>It is genuinely a miracle that only a relatively small number of Australians have been killed. We miss every one of them; every one of them is a terrible loss. But, compared with the losses of other countries, including countries whose people in that region were mostly tourists, as ours were, our loss was very small. That underlines the great compassion and generosity of the Australian people. Of all the Western countries, we were probably the least affected in terms of people actually killed, and I suspect that is a function of the time of year. Most Australians who want to go to the beach on Boxing Day have a beach in Australia to go to rather than having to go to Thailand. That is not so if you are a Swede, a Norwegian or a German escaping from the frozen north. Notwithstanding that relatively small loss, tragic though it was, our contribution was greater per capita than any other country. I believe that great compassion and that generosity is because of the empathy we felt as a people who live mostly by the sea and are close to the sea and who do not turn our backs to the sea. As coast-living people we had a great and immediate empathy with that disaster, recognising its nature and recognising how it could have come to affect us.</para><para>The leadership shown by the Prime Minister and all his ministers has been outstanding, and I think it is wonderful to see such bipartisan endorsement for the government's leadership in the midst of this crisis. The Prime Minister's leadership was pre-eminent. He is the Prime Minister; it was his initiative to make this appropriately enormous pledge of aid to Indonesia, our nearest neighbour and the country that was worst hit. It is important to bear in mind, as the member for Flinders said, that no matter how good your warning system might have been no warning could have saved the people of Aceh. The earthquake was on their doorstep. Better warning systems are needed and will be put in place, and they certainly could have helped the people in Thailand, India, Sri Lanka and further afield. But if the earthquake is on your doorstep there will never be enough time.</para><para>The aid that has been given and the help that has been given by our defence forces and our public servants has been outstanding. I would also like to pay tribute to the outstanding work done by Alexander Downer, our foreign minister. Bruce Billson, the Parliamentary Secretary for Foreign Affairs, is, in many respects, an unsung hero. He was everywhere around the region organising aid. I had many discussions with him because many of my constituents who had relevant experience wanted to assist with support. </para><para>One organisation in which I am involved—of which I am a director, in fact—is Clean Up Australia, headed by Ian Kiernan. It is the largest grassroots environmental organisation in Australia and famous for organising Clean Up Australia Day, which we are all familiar with. Clean Up Australia, which has a very important commitment to water purification and water recycling, immediately put in place measures which enabled it to deliver a great many small water purification devices—you could call them `plants' but they are really more like devices—to the damaged areas so that people in villages could quickly get clean drinking water again. Obviously, large water purification plants are only suitable in large centres where there is a considerable population, and in Indonesia, in particular, the population is very dispersed.</para><para>In my electorate, as in every electorate—I think every member and every senator in this parliament would have had the same experience—constituents were immediately generous. People were generous in accordance with their means, and some people gave beyond their means. In my own electorate there were extraordinary events. There was one dinner that my friends Michael and Judy McMahon organised at Catalina, a restaurant in Rose Bay, which raised $277,000 in one night—an extraordinary amount of generosity. There were similar events at other restaurants and clubs, and there were walks, bikeathons and so forth. There has been a massive outpouring of compassion across Australia and of course across my own electorate.</para><para>The question, I suppose, when we talk about compassion and the generosity of our community is: how can we ensure that this continues? A lot of people are asking the question: is this just a one-off event? I visited the international charity Caritas, which is the Catholic Church's international relief agency, the other day and met with its director, Jack de Groote. They have obviously been overwhelmed by the generosity. But there are of course many other disasters in other parts of the world which have not been as spectacular but where the need is just as great. Has this event opened up the compassion in our hearts not just for this occasion but to make us a more generous, more compassionate and more humane nation? I hope it has. I believe it has. But I think it will be up to all of us to ensure that that spirit of philanthropy, that spirit of giving, continues across the community.</para><para>We should of course remember the victims of the South Australian bushfire disaster, who were very much closer to home. Natural disasters occur in many shapes, in many forms and in many different places. None of us are exempt. The victims of that disaster suffered just as the victims of the earthquake in the Indian Ocean did, and they have rightly deserved our compassion, support and sympathy as well.</para><para>In terms of the future protection against earthquakes, we cannot proof ourselves against earthquakes. The power of the earth not only exceeds the ability of man to resist it but exceeds the ability of man to comprehend it. One of the important lessons from all of this, I believe, is the need to focus on the ability to respond to disasters quickly. Were it not for the Australian and United States armed forces, the people of Aceh would not have received the aid they received in as timely a fashion as they did. The massive infrastructure that is required to deliver aid to these areas at this stage in this region is largely in the hands of the United States. After the United States, our ability to do that would be second. It is a very important role for the defence forces. It is extraordinary, really, to see that the United States—whose image in parts of Indonesia and the region has perhaps not always been as high as it would like it to have been—because of that massive military presence, was singularly able to give the relief that it did to the people in that region. </para><para>We need to think more about the ability to deliver aid. I remember speaking with diplomats in Colombo, on the telephone obviously, after the earthquake. They made the point—and this was even more the case in Indonesia—that there simply was no infrastructure left. The roads had been destroyed. It was extremely hard to get aid into places which had been so damaged other than by ship or by air. By definition, your conventional infrastructure has been destroyed, so you need something else.</para><para>In summary, this has been a disaster almost beyond comprehension. However, it has brought out in the people of Australia not just great sympathy and great compassion but great deeds by many Australians in the defence forces and the public service and by our diplomats and our medical teams. Right down to the day-to-day level of ordinary Australians, people have felt the pain of our neighbours in the Indian Ocean, and they have done their best, be it with big cheques from corporations or wealthy individuals down to coins in buckets in shopping centres and in churches. In doing that, we have shown what we have always known but too often forget: that everybody around the world, all of us, are each other's brothers and sisters, and when any of us are hurt or when any of us are subject to a disaster then we all suffer. We relieve that suffering by showing our compassion and our generosity in the way we have done.</para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>11:47:00</time.stamp><page.no>142</page.no><name role="metadata">Livermore, Kirsten, MP</name><name role="display">Ms LIVERMORE</name><name.id>83A</name.id><electorate>Capricornia</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I felt very strongly that I needed to speak on this motion. As an individual I wanted to express my sincere sympathy for the survivors of this terrible disaster and to pay my respects to those hundreds of thousands of people who have lost their lives. I also want to stand here as the member for Capricornia to express on behalf of my electors, the people of Central Queensland, their sense of loss and connection to this event that has rocked our world. Hopefully this is going to shape our world into the future as we meet the challenges that this disaster has presented to us.</para></talk.start><para>I got a sense of how the community was feeling when I attended a service at St Joseph's Cathedral, which is just a couple of blocks away from my house. Rockhampton's Churches Together group organised the remembrance service and put the call out to the community to come together to share our shock, our grief and our sense of solidarity and unity as human beings as we were confronted with the terrible images that were coming through the media, and the stories that people in our local community were connected to more directly from the disaster zone.</para><para>We met together at St Joseph's Cathedral, and one of the touches that was suggested—I believe it was by Bishop Brian Heenan from the Catholic Church—was for each person to bring a small tribute; not a wreath or a fancy bouquet that we can just ring up and order from the florist, but for each person or family to bring along a small tribute from their garden, something that meant something to them personally. It was quite moving to watch people from all walks of life from Central Queensland filing down the centre aisle of the cathedral and placing those floral tributes on the altar of the cathedral. Rockhampton is a very tropical place and of course there were hibiscus and frangipani and all the tropical flowers that are bursting out all over Queensland at the moment. More than anything else, that really spelled out to me the connection between the people of Central Queensland and the people in Thailand, Indonesia and Sri Lanka. We linked ourselves to that region through the image of those tropical flowers, because, of course, that is the environment our neighbours in the Indian Ocean and South-East Asia share with us as people of the tropics. That really brought home to me how my community was feeling and the importance of using this opportunity to express, on their behalf, their sympathy and feelings of solidarity with our neighbours who are trying to rebuild their lives after this terrible disaster. </para><para>Having said that I felt strongly that I should participate in this debate, I actually found it incredibly difficult to prepare for it because going through the news clippings and the speeches that have been made about this just brought it all back. It made me look again at the pictures of those orphaned children and the people who had lost everything. I also saw the joy that people with nothing material left in their lives felt when they found a loved one who they thought was missing. It really made me forget about being a member of parliament and respond to it as a human being. So, in trying to prepare for this, I really got lost in the enormity of it all—not just the scale of loss and the scale of the disaster but also the scale of the rebuilding effort that is going to be required by the international community as we help our neighbours in the Indian Ocean nations rebuild their countries, lives and communities.</para><para>It is one thing for me to relive it by flipping through some news clippings; it is another thing for the people who are actually living through this day by day—the people who have lost their homes, families and everything they know. This was really brought home to me when I attended the Asia-Pacific Parliamentary Forum in Vietnam in the middle of January. Sitting around the table were representatives from Malaysia, Thailand and Indonesia who were directly affected by this happening to their countries. The Indonesian delegation made a presentation on the first morning of the meeting. They had a video presentation that was the most graphic thing that I have seen in all the news coverage. This was an absolute fly-on-the-wall documentary, taken in what appeared to me to be real time, of people just sitting outside in Banda Aceh having breakfast in front of cafes, stopping to chat to neighbours—it was normal life happening in front of your eyes—and then all of a sudden there was water flowing down the streets. In the footage that I saw, it was quite innocuous—there was just this water coming. But then it kept coming, and all of a sudden it was not water anymore—it was a solid wall of debris sweeping everything in front of it. This idyllic scene of families talking, planning their mornings and eating their breakfast was swept away, both in reality in that location and metaphorically as that happened across a quarter of our world. It was so graphic and profound. The scale of the disaster was demonstrated to me by breaking it down to that very personal snapshot of what was happening in these people's lives as their whole world was swept away.</para><para>The point of all that is that, while it is hard for us to relive what happened, we have to keep reliving it, remembering it and understanding what is required to help these people get back on their feet. It was a situation where you could not change the channel; we were watching the video as part of the Indonesian presentation. As hard as it was and as horrific as it was, you could not change the channel. That is what we have to remember—the people in Thailand, Indonesia and Sri Lanka cannot change the channel. It is their life, and if it is their life then it is our life too.</para><para>The scale of the disaster was enormous but so was the scale of the response from Australia. I am incredibly proud of the $1 billion that the Australian government has provided and the leadership in the aid effort that we have shown as a country. There has also been a quarter of a billion dollars donated by ordinary people and corporations from around Australia. I pay tribute to the people in my electorate for the wonderful response they made. I do not think I have been to a community function since this happened where there has not been a raffle, tickets for a dinner or a street stall raising money and awareness of what is happening in these places, what is required to assist, and the importance of ongoing assistance to ensure that we do not forget what is needed to help these people. </para><para>I would also like to pay tribute to those people in my electorate who have gone to work as volunteers—the doctors, engineers and other aid workers who have gone over to these places to be confronted with incredible hardship and to work in a terribly testing environment. They are basically putting their comfortable lives, in many cases, on hold to help those most in need in our international community.</para><para>Although many members have said this, it is worth noting again: the open-heartedness and generosity demonstrated by the Australian people offer a new dawn in our relationship with Indonesia and our other neighbours. As I said, I was at the Asia-Pacific Parliamentary Forum in Vietnam not long after the tsunami happened, and the sense of unity, the sense that we needed each other as a region and that we had an obligation to each other, was incredibly strong. It was great to be part of the goodwill between all the countries. There was a coming together as human beings and as representatives of our various countries to say, `We want to know what you need and we want to be there to help in the long term.' That is going to set the platform for such a strong relationship going forward not only with Indonesia but with our other near neighbours.</para><para>We need to take forward the lessons that come out of this. We have heard much technical detail about the need for an early warning system and the importance of Australia getting on board with that not only for our own safety and security into the future but also to assist the countries that stand to lose the most if a similar event happens in the future. We need to offer our expertise and financial assistance for those early warning systems.</para><para>We also need to respect the power of nature. We need to understand our world and the environmental challenges we face. We need to work in partnership with other countries to ensure that we do not put our heads in the sand, that we use this demonstration of how powerful and unstoppable these natural forces can be, and that we respect nature, the environment and the planet we live on. We must make sure we do everything we can to live within our natural boundaries as residents of this planet. That includes things like the Kyoto protocol and understanding the challenges facing the small island-states in our Pacific region and in other parts of the world. When we focus on what has happened in the current disaster, we must also understand the environmental disasters that might occur in the years ahead which could affect the people living on the Pacific islands and in other small island-states around the world. We must help them—and certainly not make things worse for them—and understand that we all have to shoulder our responsibility to other nations and other people around the world.</para><para>In my remarks to the APPF, I obviously expressed my condolences and also that sense of solidarity and desire to do everything we can. But I think the most important thing for us as we conclude this debate is to keep remembering, to make sure that we do not change the channel when it gets a bit confronting or go on to the next thing that comes along—to make sure that we are there for the long haul with our neighbours. As I said to the APPF meeting, right now we have this great sense that we have done our bit, but we have to make sure that next year, the year after and the year after that we can look our neighbours in the eye and know that we have continued to do everything we can to help them as they rebuild their lives. Australia has the capacity to do it—we have already shown that in the last month—but we need to make sure that we continue to do it and continue to build those bridges, both real and metaphorical, with our neighbours. Thank you for the opportunity to participate in the debate on this motion. The bipartisan spirit that has been demonstrated in this debate has been very instructive and shows how we can work together when it really counts. </para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>12:01:00</time.stamp><page.no>145</page.no><name role="metadata">Southcott, Dr Andrew, MP</name><name role="display">Dr SOUTHCOTT</name><name.id>TK6</name.id><electorate>Boothby</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I would like to associate myself with this motion, support it and support the remarks of the speakers who have preceded me. Boxing Day in Australia is normally a day we associate with family, recovering after perhaps overindulging on Christmas Day, having a holiday if we are not involved in essential services, the start of the Sydney Hobart Yacht Race or the start of the Melbourne cricket test. There are always positive associations with Boxing Day. But now, for our lifetimes, we will always remember it as the day that the tsunami struck a number of countries right around the Indian Ocean.</para></talk.start><para>It is estimated that almost 300,000 people have lost their lives. In Aceh and in Sri Lanka there are people who have lost 50 or 60 members of their extended families. There are couples who were separated—including, of course, many Australians, and we know about them. There are children who were lost. I remember one story of a woman who was holding two children and let go of the older child. Luckily that child was saved—but just to hear that as a parent and think about ever having to make that sort of choice!</para><para>The tsunami was the result of an earthquake just off the west coast of Aceh. It appears that there is increased activity of the plates just off that coast. There have been a number of tremors in that area in the last four or five years. So, while tsunamis are uncommon in recent history in the Indian Ocean region, we do have these plates, where one has slipped underneath the other one, and it seems that tremors are now fairly common. In recent times, the biggest tsunami in that area was of course the tsunami from the explosion of Krakatoa in the 1880s. I think that led to the deaths of about 30,000 people in Indonesia, but this one has been on a different scale.</para><para>Many of these deaths were preventable. The travel times between the epicentre of the earthquake and Sri Lanka and Chennai and so on were quite long. We are not talking minutes; we are talking hours. Many of these deaths were preventable. It is hoped that, just as the Pacific Ocean has a very well-monitored and well-organised tsunami warning system, the Indian Ocean will be able to have something too.</para><para>Just as we found after the bombings in Bali, the tsunami struck many areas that Australians are familiar with. Many Australian holidaymakers would be familiar with the west coast of Thailand, especially Phuket island, with Sri Lanka, with the Maldives and with the Seychelles. We have overseas students studying in Australia and past students who have returned to their countries from Sri Lanka, India, Bangladesh, Thailand and Indonesia, including Aceh. A whole group of Acehnese students are studying in my own state at the University of South Australia.</para><para>For cricketers there were stadiums where they play test cricket, such as the stadium at Chennai, formerly Madras; and the stadium at Galle, where Shane Warne broke the record for the number of wickets taken in test cricket. There are many Australians with dual citizenship who have emigrated from these countries and who have families there. This was the largest natural disaster in the last 100 years and it affected an unprecedented number of countries. It affected their coastlines and so on, but it also affected an unprecedented number of nations and nationalities because of the Europeans who were holidaying in Sri Lanka and Thailand. These were tourist destinations, so it affected the whole world. </para><para>We saw unexpected heroes—the young Australians in Sri Lanka and Thailand, who had some training as nurses, doctors or whatever, who interrupted their holidays to go and do what they could, without many supplies and so on, to help their fellow human beings. There was a young British girl in India, who was about 10 years old, who had learnt in her class that when the water recedes it means there is going to be a Tsunami. She warned people on her beach when she saw this happening and was able to save the lives of hundreds.</para><para>The response to the tsunami I think showed Australia at its best. I was very proud of the response from the Australian government. I was very proud of the response from the Australian public. I was very proud of the response from those who were there who did what they could. Our military personnel are trained to adapt and they are up there now providing food, fresh water, medical supplies and a 90-bed hospital. The HMAS <inline font-style="italic">Kanimbla</inline> is there with 250 sailors and 150 engineers. In times of tragedy we do find heroes. Peter Cosgrove became known to us through East Timor. The Australian of the Year became known to us as a burns surgeon in Bali. We now have people like Colonel Georgina Whelan, a military surgeon.</para><para>We have sent five civilian medical teams. Many of those on the civilian medical teams from South Australia I know well—I worked and trained with them. Many of those people are enormously experienced. They have been to the Persian Gulf, Somalia, Bougainville, East Timor and so on. I met some of them last weekend and spoke to them about the work they did in cleaning up the hospital in Banda Aceh. They were given an incredibly tough job which involved cleaning up the hospital, removing bodies and so on, but they did it and they did it well. As a result of that, through the public face of Australia in Aceh—our military, our civilian medical teams and so on—we have earned enormous goodwill. We saw the Australian Public Service at its best. There was a really coordinated response right across government.</para><para>For the National Day of Mourning and Reflection last January I was able to attend a service at the Somerton Park Baptist Church and later a multifaith service at St Peter's Anglican Cathedral, which was really moving and involved Hindu, Thai, Muslim and Christian representatives. Later this month I will be going to a dinner to raise funds for people in India and Sri Lanka at the Hindu temple in Oaklands Park, in my electorate.</para><para>As part of this response we have announced $1 billion to Indonesia over five years. I am very proud that we have announced this. It is very important in the administration of this that we do not lose the goodwill that our volunteers have gained in Indonesia. This money will attract all sorts of carpetbaggers and it is really important that we attract people who are working with goodwill and working to advance the way in which Australia is seen in this area. We have had something like 6,000 medical personnel register to volunteer in a tsunami area, and I think that is great. But I am concerned that we may see, with this, people who may lose us some of the goodwill that we have.</para><para>I would like to conclude by paying tribute to a constituent of mine who was visiting Sri Lanka when the tsunami struck. He was Sujeewa Kamalasuriya, a 39-year-old Adelaide businessman. He was originally from Sri Lanka and he moved to Australia in 1990. He lived in my electorate of Boothby in Melrose Park, and he became an Australian citizen about five years ago. He ran an Adelaide cleaning business. He was a keen cricketer—he represented Sri Lanka at the under-19 level and he played with the Adelaide High Old Scholars. He was snorkelling off Unawatuna Beach, south of Colombo, when the tsunami struck. His business partner, Sarah Roberts, was rescued but he unfortunately drowned. His body was later recovered and there was a funeral held in Adelaide in January. I would like to again give my condolences to all those who lost friends or family in the tsunami, especially to the friends and family of my constituent Sujeewa Kamalasuriya. </para></speech><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>12:12:00</time.stamp><page.no>147</page.no><name role="metadata">King, Catherine, MP</name><name role="display">Ms KING</name><name.id>00AMR</name.id><electorate>Ballarat</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I thank the House for the opportunity in this place to recognise the enormous loss of life in South-East Asia and to come together as a parliament in support of the devastated communities across the region. Like the rest of the nation I watched with horror the events as they unfolded on Boxing Day. As the number of dead and missing grew each hour and the first images of what had happened and the devastation left behind began to appear on our television screens, the enormity of the tragedy sank in. Who could believe that water could do such damage in such a short time?</para></talk.start><para>People who have been to the region cannot find the words to describe the enormity of what they have seen. Traumatised survivors struggle to regain some normality in communities that have literally lost well over half of their populations. The response of the Australian community has been enormous. We can be an open-hearted, generous community, and our prompt response to the tsunami has shown that we are prepared to dig deep for disaster victims. Like all other MPs, I have many stories of local generosity, from the schoolchildren who set up lemonade stalls in the street, the Ballarat Regional Multicultural Council's concert to assist the people of the Ampara region in Sri Lanka, the City of Ballarat's variety concert—</para><para><inline font-style="italic">A division having been called in the House of Representatives—</inline></para><para><inline font-weight="bold">Sitting suspended from 12.15 p.m. to 12.29 p.m.</inline></para><continue><talk.start><talker><name.id>00AMR</name.id><name role="metadata">King, Catherine, MP</name><name role="display">Ms KING</name></talker><para>—Other examples of generosity have come from the Anglican church's coffee morning concert and trivia night, the Clunes community donation of the Coloma Day proceeds, the collections taken in Bacchus Marsh and the fundraising concert and the many fundraising activities of Caritas, the Seventh Day Adventists, Oxfam, Red Cross and all of the individual efforts across the Ballarat, Hepburn and Moorabool shires.</para></talk.start></continue><para>There are two people to whom I particularly want to pay tribute. The first is Sally Harvey from Lyonville. A few weeks after the tragedy, Sally sent an email to friends in the Hepburn shire. She says, in part:</para><quote><para>Hello one and all</para><para>By now I have spoken to some of you and you will be aware of the project I have embarked on. Thinking about the terrible and almost unbelievable circumstances and ramifications of this tragedy, I wondered what a single mother might do other than making a $10 or so donation which, however useful, is not really the sort of contribution that satisfied my ideal of possibilities available. So I decided to have a performance night extravaganza and make a community event out of it to ensure that as many people as have an urge to have an opportunity to participate and to have a concerted effort to raise a substantial sum to help those in a situation that is affecting young and old alike all over the world.</para></quote><para>I seek leave to continue my remarks later.</para><para>Leave granted; debate adjourned.</para></speech></debate><debate><debateinfo><title>ADJOURNMENT</title><type>Adjournment</type><page.no>148</page.no></debateinfo><para>Mr NEVILLE (Hinkler) (12.30 p.m.)—I move:</para><motion><para>That the Main Committee do now adjourn.</para></motion><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Alcohol</title><page.no>148</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>12:30:00</time.stamp><page.no>148</page.no><name role="metadata">Quick, Harry, MP</name><name role="display">Mr QUICK</name><name.id>AV5</name.id><electorate>Franklin</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—`Australians are dying for a drink' was the message members and senators received at a very important briefing earlier this week. The briefing was conducted by Professor Ian Webster, Chair of the AER Foundation. AER stands for alcohol education and rehabilitation. The foundation is an independent company that was set up in 2001 with a grant from the Australian government. Its charter is to enhance the capacity of the alcohol and other drugs sector to address alcohol and other illicit substance abuse and to promote the responsible consumption of alcohol.</para></talk.start><para>Qualitative research was carried out for AER by Quantum Market Research, and interviews were conducted in New South Wales, Victoria, Queensland, South Australia and Western Australia with people 16 years and over. Mr Daryl Smeaton, CEO of the AER Foundation, highlighted the fact that:</para><quote><para>... alcohol is a `sacred cow' in Australia. It is an intrinsic part of our social fabric with people reporting a gentle pressure to drink and that choosing not to drink can be confronting for those who do.</para></quote><para>Daryl Smeaton goes on to say:</para><quote><para>Individuals describe a reluctance to challenge people who are drinking to excess; the right to drink alcohol is linked to an individual's freedom.</para></quote><para>The research shows that here in Australia we have a huge problem caused by alcohol misuse, a problem that is increasing in severity and one which receives very little real funding compared with the massive amount of federal funding spent targeting illicit drug users. No other social problems result in such widespread harm to so many Australians. It is a fact that impulsive behaviour caused by excessive use of alcohol is a major factor in the following: 70 to 80 per cent of night-time assaults, 50 per cent of domestic and sexual violence, 50 per cent of deaths from assault, 44 per cent of deaths from fires, 35 per cent of industrial accidents, 34 per cent of deaths from falls and drowning, 30 per cent of all road deaths, 16 per cent of child abuse deaths and 12 per cent of suicides.</para><para>What do these percentages mean in reality? It is hard to believe that every year in Australia alcohol misuse contributes to around 3,500 deaths, the majority being avoidable accidents. A further 95,000 Australians are hospitalised. And what is the estimated financial cost of the problem to Australian society? A staggering $7.5 billion, and each and every one of us suffers that burden of harm. Australians need to be shaken awake from their apathy and confront the crisis that is affecting every aspect of our entire community.</para><para>And why do I say we have a crisis? The research highlights some frightening findings. I mentioned at the start of my speech that in Australian culture there is an acceptance that getting drunk is part of the Australian way of life. Drinking alcohol is seen as a rite of passage into adulthood. The frightening research findings are: nearly half of the respondents believed that getting drunk is an acceptable part of the Australian way of life; one in three believed that binge drinking is okay and that it is only a problem if you do it all the time; one in five believed binge drinking is okay as long as you do not embarrass yourself; one-third said it is okay to drink to excess at home or on special celebrations such as birthdays and anniversaries; and 21 per cent felt that you should not tell another person how much is too much when it comes to drinking. It is frightening, because there seems to be an acceptance of these beliefs. </para><para>Society accepts—nay, condones and encourages—its young people to become part of this binge-drinking culture. Remember what happens in schoolies weeks in Victoria, New South Wales and Queensland. Next week, across Australia, during orientation week at our universities we will see a week of alcohol abuse and alcohol excess.</para><para>Having a bronzed suntan used to be part of being Australian. However, the threat of skin cancer and the Slip, Slop, Slap campaign motivated more and more reasonable behaviour. If Australia can achieve a cultural shift away from the bronzed Aussie image where skin cancer incidences are reducing, then why, oh why, can't we do it with binge drinking?</para></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Flinders Electorate: Rural Support and Telecommunications Services</title><page.no>149</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>12:35:00</time.stamp><page.no>149</page.no><name role="metadata">Hunt, Gregory, MP</name><name role="display">Mr HUNT</name><name.id>00AMV</name.id><electorate>Flinders</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister for the Environment and Heritage</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I want to take this opportunity to announce a series of rural services which will assist the seat of Flinders and residents throughout Bass Coast, Westernport and the Mornington Peninsula, primarily in the area of rural support services and improved telecommunications services. I want to congratulate those individuals and community groups that have fought hard for these services.</para></talk.start><para>My first announcement is about the Grantville rural transaction centre. I am delighted to inform the House that the Grantville rural transaction centre will officially open on 19 March 2005. One month from now we will see a new centre opening on the main highway which will provide a range of new and enhanced services: (1) it will provide local government services (2) it will be a Centrelink access point (3) it will have Medicare Easy Claim facilities and (4) most important of all the different facilities, the Grantville transaction centre will include medical rooms. Already, thanks to the work of Bass Coast Shire Council, particularly Councillor John Hulley, who has done a tremendous job, and Helen Padalini, also from the Bass Coast Shire Council, there will be a doctor who will visit there on a part-time basis. That is a tremendous outcome and a great result for the towns of Corinella, Coronet Bay, Glen Forbes, Kernot, Almurta and, of course, Grantville and the town of Bass itself. On 19 March, along with a series of other facilities which come with it, the Bass Coast Shire Grantville rural transaction centre will be opened. That is great step forward. I want to congratulate all those involved—in particular, the community, led by Councillor John Hulley and Helen Padalini, and the broader community in general.</para><para>My next announcement concerns a series of mobile and broadband telephony services which have been increased or will be increased across Flinders. In relation to mobile phone coverage, Optus has installed 10 new mobile sites over the past two years. Significantly, it plans to improve mobile coverage within the seat of Flinders in at least eight areas over the coming two years in Blairgowrie Beach, Rye, central Rosebud, east Rosebud, the Osborne area of Mount Martha, central Moorooduc, Tooradin and north Lang Lang. There will be improved mobile phone coverage from Optus in all those areas. Similarly—and this is one of the benefits of competition—Telstra has increased and will increase both its broadband and its mobile coverage throughout the Mornington Peninsula and Westernport areas. It has done so over the last few years and will do so in the coming few years. Broadband—and I am delighted to say this—has recently been extended to Crib Point, Fingal, Flinders, Pearcedale, Shoreham, Warneet, Tyabb and Devon Meadows. Over the coming 16 months broadband is planned for Koo Wee Rup, Grantville, Corinella, Main Ridge, Red Hill, Tooradin, Newhaven and San Remo. All of those areas will have increased broadband services. I am delighted with the result and pleased to have been able to work with the community on those outcomes in each of those areas. </para><para>In addition to that, mobile coverage has already been extended in Ventnor, Anderson, Newhaven, Hastings, Cranbourne, Tooradin, Blairgowrie and Sorrento and will be extended to Rosebud, Cranbourne and Balnarring. Hopefully, it will also be extended to Shoreham, Boneo, Moondah Beach and other areas on the Mornington Peninsula. Taken together, that is a tremendous set of initiatives. I believe that we have made real progress. Something as simple as a payphone can make a difference to those who can neither afford nor have access to telephony within their own homes. There will be four new installations in our area that will be completed in the next 18 months. They include a new payphone for Eramosa Road in Somerville, Josephine Avenue in west Cranbourne, Point Nepean Road in Rosebud and also Mathis Avenue in Tootgarook, amongst others. Telecommunications and medical services are critical. On both of those fronts we are making tremendous progress. I am delighted to inform the House of this, and I thank the community. <inline font-style="italic">(Time expired)</inline></para></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Communications: The Ashes</title><page.no>150</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>12:40:00</time.stamp><page.no>150</page.no><name role="metadata">Livermore, Kirsten, MP</name><name role="display">Ms LIVERMORE</name><name.id>83A</name.id><electorate>Capricornia</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I want to add my support to the growing number of calls for the upcoming Ashes series to be broadcast on free-to-air television. I am sure we all have stories from our families about our fathers or grandfathers sitting there wrapped up in a blankets on a cold winter's night in front of the old radiogram listening to the broadcasts of the Ashes tours of England in the fifties and sixties. In my family there is a story of my dad falling asleep on the floor listening to the test cricket coverage in the middle of the night. I suspect there are a number of members of this chamber who have similar memories of their introduction to Ashes cricket.</para></talk.start><para>The government needs to act, and act now, if it is to preserve those experiences in the lives of our current generation of young cricket fans. The government has itself acknowledged the importance of events like the Ashes test series to our sense of national identity and pride by including them in the antisiphoning scheme set up in the Broadcasting Services Act. The purpose of the scheme, we are told, is to protect the access of Australian viewers to events of national importance and cultural significance on free-to-air television by preventing pay TV operators from siphoning off television coverage of those events before free-to-air broadcasters have an opportunity to obtain broadcasting rights.</para><para>The problem is that the upcoming Ashes series has fallen through the gaps in the government's antisiphoning scheme and at this stage will only be seen by the 25 per cent of Australians who have access to pay TV. So far the government has adopted a hands-off approach which is totally indifferent to the concerns of ordinary sports fans in my electorate. For example, in answer to a question in the Senate on 18 November last year the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts said:</para><quote><para>The acquisition of broadcast rights is, I am sure all would agree, a commercial decision for the relevant broadcasters.</para></quote><para>The minister went on to say:</para><quote><para>Ultimately, the government would not as a matter of principle dictate day-to-day decisions on programming which are taken by either the national or commercial broadcasters.</para></quote><para>We are not asking the minister to do the networks' job for them, but we are asking the minister to do her job—that is, to protect the interests of the average Australian viewer like those in my electorate. The truth is that Channel 9 has grabbed so many exclusive rights to major sporting events that it cannot do justice to any of them. We have seen a fall in attendances at football matches and cricket matches because the public is not given enough coverage to maintain the public interest in these sports. Now with the Ashes we see the true damage done to our Australian way of life as this government allows our great sporting tradition to be used for profit by a few media moguls. </para><para>Last year, for example, my constituents complained that they were not able to see their favourite AFL team on free-to-air television. They did not understand why they had to give up their Friday night indoor bowls or other activities if they wanted to see their rugby league match of the round. You have to ask yourself: who decided to move the rugby league games? Who decided that Channel 9 would not take this year's Ashes tour? Who decided that regional Queenslanders could only watch Aussie rules after 11 p.m.? Of course it is the same people who stand to gain the most by forcing sports fans onto pay TV. Once again we see regional Australians suffering as this government does everything it can to give Mr Murdoch and Mr Packer everything they want.</para><para>At the moment the ABC are the only ones in there having a go. The ABC are negotiating over broadcast rights for the Ashes with the England and Wales Cricket Board, but they need help from the government to give them the best possible chance of securing free-to-air broadcast rights. In the Senate estimates hearings earlier this week Mr Russell Balding explained that the ABC could be assisted by the minister keeping the Ashes tour on the antisiphoning list—and not accede to the request by the English cricket board to de-list the Ashes series—and would like the parliament to consider lifting the genre restrictions on the ABC's second digital channel. Of course the ALP has gotten behind that call and is asking the minister to do those things to give the ABC the best chance possible of broadcasting the Ashes. The people of Central Queensland have had enough. They demand that this government does whatever is necessary to ensure the 2005 Ashes series is broadcast live and free to air for all Australians. Otherwise it will no longer be a question of the game never being the same but rather that the game will simple cease to be.</para></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Human Rights in Darfur</title><page.no>151</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>12:45:00</time.stamp><page.no>151</page.no><name role="metadata">Laming, Andrew, MP</name><name role="display">Mr LAMING</name><name.id>E0H</name.id><electorate>Bowman</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I acknowledge the member for Capricornia, who joins a long list of people from the opposition speaking about antisiphoning but coming up with simply no concrete solution to coverage of the Ashes series, except suggesting that somebody steps in or we protect the interest of Australian viewers. How relative things are. Just eight years ago damage to the Australian way of life was no jobs, inflation, interest rates, collapsing businesses and no hope for ordinary Australians, and now damage to the Australian way of life is not having coverage of the Ashes series locked in a few weeks before the first test.</para></talk.start><para>I rise to continue my remarks from Monday on the ongoing humanitarian and human rights crisis in Darfur in Western Sudan. I am driven to make these comments because of my time on the Sudanese border just one month ago at a time when President Mubarak was announcing a package of aid and economic cooperation from Egypt for Sudan. It is of great concern to me that within that country, as one examines the current situation in Darfur, we are seeing shades of Rwanda—the great lesson in public policy of the last century about inaction and indecisiveness. Those atrocities in Rwanda ring loudly in the ears of anyone who was involved in international aid and reconstruction over the last decade. </para><para>The causes of this particular conflict are unique, but they have a familiar pattern. Competition back in the 1980s between the nomadic and mainly northern Arabic populations and the more stable grazing and farmland communities further south has led to an administrative system heavily biased in favour of the Arabic tribes, who control 19 of the 24 administrative areas. The Khartoum government has supported that and discriminated against and marginalised the African communities by providing support to the Janjaweed to suppress the non-Arab populations. Janjaweed is a colloquial expression which means `man with a gun on a horse'. These militiamen are primarily members of a nomadic Arab tribe who have lighter skin than their African counterparts.</para><para>Earlier this month, the United Nations special inquiry found that attacks by the Janjaweed militia were occurring with the acquiescence of state officials, and that is the problem: the notion of state sovereignty and whether we can intervene in situations like this. It flows on from 18 September 2004, when the United Nations Security Council passed resolution 1594 establishing a commission of inquiry and raising the possibility of sanctions against Sudan if it did not act to stop attacks against civilians and allow humanitarian agencies to do their good work without hindrance.</para><para>Jan Pronk, the UN's special representative, commented in his report that the el-Bashir government had failed to stop the Janjaweed. According to that report—and, again, doesn't this sound like Rwanda or echoes of the Congo, where there have been 70,000 deaths each and every year for two decades—there has been indiscriminate and widespread killing and bombing of civilians; the forcible transfer of 1.85 million Darfur civilians; the creation of 1.65 million internally displaced persons, with over 200,000 refugees fleeing across the border to Chad; the destruction of 2,000 villages and hamlets; the systematic perpetration of rape and violence, including abduction, torture and gang rape of women and girls; the plundering and looting of civilian property; the torture and inhumane treatment of civilians—and the list goes on.</para><para>The Australian government wrote to the President of the United Nations Security Council on 28 January this year, urging action to prevent further violence in Darfur. The Australian government has called for the introduction of targeted measures, such as individual travel bans and asset seizures, to bring pressure to bear on the parties. We know that these are important steps but of limited impact unless they are coordinated through the UN. The Minister for Foreign Affairs has already indicated that, if requested by the United Nations, Australia would consider sending assistance or a small peacekeeping force.</para><para>I commend the Australian government, and I commend the Minister for Foreign Affairs for his continued support of humanitarian efforts in Darfur and for urging a cessation of violence. It is clear from those actions of Minister Downer that the Australian government is committed to supporting those international efforts fully to end this appalling tragedy. The echo of Rwanda in our ears is heard still and also that famous comment of our former foreign minister that there is no peacekeeping possible when there is no peace to keep—and I hope I have paraphrased him correctly. We must build consensus. We must ensure that we act before it is too late. Africa's ethnic and tribal disputes must not be considered as a matter of national sovereignty and ignored. The spill-over effect to other economies is substantial. The instability that leads to erosion and loss of physical, financial, human and social capital is enormous. </para></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Safety, Rehabilitation and Compensation Act</title><page.no>153</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>12:49:00</time.stamp><page.no>153</page.no><name role="metadata">Ripoll, Bernie, MP</name><name role="display">Mr RIPOLL</name><name.id>83E</name.id><electorate>Oxley</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I want to speak about the effects of section 21 of the Safety, Rehabilitation and Compensation Act and in particular about its effects and the unreasonable hardship it is causing to one of my constituents, Ian Emery, and his family, and to many other former public servants. Changes were made in 2001 to ensure that all federal public servants on compensation received 75 per cent of their former salary. The level of 75 per cent was promoted in the compensation scheme's charter. The changes to section 21 of the above act ensured that all federal public servants who remained on ongoing compensation payments received that amount of former salary. These changes fail to include Mr Emery or the cohort group that he belongs to of some 1,500 former public servants, some of whom are receiving as little as 40 per cent of former salary. Mr Emery received a voluntary redundancy package and remains on ongoing compensation payments because Comcare's support for invalidity and retirement was not accepted by the retirement benefits office.</para></talk.start><para>While sections 19, 20 and 21 under the SRC Act were originally introduced to avoid double-dipping—prior to 1988 officers were actually entitled to receive payments both from ComSuper and Comcare—it was at no time the intention of the original legislation to create further disadvantage to those falling within the provisions of sections 19, 20 and 21. Mr Emery's financial hardship is further compounded by the reduction of his wife's parenting allowance by some 80 per cent as a result of the CPI increases that Mr Emery is paid. It reduces his wife's payment by 50 per cent on each increase. This has effectively reduced Mrs Emery's parenting allowance from $370 to just $70 per fortnight.</para><para>The two areas of concern under the SRC Act which I would like to draw to the attention of the House are as follows: firstly, the deeming provisions for lump sum superannuation payments and, secondly, the discounting of the weekly compensation payments by five per cent to take account of the amount that the employees are required to pay as a compulsory contribution to superannuation. The only explanation for this deduction offered by Department of Employment and Workplace Relations is stated in their training manual—that is, `because it came out before'. It is simply that. There is no other reason. Just because it happened in the past, it continues to happen now.</para><para>Under section 21 of the SRC Act the deeming provisions for lump sum superannuation payments prescribe the application of a notional rate of 10 per cent per annum. Provisions apply when a person in receipt of compensation exits from employment under voluntary redundancy provisions and takes superannuation entitlements as a lump sum. To determine the notional weekly value of the superannuation lump sum benefit, it is divided by 520. This divisor assumes that over the long-term period invested at 10 per cent there will be a certain specific return. This rate was set in 1988 when interest rates were much higher. A former employee in receipt of both a compensation related payment and a lump sum has the amount of weekly payments reduced by the method set out, which I have just explained. Each year, therefore, it is assumed that the superannuation lump sum is generating an earning rate of 10 per cent. The fortnightly compensation payment, under the SRC Act, is reduced accordingly. Hence the inequality in what is taking place today.</para><para>For the past 10 years, Mr Emery's lump sum payment has been deemed with 11 per cent, which means a fortnightly deduction of $542 from his compensation payment. This has resulted in the recovery by the federal government of more than the total amount of $141,000 that Mr Emery had originally received in his voluntary redundancy package in 1994. Mr Emery's case is a special case, as he and his wife and three young children are not only financially affected by the impact of section 21 but his wife's parenting allowance is also reduced by more than $300 per fortnight. I am sure members everywhere in this House can understand the extreme hardship that this person and his family are suffering, along with 1,500 other former public servants who are treated in a very inequitable way by the provisions under this act, which can be fixed. It was never the intention of this act to do this to people. </para><para>For employees who continue to work, the five per cent deduction from their salary accumulates a benefit which is repaid as a lump sum plus earnings on retirement. In contrast, the five per cent deduction is lost to Mr Emery forever, which is contrary to the intention of the current legislation. The intention of this superannuation deduction is clearly spelt out in Comcare's letter to the Superannuated Commonwealth Officers' Association Federal Council dated 18 March 2002, which states that the deduction is meant to continue a benefit. It does not in Mr Emery's case or in the cases of those other people it affects.</para><para>The Department of Employment and Workplace Relations appears to have failed to recognise this fact. I have written to them, I have written to the minister and I will continue to pursue this injustice until this area is fixed. The situation can easily be remedied in three ways: first, by adjusting the 10 per cent deeming rate to deeming rates used by other government departments; second, by either stopping the practice of discounting weekly compensation payments by five per cent or placing contributions into the fund that accrues the benefit; and, third, by immediately supporting an act of grace support for superannuation deductions made for those no longer in the fund. I believe, as I believe all other members in this place would, that we need to make this right, because it is hurting people. <inline font-style="italic">(Time expired)</inline></para></speech></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Herbert Electorate: James Cook University</title><page.no>154</page.no></subdebateinfo><speech><talk.start><talker><time.stamp>12:55:00</time.stamp><page.no>154</page.no><name role="metadata">Lindsay, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr LINDSAY</name><name.id>HK6</name.id><electorate>Herbert</electorate><party>LP</party><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I am pleased to say that James Cook University in North Queensland has done it again. James Cook is arguably now the leading regional university in Australia. Headquartered in Townsville, under the leadership of Vice-Chancellor Bernard Moulden, the university has powered ahead. Next week, after the conclusion of orientation week, university studies will begin and degrees in rehabilitation sciences will be available at James Cook for the first time. I am very pleased to say that the federal government has contributed significantly to these new degrees through the provision of some $6 million in capital to build a new rehabilitation sciences building.</para></talk.start><para>The building is state of the art. It will provide the best facilities of its type in Australia out of any of the universities in this country. It is a credit to James Cook University and to executive dean Professor Ian Wronski in what they have been able to achieve in the area of rehabilitation sciences. Many university buildings are just a set of walls and some windows; this building has been designed for the tropics and as a pleasant workspace. More than that, senior staff have been to other universities to take all of the best ideas and incorporate them in the new facility at James Cook. When the students enter the building next Monday, they are going to be delighted. The students themselves have voted with their applications. For every place that was available in the new courses, there were nine applicants. That is incredible and it is a great tribute to James Cook that students want to attend its rehabilitation sciences courses. </para><para>The new courses are integral to further developing high-quality tertiary education in North Queensland. Until now, students wishing to do degrees in rehabilitation sciences have had to go to Brisbane for their courses. I believe, as the university believes, that students who study locally will remain locally. It is particularly important in regional Australia that we have our fair share of scientists and practitioners to make sure that our community is properly serviced.</para><para>The degrees in physiotherapy and speech therapy came in response to the shortage of allied health professionals in Queensland, particularly in rural regions. The expansion of JCU's health and rehabilitation sciences degree has brought an extra 200 students to JCU. The degree headquarters will house a state-of-the-art sports performance measurement facility—the first of its kind outside a major Australian metropolitan centre.</para><para>But that is not all; James Cook has recognised there is more to do. We are already looking to the future, and in the next university year, starting in 2006, a new veterinary science course will begin. This will also be part of the health precinct that has been built at JCU. Mr Deputy Speaker Causley, you may say: why is veterinary science of interest in the health precinct? What it will be looking at and specialising in is the transfer of diseases in animals to humans, known scientifically as the process of zoonosis. We will see a tropical university looking at these sorts of things through a new vet science degree.</para><para>Then there is the tropical sciences research precinct which will be established. About $80 million will go into that. It is very exciting because it will be part of a collaboration and co-location with the reef CRC, Marine Science, CSIRO, the DPR&amp;F, BSES and so on. It is very exciting. In 10 years we will see James Cook in the top five research universities in the world for tropical sciences. It is a tremendous achievement from a university that in 1997 did not know how it was going to pay its salaries for the next week. Congratulations to James Cook University and its leadership. You have done well and you are going to do even better.</para><para><inline font-weight="bold">Main Committee adjourned at 1.00 p.m.</inline></para></speech></subdebate.1></debate></maincomm.xscript><answers.to.questions><debate><debateinfo><type>Answers to Questions in Writing</type><title>QUESTIONS IN WRITING</title><page.no>156</page.no></debateinfo><para></para><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Gambling</title><page.no>156</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 20)</subtitle><id.no>20</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>156</page.no><name role="metadata">Murphy, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Murphy</name><name.id>83D</name.id><electorate>Lowe</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister representing the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, in writing, on 17 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Can the Minister confirm that unregulated foreign betting exchanges are using their websites to actively target Australians with sports and race betting products in competition with legal wagering offered by Australian companies thus depriving the Federal Treasury of GST revenue and the states and community groups of gambling tax.</para><para>(2)	Can the Minister confirm that one of the organisations involved in this new form of internet gambling, Betfair, now has a senior executive permanently stationed in Australia to directly promote this service to Australian gamblers.</para><para>(3)	Is it the case that unregulated betting exchanges allow multiple real-time bets on virtually any sport and any outcome; if so, does this development have the potential to increase problem gambling and corruption in sport.</para><para>(4)	Can the Minister confirm that in the UK, where betting exchanges originated, gambling activity has increased dramatically resulting in the British Racing Authority asking the UK Government to conduct a Royal Commission into the activities of betting exchanges.</para><para>(5)	Why has the Government not acted to crack down on the foreign betting exchanges.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>156</page.no><name role="metadata">McGauran, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McGauran</name><name.id>XH4</name.id><electorate>Gippsland</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts has provided the following answer to the honourable member's question:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Interactive wagering and lotteries are not prohibited under the Interactive Gambling Act 2001 (IGA). To the extent that betting exchanges retain the inherent characteristics of a wagering service, they are not, therefore, prohibited in Australia.</para><para>	The Department of Communications, Information Technology and the Arts conducted the statutory review of the operation of the IGA. The objective of the IGA is to minimise potential social harm attributable to new and innovative forms of gambling, and betting exchanges were considered in this context. The review found that there was no compelling evidence to suggest that betting exchanges were likely to contribute to an increase in the level of problem gambling. The previous Minister announced the Government's decision not take any regulatory action specifically in relation to betting exchanges on 12 July 2004.</para><para>	The licensing and regulation of gambling services and the revenue received from them is a matter for State and Territory Governments. Any questions about GST revenue would need to be directed to the Treasurer.</para><para>(2)	I am unable to comment on the movements of employees of private companies.</para><para>(3)	See the response to part (1).</para><para>(4)	I understand the British Horseracing Board (BHB) called for an Independent Commission of Inquiry into betting exchanges in October of 2003. The UK Government has prepared a draft gambling bill, aimed at modernising UK gambling regulation. I understand the BHB has been heavily involved in this process, particularly in relation to betting exchanges.</para><para>	The bill has been subject to the scrutiny of a Joint House Committee of the UK Parliament.</para><para>	I understand that the BHB urged the Committee examining the bill to provide the proposed Gambling Commission (that would be established by the bill) with powers of investigation in relation to betting exchanges, among other things. </para><para>	The Joint Committee's final report of 7 April 2004 concluded that there was nothing intrinsically wrong with betting exchanges but supported the need for licensing for both government revenue and fraud investigation reasons. The Committee repeatedly noted the superior audit trail available from betting exchanges and the willing co-operation of the leading operator, Betfair.</para><para>(5)	See the response to part (1).</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Telstra: Outsourcing</title><page.no>157</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 22)</subtitle><id.no>22</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>157</page.no><name role="metadata">Murphy, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Murphy</name><name.id>83D</name.id><electorate>Lowe</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister representing the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, in writing, on 17 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Further to the answer to question No. 3042 (<inline font-style="italic">Hansard</inline>, 15 June 2004, page 29858), what ownership conditions did the Indian Government impose on Telstra, or its subsidiaries, before it granted Telstra permission to operate in India.</para><para>(2)	Is it the case that the Government of India requires that it own a controlling interest in a company before it allows it to operate in India.</para><para>(3)	What action is the Minister taking to ensure that employees of Telstra, or of its subsidiaries or affiliates operating in India, are being afforded industrial rights and privileges equivalent to those enjoyed by workers in Australia; if no action is being taken, why not.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>157</page.no><name role="metadata">McGauran, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McGauran</name><name.id>XH4</name.id><electorate>Gippsland</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts has provided the following answer to the honourable member's question:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	None. Telstra has advised that while some of its outsourced projects have been awarded to multinational firms that are undertaking part or all of the work in India, Telstra does not operate in India.</para><para>(2)	The question of ownership conditions imposed by the Government of India on companies operating in India are a matter for the Government of India.</para><para>(3)	Telstra has advised that it does not operate in India. See part (1).</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Telstra: Outsourcing</title><page.no>157</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 23)</subtitle><id.no>23</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>157</page.no><name role="metadata">Murphy, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Murphy</name><name.id>83D</name.id><electorate>Lowe</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister representing the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, in writing, on 17 November 2004:</para></talk.start><quote><para>Further to the answer to question No. 3042 (<inline font-style="italic">Hansard</inline>, 15 June 2004, page 29858), which jobs is Telstra proposing to move offshore and what are the details.</para></quote></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>157</page.no><name role="metadata">McGauran, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McGauran</name><name.id>XH4</name.id><electorate>Gippsland</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts has provided the following answer to the honourable member's question based on information provided by Telstra:</para></talk.start><quote><para>Telstra has advised that while some of its outsourced projects have been awarded to multinational firms that are undertaking part or all of the work offshore, Telstra itself does not operate in India.</para></quote></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Media: Cross-Media Ownership Rules</title><page.no>157</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 24)</subtitle><id.no>24</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>157</page.no><name role="metadata">Murphy, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Murphy</name><name.id>83D</name.id><electorate>Lowe</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister representing the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, in writing, on 17 November 2004:</para></talk.start><quote><para>Further to the answer to part (2) of question No. 3435 (<inline font-style="italic">Hansard</inline>, 1 June 2004, page 29466) can the Minister explain why it is desirable to allow further concentration of media ownership in Australia by Australia's two principal media proprietors owning both newspapers and television stations in Australia's metropolitan markets. </para></quote></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>158</page.no><name role="metadata">McGauran, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McGauran</name><name.id>XH4</name.id><electorate>Gippsland</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts has provided the following answer to the honourable member's question:</para></talk.start><quote><para>The Government is committed to reforming Australia's media ownership laws, while protecting the public interest in a diverse and vibrant media sector. The Government's previous media ownership reform bill lapsed following the calling of the election. The Government now has a further opportunity to consider its approach to media ownership reform, and as part of this process it will be consulting with stakeholders about the best means of implementing its commitment.</para></quote></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Media: Cross-Media Ownership Rules</title><page.no>158</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 26)</subtitle><id.no>26</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>158</page.no><name role="metadata">Murphy, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Murphy</name><name.id>83D</name.id><electorate>Lowe</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister representing the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, in writing, on 17 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Has the Minister read the article titled “Nationals flag serious concerns about media laws” published in <inline font-style="italic">The Australian Financial Review</inline> on 4 November 2004.</para><para>(2)	In respect of the report that, in relation to the intention to remove cross-media and foreign ownership laws or to draft a new plan, the Member for Page sees the need for the Government to look closely at the Trade Practices Act 1974, can the Minister explain what changes may need to be made to that Act; if not, why not.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>158</page.no><name role="metadata">McGauran, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McGauran</name><name.id>XH4</name.id><electorate>Gippsland</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts has provided the following answer to the honourable member's question:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Yes.</para><para>(2)	See answer to Question on Notice No. 24.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Media: Cross-Media Ownership Rules</title><page.no>158</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 27)</subtitle><id.no>27</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>158</page.no><name role="metadata">Murphy, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Murphy</name><name.id>83D</name.id><electorate>Lowe</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister representing the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, in writing, on 17 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Has the Minister read the article titled “Lees' about-turn on media law” in <inline font-style="italic">The Australian Financial Review</inline> on 5 November 2004.</para><para>(2)	In respect of the report that the Minister is considering whether to introduce the original media ownership bill or to introduce the form of the bill which contains concession that the Government had previously agreed to protect diversity, has the Minister met with independent Senators to discuss this issue; if not why not; if so, what was the outcome of those meetings.</para><para>(3)	In respect of the report that The Nationals are deeply worried that the bill will result in concentration of media ownership in rural areas and the centralisation of rural news rooms to the detriment of local news content, how is the Minister addressing these concerns.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>158</page.no><name role="metadata">McGauran, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McGauran</name><name.id>XH4</name.id><electorate>Gippsland</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts has provided the following answer to the honourable member's question:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Yes.</para><para>(2)	The Government will not discuss the details of individual discussions with MPs or Senators.</para><para>(3)	See answer to Question on Notice No. 24.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Media: Cross-Media Ownership Rules </title><page.no>159</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 28)</subtitle><id.no>28</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>159</page.no><name role="metadata">Murphy, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Murphy</name><name.id>83D</name.id><electorate>Lowe</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister representing the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, in writing, on 17 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Has the Minister read the article titled “Media law review to look at digital effects” in <inline font-style="italic">The Australian Financial Review</inline> on 10 November 2004.</para><para>(2)	In respect of the report that the Minister claims the Government will ensure that consumers can access more, not less, content and that the Minister needs to protect and promote diversity, can the Minister guarantee that the proposed legislation will prevent further concentration of media ownership in Australia; if so, how; if not, why not.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>159</page.no><name role="metadata">McGauran, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McGauran</name><name.id>XH4</name.id><electorate>Gippsland</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts has provided the following answer to the honourable member's question:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Yes.</para><para>(2)	See answer to Question on Notice No. 24.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Governor-General: Counter-Terrorism Exercises</title><page.no>159</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 140)</subtitle><id.no>140</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>159</page.no><name role="metadata">Melham, Daryl, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Melham</name><name.id>4T4</name.id><electorate>Banks</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Prime Minister, in writing, on 18 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	What was the nature of the Governor-General's participation in the national counter-terrorism exercise known as Mercury 04?</para><para>(2)	Did the Governor-General's participation in the Mercury 04 exercise relate to procedures for callingout of the Australian Defence Force?</para><para>(3)	Has the Governor-General participated in any other counter-terrorism or other emergency preparedness exercises; if so, what has been the nature of the Governor-General's involvement?</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>159</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Howard</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The answer to the honourable member's question is as follows:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	As the first ever multi-jurisdictional counter-terrorism exercise, Mercury 04 was the largest counter-terrorism exercise ever conducted in Australia, involving the Australian Government and the governments of Victoria, South Australia, Tasmania and the Northern Territory.</para><para>	The Governor-General participated in exercise Mercury 04 through simulated Executive Council meetings. The purpose of these meetings was for the Governor-General, acting on the advice of senior ministers, to consider applications for call out of the Australian Defence Force in support of state and territory civilian authorities, in accordance with arrangements set out under the National Counter-Terrorism Plan.</para><para>	During the exercise, the Governor-General also visited the National Crisis Centre and Exercise Control Central, both of which were located in the Protective Security Coordination Centre of the Attorney-General's Department.</para><para>(2)	See above.</para><para>(3)	As indicated above, Mercury 04 was the first exercise of its type and scope conducted in Australia. I am advised that the Governor-General has not participated directly in previous counter-terrorism exercises, although he has been briefed on issues relating to these exercises. The Official Secretary to the Governor-General has represented the Governor-General in previous annual national counter-terrorism exercises by participating in simulated Executive Council meetings to consider applications for call out of the Australian Defence Force.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Governor-General: Patronage </title><page.no>159</page.no><subtitle><inline font-weight="bold">(Question No. 144)</inline></subtitle><id.no>144</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>160</page.no><name role="metadata">Melham, Daryl, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Melham</name><name.id>4T4</name.id><electorate>Banks</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Prime Minister, in writing, on 18 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	What guidelines or other arrangements are in place in relation to decisions to extend vice-regal patronage to organisations.</para><para>(2)	What criteria are applied in determining whether the Governor-General or Her Excellency Mrs Jeffery agree to serve as patron of an organisation.</para><para>(3)	Does the Governor-General seek advice from him or his department before the Governor-General or Her Excellency Mrs Jeffery agree or decline to serve as patron of charitable or other organisations.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>160</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Howard</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The answer to the honourable member's question is as follows:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	to (3) I am advised by the Official Secretary to the Governor-General that requests for the granting of Vice Regal Patronage are considered on a case by case basis and on their merits. Factors such as, but not confined to, the nature and aims of the organisation, its financial status and source of funding, the degree to which the organisation has a national focus, and evidence of long standing credibility, are taken into consideration.</para><para>	I am also advised that the Office of the Official Secretary to the Governor-General consults officials from government departments, business and community groups and academia as necessary in formulating advice for the Governor-General and Mrs Jeffery.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Governor-General: Correspondence</title><page.no>160</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 148)</subtitle><id.no>148</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>160</page.no><name role="metadata">Melham, Daryl, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Melham</name><name.id>4T4</name.id><electorate>Banks</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Prime Minister, in writing, on 18 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Is he aware that the Governor-General writes to the Queen only “once or twice a year” to inform her of developments in Australia as reported in the Governor-General's interview in the <inline font-style="italic">Sunday </inline><inline font-style="italic">Age</inline> on 7 November 2004.</para><para>(2)	Have he and the Governor General discussed the frequency of correspondence required to ensure that the Queen is kept properly informed of developments in her Australian realm.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>160</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Howard</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The answer to the honourable member's question is as follows:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	and (2) No. Consistent with long standing practice, correspondence between the Governor-General and The Queen is of a private or personal nature.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Governor-General: China Visit</title><page.no>160</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 149)</subtitle><id.no>149</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>160</page.no><name role="metadata">Melham, Daryl, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Melham</name><name.id>4T4</name.id><electorate>Banks</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Prime Minister, in writing, on 18 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Can he confirm that the Governor-General will visit China in 2005 as indicated in the Governor-General's interview in the <inline font-style="italic">Sunday Herald-Sun</inline> on 7 November 2004; if so, (a) when will the visit take place, (b) will it be a State Visit, (c) will the Governor-General be received by the Chinese President when he visits Beijing, and (d) will the Governor-General visit any other countries; if so, which countries.</para><para>(2)	Did the Governor-General consult with him, the Minister for Foreign Affairs or any other Minister or relevant Department about the Governor-General's public announcement of the visit to China.</para><para>(3)	Did the Australian Government consult with the Chinese Government concerning the Governor-General's announcement of the visit to China.</para><para>(4)	When will a formal announcement of the Governor-General's planned visit to China be made by (a) him, and (b) the Chinese Government.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>161</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Howard</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The answer to the honourable member's question is as follows: </para></talk.start><para>(1)	to (4) The Governor-General has received an invitation from The President of the People's Republic of China to visit China and, consistent with well-established practice, the Governor-General has discussed the possibility of such a visit with me, along with visits to other overseas countries.</para><para>	Any announcement concerning the timing of a visit by the Governor-General to China will be a matter for mutual agreement between the Governments of The People's Republic of China and Australia.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Howard Government: Continuity of Government Plans</title><page.no>161</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 153)</subtitle><id.no>153</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>161</page.no><name role="metadata">Melham, Daryl, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Melham</name><name.id>4T4</name.id><electorate>Banks</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Prime Minister, in writing, on 18 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Can he confirm that the Government has Continuity of Government plans to minimise the impact of a terrorist attack or other emergency on the Executive Government and to ensure an early return to normal government functioning.</para><para>(2)	What funds or resources have been allocated to the development or enhancement of facilities outside Canberra which would allow the Governor-General or an Administrator of the Commonwealth, the Prime Minister and other Ministers and key public servants to carry out government decision making and communicate with the Australian public in the aftermath of a large-scale attack on the Commonwealth Parliament.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>161</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Howard</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The answer to the honourable member's question is as follows:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	I can confirm that the Government has Continuity of Government plans. These plans aim to minimise the impact of a national security emergency on critical government operations and provide for the rapid resumption of `near normal' government business under alternate arrangements until normal operations can be resumed.</para><para>(2)	I am advised that, wherever practicable, the plan relies on the use of existing facilities, resources and protocols but in some instances, modest additional resources may be required to develop or enhance facilities outside Canberra which would allow the Governor-General or an Administrator of the Commonwealth, the Prime Minister and other Ministers and key public servants to carry out government decision making and communicate with the Australian public in the aftermath of a large-scale attack on the Commonwealth Parliament.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Howard Government: Continuity of Government Plans</title><page.no>161</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 155)</subtitle><id.no>155</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>161</page.no><name role="metadata">Melham, Daryl, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Melham</name><name.id>4T4</name.id><electorate>Banks</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Prime Minister, in writing, on 18 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Is he aware of the first Report of the Continuity of Government Commission in the United States which was sponsored by the American Enterprise Institute and Brookings Institution and funded by the Carnegie, Hewlett Packard, and MacArthur foundations.</para><para>(2)	Is he aware of the Commission's observation that within the US federal system of government, the Congress is the institution least able to reconstitute itself after a catastrophic attack.</para><para>(3)	Has his department considered any of the issues discussed in the first Report of the US Continuity of Government Commission, for example, the potential for mass vacancies in the Parliament or large numbers of incapacitated Members or Senators leaving the Parliament unable to function for many months thus leaving a vacuum in constitutional legislative authority; if so, does the Government intend to take any measures to address these issues in the Australian context.</para><para>(4)	Can he assure the House that any Continuity of Government plans developed by the Commonwealth Government give full weight to the need to protect and, if necessary, re-locate Members of Parliament as well as Members of the Executive. </para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>162</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Howard</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The answer to the honourable member's question is as follows:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	I am advised that the Continuity of Government Commission in the United States issued its first report on the Continuity of Government: Preserving Our Institution - The Continuity of Congress in June 2003.</para><para>(2)	I am advised that the report states that `the commission chose to begin with Congress because [within the US federal system of government] it is the institution least able to reconstitute itself after a catastrophic attack'. The report also states that `the commission will issue subsequent reports on the continuity of the presidency and the Supreme Court' and notes that `some protections exist for reconstituting the presidency pursuant to the Presidential Succession Act, under [the US] current constitutional framework.'</para><para>(3)	I am advised that my department has considered the first Report of the US Continuity of Government Commission, including the issue of mass vacancies in the Parliament or large numbers of incapacitated Members or Senators.</para><para>	Clearly, arrangements for the continued operation of the Parliament, should there be a catastrophic event resulting in mass vacancies or incapacity of Members, are an important part of recovery plans. My department has closely liaised with the Parliamentary Departments in this regard, recognising that business continuity arrangements within their own areas, including planning for significant vacancies, are a matter for them to develop and arrange. The honourable member would be aware that business continuity management is an integral part of the risk management framework, including measures to prevent or minimise the effects of any adverse situation. To this end the government has provided funding to significantly increase security arrangements at Parliament House during the past three years to address these issues in the Australian context.</para><para>(4)	I am unable for security reasons to discuss in any detail Australian Government Continuity of Government arrangements. Business continuity arrangements in relation to Members of Parliament are the responsibility of Parliamentary Departments.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Governor-General: Letters Patent</title><page.no>162</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 156)</subtitle><id.no>156</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>162</page.no><name role="metadata">Melham, Daryl, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Melham</name><name.id>4T4</name.id><electorate>Banks</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Prime Minister, in writing, on 18 November 2004:</para></talk.start><quote><para>Is any person or persons currently appointed under section 126 of the Constitution and in accordance with paragraph VI of the Letters Patent dated 21 August 1984 to serve as a deputy or deputies to the Governor-General; if so, when were the appointments made and what are the terms of the instruments of appointment.</para></quote></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>162</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Howard</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The answer to the honourable member's question is as follows:</para></talk.start><quote><para>Three persons are currently appointed pursuant to section 126 of the Constitution and in accordance with clause IV of the Letters Patent dated 21 August 1984 to be the Governor-General's deputies:</para></quote><para>	Professor Marie Bashir, AC, Governor of the State of New South Wales;</para><para>	John Michael Landy, AC, MBE, Governor of the State of Victoria; and</para><para>	the Vice-President of the Federal Executive Council.</para><quote><para>The appointments were each made on 11 August 2003. The instruments of appointment were gazetted in accordance with clause VI of the Letters Patent, and are available from the House of Representatives Table Office.</para></quote></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Media: Cross-Media Ownership Rules </title><page.no>162</page.no><subtitle><inline font-weight="bold">(Question No. 160)</inline></subtitle><id.no>160</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>163</page.no><name role="metadata">Murphy, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Murphy</name><name.id>83D</name.id><electorate>Lowe</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister representing the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, in writing, on 18 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Has the Minister read the article about Australia's media ownership laws in <inline font-style="italic">The Sydney Morning Herald</inline> on 18 October 2004 titled “ACCC dampens media talk”.</para><para>(2)	In respect of the report that (a) any easing is seen as opening the way for News Corp to buy the Ten or Seven television networks and PBL to buy the publisher of <inline font-style="italic">The Sydney Morning Herald</inline>, John Fairfax and Sons, and (b) the Minister's plans would promote diversity by providing room for more players, including foreign companies, in Australia, can the Minister explain how the government's policy will stop further concentration of media ownership in Australia; if not, why not.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>163</page.no><name role="metadata">McGauran, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McGauran</name><name.id>XH4</name.id><electorate>Gippsland</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts has provided the following answer to the honourable member's question:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Yes.</para><para>(2)	See answer to Question on Notice No. 24.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Media: Cross-Media Ownership Rules</title><page.no>163</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 161)</subtitle><id.no>161</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>163</page.no><name role="metadata">Murphy, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Murphy</name><name.id>83D</name.id><electorate>Lowe</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister representing the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, in writing, on 18 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Has the Minister read the article about the Government's proposed media ownership changes in <inline font-style="italic">The Age</inline> on 18 October 2004 titled “ACCC warn on media buy-out”.</para><para>(2)	Can the Minister explain how the proposed changes to Australia's media ownership laws would not lead to an `open slather' for media firms.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>163</page.no><name role="metadata">McGauran, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McGauran</name><name.id>XH4</name.id><electorate>Gippsland</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts has provided the following answer to the honourable member's question:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Yes.</para><para>(2)	See answer to Question on Notice No. 24.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Media: Cross-Media Ownership Rules</title><page.no>163</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 162)</subtitle><id.no>162</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>163</page.no><name role="metadata">Murphy, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Murphy</name><name.id>83D</name.id><electorate>Lowe</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister representing the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, in writing, on 18 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Has the Minister read the article titled “Nats threaten to block quick sale of Telstra” in <inline font-style="italic">The Canberra Times</inline> on 18 October 2004.</para><para>(2)	Can the Minister confirm the report that the Government would move on its policy of loosening cross-media ownership controls and that the Minister acknowledged that this would lead to more foreign ownership of Australian media companies.</para><para>(3)	Can the Minister explain how the proposed changes to Australia's media ownership and foreign ownership laws would ensure that, for example, Mr Packer's and Mr Murdoch's media companies would not be able to purchase more Australian newspapers, radio stations and television networks and at the same time own and control their existing media interests; if not, why not.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>163</page.no><name role="metadata">McGauran, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McGauran</name><name.id>XH4</name.id><electorate>Gippsland</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts has provided the following answer to the honourable member's question:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Yes.</para><para>(2)	and (3) See answer to Question on Notice No. 24. </para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Telstra: Privatisation</title><page.no>164</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 163)</subtitle><id.no>163</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>164</page.no><name role="metadata">Murphy, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Murphy</name><name.id>83D</name.id><electorate>Lowe</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister representing the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, in writing, on 18 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Would the Minister provide an up-date on the Government's agenda in respect to the full sale of Telstra.</para><para>(2)	Are there barriers to the full sale of Telstra; if so what are the details.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>164</page.no><name role="metadata">McGauran, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McGauran</name><name.id>XH4</name.id><electorate>Gippsland</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts has provided the following answer to the honourable member's question:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	The Government has consistently stated the importance of the adequacy of rural telecommunications services now and into the future, and has undertaken to address this issue before Telstra is sold.</para><para>	High quality telecommunications services in regional, rural and remote areas are a key objective of the Government.</para><para>	The primary focus of the Government in ensuring the adequacy of regional telecommunications services is the implementation of the 39 recommendations made by the Regional Telecommunications (Estens) Inquiry (RTI). These involve arrangements to enhance existing and future telecommunications services in regional, rural and remote Australia.</para><para>	The Government is implementing its RTI response as a matter of priority.</para><para>	Services have already improved as a result of the Government's progress to date. But there are still more improvements to be made as recommendations are implemented. The Government is committed to implementing its RTI response in full.</para><para>(2)	The Government also plans to look at the adequacy of the current telecommunications regulatory regime and the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, Senator Coonan, is currently conducting a program of visits to rural and regional Australia.</para><para>	On 13 December 2004, the Government announced a scoping study into the possible sale of the Government's remaining shares in Telstra.</para><para>	The Government has consistently stated that it has three preconditions for any further sale of Telstra:</para><para>	Arrangements must be in place to give all Australians, in particular people living in regional Australia, access to adequate telecommunications services;</para><para>	Passage of sale legislation by Parliament that removes the obligation for the Government to own a minimum of 50.1 per cent of Telstra shares; and</para><para>	Market conditions being conducive to achieving an appropriate return for taxpayers from the sale.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Communications: Free-to-Air Television</title><page.no>164</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 164)</subtitle><id.no>164</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>164</page.no><name role="metadata">Murphy, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Murphy</name><name.id>83D</name.id><electorate>Lowe</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister representing the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, in writing, on 18 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Has the Minister read the draft report on the Productivity Commission's Review of National Competition Policy Reforms.</para><para>(2)	Will the Government act on the advice of the Commission to the effect that, unless the reviews currently in progress provide a good cause to the contrary, the Government should amend its broadcasting policy to remove the restrictions on the number of commercial free-to-air TV stations, multichannelling and datacasting as a pre-condition for liberalisation of cross- media ownership rules; if not, why not. </para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>165</page.no><name role="metadata">McGauran, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McGauran</name><name.id>XH4</name.id><electorate>Gippsland</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts has provided the following answer to the honourable member's question:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	I have read parts of the draft report.</para><para>(2)	The Government will give careful consideration to all issues raised in the series of reviews of the digital regime which is currently underway and will respond appropriately.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Communications: Free-to-Air Television</title><page.no>165</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 165)</subtitle><id.no>165</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>165</page.no><name role="metadata">Murphy, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Murphy</name><name.id>83D</name.id><electorate>Lowe</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister representing the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, in writing, on 18 November 2004:</para></talk.start><quote><para>Can the Minister explain how lifting the moratorium on free-to-air television licences would provide greater competition to the existing media companies in the provision of news and information to the public.</para></quote></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>165</page.no><name role="metadata">McGauran, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McGauran</name><name.id>XH4</name.id><electorate>Gippsland</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts has provided the following answer to the honourable member's question:</para></talk.start><quote><para>Licence arrangements after the end of the moratorium on free-to-air commercial television licences in 2006 are being considered in the context of the range of matters being dealt with in the reviews of the digital television regulatory framework. These reviews are required in 2004 and 2005 under the Broadcasting Services Act 1992.</para><para>The question of whether any further commercial television licences should be issued after 2006 will be one for the government of the day.</para><para>The Government is committed to media ownership reform. Clearly there are linkages between media ownership reform and other policy issues in communications, including those which have the capacity to change the structure of the industry and the competitive relationships between companies. These linkages will be examined by the Government as it considers the best means of implementing its commitment.</para></quote></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Governor-General: 41st Parliament Opening Speech</title><page.no>165</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 167)</subtitle><id.no>167</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>165</page.no><name role="metadata">Melham, Daryl, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Melham</name><name.id>4T4</name.id><electorate>Banks</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Prime Minister, in writing, on 29 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	In respect of the report in the <inline font-style="italic">Sydney Morning Herald</inline> on 17 November 2004 that the Governor-General wished to make personal additions or amendments to His Excellency's speech at the opening of the 41st Parliament, what is his understanding of the Conventions that apply to the drafting and delivery of the Governor-General's speech to the Parliament.</para><para>(2)	What latitude is there for the Governor-General to amend the text submitted to him by the Government.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>165</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Howard</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The answer to the honourable member's question is as follows:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	and (2) Established practice is that a draft is submitted to the Governor-General for his consideration. In accordance with that practice, a draft of the speech was given to the Governor-General on 10 November 2004, and he made minor changes to reflect his stylistic preferences.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Howard Government: Intergovernmental Agreement on Counter-Terrorism Laws</title><page.no>165</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 168)</subtitle><id.no>168</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>166</page.no><name role="metadata">Melham, Daryl, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Melham</name><name.id>4T4</name.id><electorate>Banks</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Prime Minister, in writing, on 29 November 2004: </para></talk.start><para>(1)	Can he confirm that (a) paragraph 3.4 (1) of the Intergovernmental Agreement on Counter-Terrorism Laws (the Agreement) signed at the Council of Australian Governments on 25 June 2004 requires the Commonwealth Government to consult with the States and Territories prior to the making of any regulation listing a terrorist organisation for the purposes of Part 5.3 of the Commonwealth Criminal Code, (b) paragraphs 3.4 (3) and (4) of the Agreement further require the Commonwealth Government to provide the States and Territories with the text of the proposed regulation together with a written brief on the terrorist related activities of the organisation to be listed by the regulation, and to offer an oral briefing by the Director-General of the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation, and (c) paragraph 3.4 (6) of the Agreement requires that approval for regulations listing terrorist organisations must be sought and responses from States and Territories must be provided through the Prime Minister and Premiers and Chief Ministers.</para><para>(2)	In respect of the making of regulations to re-list Al-Qa'ida and Jemaah Islamiyah as terrorist organisations announced by the Attorney-General on 1 September 2004, when and by what means did he consult with and seek the concurrence of the Premiers and Chief Ministers and did he provide the Premiers and Chief Ministers with the text of the proposed regulations, a written briefing and an offer of an oral briefing by the Director-General of ASIO.</para><para>(3)	In respect of the making of regulations to re-list the Abu Sayyaf Group, Armed Islamic Group, Salafist Group for Call and Combat and Jamiat ul-Ansar as terrorist organisations announced by the Attorney-General on 7 November 2004, when and by what means did he consult with and seek the concurrence of Premiers and Chief Ministers and did he provide the Premiers and Chief Ministers with the text of the proposed regulations, a written briefing and an offer of an oral briefing by the Director-General of ASIO.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>166</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Howard</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The answer to the honourable member's question is as follows:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Paragraph 3.4(1) of the Intergovernmental Agreement on Counter-Terrorism Laws (the Agreement) provides that “before making a regulation specifying a terrorist organisation for the purposes of Part 5.3 of the Commonwealth Criminal Code, the Commonwealth will consult the [states and territories] about it”.</para><para>	Paragraphs 3.4(3) and 3.4(4) of the Agreement further provide that “The Commonwealth will provide the [states and territories] with the text of the proposed regulation and will use its best endeavours to give the other parties a reasonable time to consider and to comment on the proposed regulation” and that “The Commonwealth will also provide the [states and territories] with a written brief on the terrorist-related activities of the organisation to be specified by the regulation and offer the [states and territories] an oral briefing by the Director-General of Security”.</para><para>	Paragraph 3.4(6) provides that “Approval for regulations specifying terrorist organisations must be sought, and responses from other parties must be provided, through the Prime Minister and Premiers and Chief Ministers”.</para><para>(2)	and (3) The Australian Government considers that the requirements in clause 3.4 of the Agreement do not apply to the re-listing of terrorist organisations. I am advised, however, that the Attorney-General wrote to state and territory attorneys-general on 30 August 2004 to inform them that he had decided to re-list Al-Qa'ida and Jemaah Islamiyah and to provide them with a written briefing prepared by the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation. The Attorney-General wrote again on 1 November 2004 to inform them that he had decided to re-list the Abu Sayyaf Group, Armed Islamic Group, Salafist Group for Call and Combat and Jamiat ul-Ansar and to provide them with a written briefing prepared by the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>`Children Overboard' Affair</title><page.no>166</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 178)</subtitle><id.no>178</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>167</page.no><name role="metadata">Beazley, Kim, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Beazley</name><name.id>PE4</name.id><electorate>Brand</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Prime Minister, in writing, on 29 November 2004: </para></talk.start><para>(1)	Does he recall telling the House on 12 March 2002 that in his view, “ministerial staff are accountable to the minister and the minister is accountable to the Parliament”.</para><para>(2)	At what point prior to 10 November 2001 did he have conversations with any Minister, staff member or Commonwealth official which cast doubt on whether children from <inline font-style="italic">SIEV4</inline> had been thrown overboard as suggested by the Government on 7 October 2001.</para><para>(3)	Did he have a conversation with the then Minister for Defence on or about 12 October 2001 which went to the veracity of the original report and whether or not subsequent evidence in the form of videos, photos, witness statements or defence reports failed to sustain the original allegation.</para><para>(4)	In his conversation with the then Minister for Defence on 7 November 2001 did the Minister mention his earlier conversation with the Acting Chief of the Defence Forces Air Marshal Angus Houston; if so, did the Minister's conversation include any expression of doubt over whether or not children had been thrown overboard as indicated in initial government statements.</para><para>(5)	How many conversations did he have with the then Minister for Defence's aide, Mr Michael Scrafton, and for how long, on 7 November 2001.</para><para>(6)	Did those conversations at any point carry the implication that one or both parties were aware that neither videos, photos nor witness statements provided evidence that children were thrown overboard because none, in fact, had been.</para><para>(7)	In his conversations with Mr Scrafton, was any mention made of the photos of the alleged incident previously released by the Government being not in fact photos of children who had been thrown into the water on 7 October 2001.</para><para>(8)	Does he recall that during his press conference on 19 February 2002 he suggested that he might have had a different recollection of the context of the conversation than Mr Scafton and, as none of the inquiries initiated by the Government reported such a difference, can he explain how he reached this conclusion.</para><para>(9)	Does he recall saying at his press conference on 19 February 2002 that on 7 November 2001 he had “....asked Miles (Jordana) to go through the material I had already seen or the office received”.</para><para>(10)	Did any of that material include papers or other documentation about the <inline font-style="italic">SIEV4</inline> incident which made no mention of children being thrown overboard.</para><para>(11)	In respect of Mr Jordana's examination of this material, (a) what documents, videos, photos or witness statements were drawn to his attention either directly, or in verbal briefings, from this process, (b) what information did they contain on whether or not evidence verified the initial government statements, and (c) who briefed him on this material.</para><para>(12)	When did Mr Jordana, or any one else in the Prime Minister's office, become aware that there was no evidence in videos, photos, or defence reports for the proposition that children on <inline font-style="italic">SIEV4</inline> had been thrown overboard.</para><para>(13)	Did he in any conversation with staff, ministerial colleagues or public servants indicate that he would rather not be briefed on the full circumstances of the <inline font-style="italic">SIEV4</inline> children overboard story prior to 10 November 2001.</para><para>(14)	Did he ask Mr Jordana or any other staff member in the days after the initial report to verify the facts around the interception and sinking of <inline font-style="italic">SIEV4</inline> and present them to him.</para><para>(15)	Did any `talking points' received by him from his staff, his department or the Department of Defence mention the <inline font-style="italic">SIEV4</inline> incident and what was the content of that reference.</para><para>(16)	On 7 November 2001, or at any time afterwards, did Mr Jordana inform him of advice that he had received from Ms Jane Halton regarding doubt his department had that the photos received and made public of the <inline font-style="italic">SIEV4</inline> incident verified that children had been thrown overboard. </para><para>(17)	On how many occasions prior to 10 November 2001 did he discuss the children overboard incident with Ms Jane Halton, what were the dates of their discussions and what advice did she provide.</para><para>(18)	On how many occasions after 10 November 2001 did he discuss the children overboard incident with Ms Jane Halton, what were the dates of their discussions and what advice did she provide.</para><para>(19)	On how many occasions prior to 10 November 2001 did he discuss the children overboard incident with Mr Max Moore-Wilton, what were the dates of their discussions and what advice did he provide.</para><para>(20)	On how many occasions after 10 November 2001 did he discuss the children overboard incident with Mr Max Moore-Wilton, what were the dates of their discussions and what advice did he provide.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>168</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Howard</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The answer to the honourable member's question is as follows:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	to (20) The Honourable member is referred to the numerous and detailed responses by the Prime Minister regarding these matters already on the parliamentary and public record.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Brand Electorate: Broadband Services</title><page.no>168</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 180)</subtitle><id.no>180</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>168</page.no><name role="metadata">Beazley, Kim, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Beazley</name><name.id>PE4</name.id><electorate>Brand</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister representing the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, in writing, on 29 November 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Is it the case that Broadband service is not available in all areas of the electoral division of Brand; if so, which regions or areas do not have access to Broadband.</para><para>(2)	Is the Minister aware that a substantial number of commercial enterprises in the electoral division of Brand are unable to obtain Broadband services.</para><para>(3)	Is the Minister aware that the owners of these businesses are being advised that the reason is that they are either (a) too far from the Exchange, (b) the service is not available due to insufficient pair gains or copper cable, or (c) they are on a rim that does not support ADSL.</para><para>(4)	Is the Minister aware of the numerous approaches made to Telstra by business owners in the electoral division of Brand regarding their inability to obtain Broadband services.</para><para>(5)	What has been the response from Telstra and what action is Telstra taking to address this situation.</para><para>(6)	Can the Minister say when Broadband services will be available throughout the electoral division of Brand.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>168</page.no><name role="metadata">McGauran, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McGauran</name><name.id>XH4</name.id><electorate>Gippsland</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts has provided the following answer to the honourable member's question, based in part on information provided by Telstra:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Broadband services are available in all areas of the electoral division of Brand through a variety of technologies including Asymmetric Digital Subscriber Line (ADSL), Hybrid Fibre Coaxial (HFC), wireless, Integrated Services Digital Network (ISDN), one-way satellite and two-way satellite.</para><para>(2)	As noted in the response to part (1), all businesses are able to access broadband services through either one or more of a number of technologies including Asymmetric Digital Subscriber Line (ADSL), Hybrid Fibre Coaxial (HFC), wireless, Integrated Services Digital Network (ISDN), one-way satellite and two-way satellite.</para><para>(3)	Telstra has advised that a number of business customers are currently unable to receive ADSL services in the electoral division of Brand due to technical barriers such as the distance customers' premises are from their local telephone exchange, and the presence of pair gain equipment or Remote Integrated Multiplexers (RIMs) in the customer access network. Normally, Telstra would notify individuals and businesses who have applied for an ADSL service and are impacted by one of these barriers of the reason why an ADSL service can not be supplied, and advise them of alternative broadband services. </para><para>(4)	Telstra has advised that it has received requests for ADSL services from businesses in the electorate of Brand.</para><para>(5)	As noted in response to part (3) where ADSL is not available Telstra advises businesses of alternative broadband services.</para><para>	Telstra has advised it is committed to an ongoing program of improving the availability of ADSL services. In August 2004, Telstra announced that it will be spending $28 million to extend ADSL services to an extra 250,000 lines by upgrading and replacing RIMs and other pair gain systems, mainly in metropolitan areas. In the electoral division of Brand, this has resulted in major network enhancement projects in Rockingham, Medina and Mandurah. Further upgrades are proposed for Medina, Mandurah and Coogee.</para><para>	There are also a number of alternative broadband providers that offer competitive services to customers in the electoral division of Brand. These include WestNet and EFTel which offer wireless services across a large part of Perth's metropolitan area, e-wire which offers services over its HFC network in Madora, Secret Harbour and Baldivis, and several one-way and two-way satellite providers.</para><para>(6)	As noted in the response to part (1), broadband services are already available throughout the electoral division of Brand.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet: Australian Workplace Agreements</title><page.no>169</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 194)</subtitle><id.no>194</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>169</page.no><name role="metadata">Bevis, Arch, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Bevis</name><name.id>ET4</name.id><electorate>Brisbane</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Prime Minister, in writing, on 29 November 2004:</para></talk.start><quote><para>How many employees of the Minister's department (a) had their conditions of employment set by an AWA at (i) 30 June 2001, (ii) 30 June 2002, (iii) 30 June 2003, and (iv) 30 June 2004, and (b) currently have their conditions of employment set by an AWA.</para></quote></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>169</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Howard</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The answer to the honourable member's question is as follows:</para></talk.start><para>(a)	(i)	123;</para><para>	(ii)	116;</para><para>	(iii)	141; and</para><para>	(iv)	151.</para><para>(b)	135 as at 29 November 2004.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Communications, Information Technology and the Arts: Australian Workplace Agreements</title><page.no>169</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 209)</subtitle><id.no>209</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>169</page.no><name role="metadata">Bevis, Arch, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Bevis</name><name.id>ET4</name.id><electorate>Brisbane</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister representing the Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts, in writing, on 29 November 2004:</para></talk.start><quote><para>How many employees of the Minister's department (a) had their conditions of employment set by an AWA at (i) 30 June 2001, (ii) 30 June 2002, (iii) 30 June 2003, and (iv) 30 June 2004, and (b) currently have their conditions of employment set by an AWA.</para></quote></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>170</page.no><name role="metadata">McGauran, Peter, MP</name><name role="display">Mr McGauran</name><name.id>XH4</name.id><electorate>Gippsland</electorate><party>NATS</party><role>Minister for Citizenship and Multicultural Affairs</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts has provided the following answer to the honourable member's question: </para></talk.start><quote><para>(a) and (b) The number of Departmental employees who had conditions of employment set by an AWA at various dates, is answered below:</para></quote><para>(i)	as at 30 June 2001, 153 employees</para><para>(ii)	as at 30 June 2002, 70 employees</para><para>(iii)	as at 30 June 2003, 85 employees</para><para>(iv)	as at 30 June 2004, 113 employees</para><quote><para>111 employees currently have their conditions of employment set by an AWA.</para></quote></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet: Legal Services</title><page.no>170</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 262)</subtitle><id.no>262</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>170</page.no><name role="metadata">Roxon, Nicola, MP</name><name role="display">Ms Roxon</name><name.id>83K</name.id><electorate>Gellibrand</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Prime Minister, in writing, on 2 December 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	What sum did the Minister's department spend during 2003-2004 on outsourced (a) barristers, and (b) solicitors (including private firms, the Australian Government Solicitor and any others)?</para><para>(2)	What sum did the Minister's department spend on internal legal services?</para><para>(3)	What is the projected expenditure on legal services for 2004-2005 for the Minister's department?</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>170</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Howard</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—I am advised by my department that the answer to the honourable member's question is as follows:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	(a)	Nil</para><para>(b)	$461,792</para><para>(2)	Nil, as staff of my department are involved in the identification of legal issues warranting external legal advice, but are not involved in the provision of direct legal services.</para><para>(3)	My department has an identified budget allocation for the procurement of professional services in total. This allocation does not differentiate between legal and other professional service fees. Accordingly, it is not possible to provide a figure for projected expenditure on legal services for 2004-2005.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Howard Government: Cabinet Documents</title><page.no>170</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 281)</subtitle><id.no>281</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>170</page.no><name role="metadata">Melham, Daryl, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Melham</name><name.id>4T4</name.id><electorate>Banks</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Prime Minister, in writing, on 2 December 2004:</para></talk.start><quote><para>In respect of each occasion persons have been granted access to Cabinet documents of the Howard Government under the Special Access provisions of the Archives Act 1983 (subsection 56(2) of the Act and Archives Regulation 9), (a) who was granted access, (b) when was access granted, and (c) what was the reason for granting access.</para></quote></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>170</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Howard</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The answer to the honourable member's question is as follows:</para></talk.start><quote><para>I am advised that no persons have been granted special access to Cabinet documents of the Howard Government under subsection 56(2) of the Archives Act 1983 and regulation 9 of the Archives Regulations.</para></quote></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Education: Podiatry and Osteopathy Courses</title><page.no>170</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 320)</subtitle><id.no>320</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>170</page.no><name role="metadata">Murphy, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Murphy</name><name.id>83D</name.id><electorate>Lowe</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister for Education, Science and Training, in writing, on 6 December 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Has he read the article titled `Courses dropped - tell the students' in The Daily Telegraph on 30 November 2004 which reported that the University of Western Sydney (UWS) recently axed both the Podiatry and Osteopathy courses for 2005 and 2006 and that the Director of the Australian Academy of Osteopaths claimed that by terminating the course the UWS seriously undermined the future of the profession in NSW. </para><para>(2)	Has he read the article titled `Union rails at closure of courses' in The Australian on 1 December 2004 which reported that staff, students and the professions' national peak bodies were not consulted.</para><para>(3)	Can he confirm that</para><para>(a)	the UWS announced the decision to close the courses on 18 November 2004,</para><para>(b)	staff and students were not consulted or properly notified of the decision,</para><para>(c)	students received their notification of acceptance for these courses from the University Application Centre three weeks before the decision, and</para><para>(d)	many students have found it is now too late to apply for other university courses; if not, why not.</para><para>(4)	Can he say what impact these course closures will have on the osteopathic and podiatric professions and the broader community.</para><para>(5)	Will he ensure students adversely affected by these course closures are allowed to enrol in other university courses in 2005; if so, what are the details; if not, why not.</para><para>(6)	Will he have the UWS decision to close these courses and the manner and timing of the closures investigated; if so, what are the details; if not, why not.</para><para>(7)	Will he ensure university courses in osteopathy and podiatry are available in New South Wales as soon as possible; if so, what are the details; if not, why not.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>171</page.no><name role="metadata">Nelson, Dr Brendan, MP</name><name role="display">Dr Nelson</name><name.id>RW5</name.id><electorate>Bradfield</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Minister for Education, Science and Training</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The answer to the honourable member's question is as follows:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	(2) and (3) I am aware of the media reports on these issues. The University did not inform me of its decision to suspend the 2005 intake into these courses prior to the announcements reported in the press. I cannot, therefore, confirm that it announced its decision on 18 November 2004 or if it consulted or notified its staff or students of the decision. I am, however, concerned about this matter and the way in which the University appears to have informed applicants. I wrote to the vice-chancellor, Professor Janice Reid, on 8 December 2004 expressing my concerns. I have also decided to include a clause in Funding Agreements from next year that will require all universities to negotiate with my Department before closing specialist courses such as these.</para><para>	The University has a notice on its website informing students that they can change their preferences with UAC at no charge if they wish to undertake an alternative course at UWS. Students had until 6 January 2005 to change their preferences to other UWS courses.</para><para>(4)	The University has said that it was not closing the courses but suspending the 2005 and 2006 intakes in order to undertake a course review. The suspension of these courses for those two years, however, may have an impact on the osteopathic and podiatric professions and the Australian Government is concerned about the possible outcomes of this move. I also note that representatives from the professions have expressed their concerns regarding the impact the suspensions will have on the future needs of the community.</para><para>(5)	Enrolment procedures are a matter for the University and the Universities Admission Centre (UAC). UWS informed students on its web site that they could change their preferences with the UAC at no charge if they wished to undertake any of the alternative courses suggested by UWS.</para><para>(6)	My Department will be monitoring this situation and will discuss this issue with the University in the next round of Funding Agreement negotiations. </para><para>(7)	My Department is developing a set of strategic principles for higher education priorities that will guide a national strategic approach to higher education provision across universities and help ensure the protection of national priorities. The principles will help inform the Government in how disciplines designated as national priority areas may be supported.</para></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet: Domestic and Overseas Travel</title><page.no>172</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 326)</subtitle><id.no>326</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>172</page.no><name role="metadata">Quick, Harry, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Quick</name><name.id>AV5</name.id><electorate>Franklin</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Prime Minister, in writing, on 6 December 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	For the year 2003-2004, what sum was spent by the Minister's department on (a) domestic, and (b) overseas air travel.</para><para>(2)	For the year 2003-2004, what proportion of domestic air travel by employees of the Minister's department was provided by (a) Qantas, (b) Regional Express, and (c) Virgin Blue.</para><para>(3)	For the year 2003-2004, what was the actual expenditure by the Minister's department on domestic air travel provided by (a) Qantas, (b) Regional Express, and (c) Virgin Blue.</para><para>(4)	For the year 2003-2004, what sum was spent by the Minister's department on business class travel on (a) domestic routes, and (b) overseas routes.</para><para>(5)	For the year 2003-2004, what sum was spent by the Minister's department on economy class travel on (a) domestic routes, and (b) overseas routes.</para><para>(6)	For the year 2003-2004, what proportion of the expenditure on air travel by the Minister's department was on the domestic routes (a) Sydney to Canberra, (b) Melbourne to Canberra, (c) Sydney to Melbourne, (d) Sydney to Brisbane, (e) Melbourne to Hobart or Launceston, and (f) Sydney to Perth.</para><para>(7)	For the year 2003-2004, how many employees of the Minister's department had membership of the (a) Qantas Chairman's Lounge, (b) Qantas Club, (c) Regional Express Membership Lounge, and (d) Virgin Blue's Blue Room paid for by the department.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>172</page.no><name role="metadata">Howard, John, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Howard</name><name.id>ZD4</name.id><electorate>Bennelong</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Prime Minister</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The answer to the honourable member's question is as follows:</para></talk.start><quote><para>I am advised by my department that; 
