ossibility of Her Majesty The Queen's attendance at the 2006 Commonwealth Games. I am further advised that Her Majesty has not yet made final decisions about her travel plans in 2006.</para></quote></answer></subdebate.1><subdebate.1><subdebateinfo><title>Health: MRI Services</title><page.no>174</page.no><subtitle>(Question No. 396)</subtitle><id.no>396</id.no></subdebateinfo><question><talk.start><talker><page.no>174</page.no><name role="metadata">Bird, Sharon, MP</name><name role="display">Ms Bird</name><name.id>DZP</name.id><electorate>Cunningham</electorate><party>ALP</party><in.gov>0</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para> asked the Minister for Health and Ageing, in writing, on 9 December 2004:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	Is he aware of the recent decision of the NSW Government to fund inpatient MRI services at Wollongong Hospital.</para><para>(2)	Is he aware that for the MRI machine at Wollongong Hospital to be financially viable it is necessary for it to conduct outpatient services.</para><para>(3)	Does he intend to adjust the criteria for future eligibility for Medicare Benefits Scheme (MBS) funding; if so, will the new criteria direct priority for MBS funding away from hospitals with a high private patient workload and give priority to public hospitals; and if they will not, why not.</para></question><answer><talk.start><talker><page.no>174</page.no><name role="metadata">Abbott, Tony, MP</name><name role="display">Mr Abbott</name><name.id>EZ5</name.id><electorate>Warringah</electorate><party>LP</party><role>Minister for Health and Ageing</role><in.gov>1</in.gov><first.speech>0</first.speech></talker><para>—The answer to the honourable member's question is as follows:</para></talk.start><para>(1)	I am aware of the recent decision of the NSW Government to fund inpatient Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI) services at Wollongong Hospital. I am pleased to see the New South Wales State Government meeting its responsibility to provide MRI services to public hospital in-patients.</para><para>(2)	The Australian Government does not grant Medicare Benefits Schedule (MBS) eligibility to MRI units within public hospitals to ensure their financial viability. State and Territory Governments are assisted in providing funding towards MRI services in their public hospitals by grants for hospital care provided to them by the Australian Government under the 2003-08 Australian Health Care Agreements.</para><para>(3)	The criteria for eligibility for MBS funding for MRI services was developed by an expert committee specifically formed for the current expansion of MBS eligibility.</para><para>	In general, the Australian Government's role in relation to hospitals is to support access to private rather than public in-patient services. The Australian Government already provides funding to State and Territory Governments for public hospitals and public patients under the Australian Health Care Agreements.</para></answer></subdebate.1></debate></answers.to.questions></hansard>
